<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Brazil-Hijacking 4thLd-Writethru a0897 09-29 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Hijacking, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0897,0776</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hijacking Ends With One Dead, Four Wounded</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with official saying hijacker
wanted to crash airliner into government building; hijacker in
critical condition; no Americans aboard. Pickup 7th graf pvs `A
small...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto RIO1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police shot and captured an armed
hijacker who wanted to crash a Boeing 737 with more than 100 people
aboard into a government building in the Brazilian capital
Thursday, officials said.
   The airliner hijacking left one person dead and four wounded in
the central Brazil city of Goiania, 850 miles northwest of Rio de
Janeiro and 150 miles northwest of Brasilia, the capital.
   The gunman was shot as he left the Boeing 737 and tried to board
a small getaway plane with a hostage after the rest of the
passengers and crew of VASP Flight 375 were released unharmed,
officials said.
   Authorities said the hijacker shot and killed the airliner's
co-pilot and wounded three other crew members. They described the
hijacker as mentally disturbed.
   Federal Police Chief Romeu Tuma told reporters in Goiania that
the hijacker received several bullet wounds throughout his body and
was in critical condition.
   Tuma identified the hijacker as Raimundo Conceicao, 28. Airport
officials said no Americans were aboard.
   The police chief said Conceicao told the control tower at
Goiania's Santa Genoveva airport that he wanted to ``slam the
Boeing 737 into a ministry building in Brasilia'' but later agreed
to take a smaller plane.
   Holding a .38-caliber revolver and taking the Boeing's pilot
with him, the hijacker descended from the jet parked on the runway
at the airport.
   A small Brazilian-made Bandeirantes plane was to take him and
the pilot to Brasilia, said air force spokesman Col. Eden
Avolinsque.
   The hijacker had demanded to talk to President Jose Sarney about
the country's economic policies, which he thought were wrong, said
Goiania police spokesman Morton Luiz.
   ``Police shot at him as he left the plane and he turned around
and shot the Boeing pilot, whom he had taken as his only hostage,''
Avolinsque told The Associated Press in Brasilia. ``He ran off into
the bushes, and police following close behind shot ... him.''
   Pilot Fernando Murillo Silva was shot in the leg, Avolinsque
said.
   ``We had orders from the president not to negotiate with the
hijacker and not to refuel the plane,'' Avolinsque said.
   Hundreds of heavily armed federal and state police and uniformed
army troops had surrounded the jet, isolated at the end of a
runway. VASP, a domestic carrier, is a Portuguese acronym for
Viacao Aerea Sao Paulo.
   VASP spokeswoman Mona Cury said Flight 375 was on its daily run
from the Amazon jungle city of Porto Velho to Rio on the southeast
Atlantic coast when it was hijacked.
   The hijacker ordered the airliner be flown to Brasilia but the
government refused to let it land, said Luiz. After nearly running
out of fuel, the jet landed in Goiania,
   ``He told the control tower he was against the economic policies
of President Jose Sarney and insisted on going to Brasilia. He
didn't make any other demands,'' Luiz said by telephone from
Goiania.
   Earlier, VASP and the Rio airport authority had reported a
passenger also was killed, but later denied the information.
   Tuma flew from Brasilia to Goiania to direct negotiations with
the hijacker. He said the man ``showed signs of mental
disturbance.''
   Luis Carlos Ferrini, a VASP employee at the Goiania airport,
said soldiers were taken to an identical plane to study it for a
possible invasion.
   Live TV reports from Goiania showed soldiers with rifles
creeping up to the plane and then running away.
   Avolinsque said the hijacker boarded the plane during a
refueling stop in Belo Horizonte, 290 miles north of Rio.
   ``About 20 minutes after takeoff, he got up and walked toward
the cockpit. A steward said, `That's not the toilet,' and the man
turned and shot him, injuring him in the head,'' Avolinsque said at
a news conference in the air force ministry.
   Avolinsque said the hijacker entered the cockpit, shot co-pilot
Salvador Evangelista in the head and a flight engineer in the leg
and ordered the pilot to fly to Brasilia.
   VASP said the plane carried 98 passengers and seven crew members.
   When the plane landed in Goiania in the early afternoon, the
hijacker permitted the injured crew members and another steward to
be taken from the plane.
   Evangelista later died, Luiz and air control officials said.
</TEXT>
