<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bradley-Trucks     09-29 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bradley-Trucks,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bradley Unveils Plan to Cut Truck Traffic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Tom Bradley on Wednesday proposed a
plan intended to cut the number of trucks traveling on highways
leading into the nation's second-largest city during peak traffic
hours.
   Bradley's plan, which will be submitted to the City Council for
approval, is intended to keep 70 percent of heavy-duty truck fleets
that normally operate during peak trafic hours off the road.
   Bradley was joined by rerpesentatives of the area's trucking
industry as he announced the plan. He said he did not blame
truckers for Los Angeles' traffic woes. But he said it was their
turn to help alleviate the traffic congestion that afflicts the Los
Angeles area.
   ``No one doubts that truck shipments are vital to our economy,''
Bradley said. ``The old saying `If you got it, a truck brought it,'
still largely applies. But there is no reason so many truck
deliveries must be made during these peak rush-hour travel times,''
Bradley said.
   The mayor's plan would allow only 30 percent of large truck
fleets to operate on city roadways from 6 a.m. to 9 a.m. and from 4
p.m. to 7 p.m.
   The 30 percent of the trucks that fleet owners decide to operate
during peak hours would have to display a city certificate that
could cost up to $60. Stiff fines would be levied if a trucker
operated without the certificate.
   Trucks weighing 29,000 pounds or more would be subject to
certification under the Bradley plan.
   The $60 certificate fee would help fund a multi-agency ``rapid
deployment force'' that Bradley said would quickly clear snarled
surface streets and freeways of broken-down trucks and cars.
   The plan includes partial exemption for owner-operators of
single trucks. They are allowed to use city roads either in the
morning or the evening rush hour. The plan will also allow for a
case-by-case exemption.
   City sanitation turcks and certain hazardous materials
collection trucks also will be exempted under the Bradley plan.
   Although the plan will only allow 30 percent of the large-fleet
trucks that currently travel during rush-hour, analysts with the
mayor's office estimate the partial exemption for owner-operators
and the case-by-case examption will result in a cut of about 50
percent.
</TEXT>
