<1ST_LINE>r a PM-35Cats     09-29 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-35 Cats,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman, 35 Cats Wear Out Welcome</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORTH BRADDOCK, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For most people, house-hunting is no
easy task. For Linda Asher and her 35 felines, it's become a
catastrophe.
   Asher thought she had found an ideal home a year ago when she
moved into a seven-room house with a big yard in North Braddock, a
Pittsburgh suburb with no law restricting pets.
   Asher said she told neighbors about the cats before she bought
the house and was told they would not be a problem.
   ``Maybe they really didn't believe me when I said I had 35
cats,'' she said.
   In July, District Justice Betty Lloyd found Asher guilty of
harassment after neighbors claimed the cats damaged their lawn
furniture and left paw prints on their cars. Asher has appealed to
Common Pleas Court.
   Asher concedes the cats wandered outside her yard despite a new
$3,800 fence that surrounds the home and is topped with an overhang
that slants inward.
   Neighbors have pressed for passage of a local pet ordinance, and
Council President Wayne Holt said the town's solicitor is drawing
up a measure.
   Frustrated over continuing problems, Asher, 47, an employment
training and placement specialist for the state, has put her house
up for sale.
   ``I've made a lot of sacrifices to keep my little family
together,'' said Asher, who also was evicted from an apartment in
Braddock because of the cats.
</TEXT>
