<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Czechoslovakia-Activist     09-29 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Czechoslovakia-Activist,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Frees Opposition Activist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court in Czechoslovakia has
freed an activist who spent four months in prison for distributing
leaflets critical of the government, an emigre source said.
   Jaroslav Popelka began a hunger strike on Sept. 2, the day he
was convicted of disturbing the public peace, and was ill when the
appellate court in Brno ordered him freed on Tuesday, the source
said.
   Popelka, 32, had been sentenced to eight months in jail and
already had spent 21 weeks behind bars since his arrest, said the
source, speaking on condition of anonymity. The appeals court on
Tuesday also reduced the charge against him to infringing on public
order.
   Popelka was arrested for passing out leaflets calling for
``genuine perestroika.'' Perestroika, or restructuring, is Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's term for his economic and political
reforms.
   Two human rights activists were arrested for unfurling a banner
that said ``Freedom for the political prisoner Jaroslav Popelka''
prior to the appeals court proceedings, the emigre said. They were
later released.
</TEXT>
