<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 0410EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shuttle-MannedFlight     09-29 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle-Manned Flight,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summary Of U.S. Manned Spaceflight Programs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of U.S. manned
space flights.
   Mercury (One-man capsules) _ Six flights, six astronauts, from
May 5, 1961, to May 15-16, 1963. The shortest flight was the first,
Alan B. Shepard, 15 minutes, 22 seconds; the longest was the last,
Gordon Cooper, 22 orbits in 34 hours, 19 minutes.
   Gemini (Two-man capsules) _ Ten flights, 20 astronauts, from
March 23, 1965, to Nov. 11-15, 1966. The longest flight was by
Gemini 7, 14 days.
   Apollo (Three-man capsules) _ Eleven flights, 33 astronauts;
from Oct. 11-22, 1968, to Dec. 7-19, 1972. Six landed on the moon,
three circled; the longest was Apollo 17, 301 hours, 51 minutes.
   Skylab (Apollo capsule used to ferry three men each to a space
station); Three flights, 9 astronauts; from May 25-June 22, 1973,
to Nov. 16, 1973-Feb. 8, 1974. Longest stay was 84 days, 1 hour, 15
minutes.
   Apollo-Soyuz (Joint U.S.-Soviet mission) One flight, three
astronauts, two cosmonauts, July 15-24, 1975.
   Space Shuttle (Reusable winged spacecraft) _ 24 successful
flights, with 91 astronauts, the first on April 12-14, 1981. Flight
25, the Challenger, exploded 73 seconds after liftoff, Jan. 28,
1986, with seven crew members, four of whom had flown before.
   Total Number U.S. flights, including Challenger: 56. Number of
crew members: 203.
</TEXT>
