<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JudgeCensured     09-29 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Judge Censured,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Supreme Court Censures Judge For Remarks To Woman Later
Slain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state's highest court censured a district
court judge Wednesday for ``discourtesy, rudeness and sarcasm'' to
a woman involved in a domestic dispute case who later was slain by
her husband.
   The state Supreme Judicial court recommended private censure for
Somerville District Court Judge Paul A. Heffernan for his courtroom
treatment of Pamela Nigro Dunn, who was murdered by her husband,
Paul, in August 1986.
   Private censure involves no fine, penalty or loss of judicial
power.
   The case stemmed from charges by Mrs. Dunn's family that
Heffernan humiliated and belittled her in court hearings.
   The high court dismissed allegations of a pattern of such
conduct by Heffernan, noting that he granted Mrs. Dunn's request
for court protection from her husband. It said no connection
existed between Heffernan's courtroom demeanor and her murder.
   Heffernan, 55, of Boston, did not return phone calls seeking
comment. His attorney, Thomas Dwyer Jr. said the judge accepts the
SJC ruling.
   Carole Nigro, Mrs. Dunn's mother, called the ruling too lenient.
``I'm not saying he was the cause of her murder, but just the way
he handles women in court is wrong.''
   A central incident in the case stemmed from a March 14, 1986,
hearing before Heffernan in which Mrs. Dunn, who had been beaten by
her husband, sought permission to return to retrieve her clothes
from her husband's house.
   At that hearing, Heffernan interrupted Mrs. Dunn and said, ``I
don't think it's the role of this court to decide down to each and
every piece of underwear who owns what. As a matter of fact, I find
it a little ridiculous to be involved in it.''
   At a March 26, 1986, hearing with both husband and wife present,
Heffernan told Dunn, ``Let's get this matter resolved. O.K.? You
want to gnaw on her or she on you, fine, but let's not do it at the
taxpayers' expense.''
   Five months after that hearing, Dunn murdered his wife and
disposed of her body at a town dump. He has been convicted of
first-degree murder.
   Heffernan ``was rude and sarcastic during portions of the Dunn
proceeding. A single listening to the tape recording of those
hearings establishes those facts,'' the justices said in their
11-page ruling.
   The decision noted that Heffernan's ``loud, deep voice (and)
physically imposing manner,'' contributed to the intimidation of
Mrs. Dunn.
   The court said it was ``troubling for the future,'' that
Heffernan refused in testimony before the state Commission on
Judicial Conduct to admit his demeanor was intimidating.
   Dwyer, Heffernan's attorney, said Heffernan had voluntarily
withdrawn from domestic dispute cases and had no mmediate plans to
resume hearing them. And he said Heffernan has tried to tone down
the resonance of his voice in court.
</TEXT>
