<HEAD>Former Metzenbaum Aide Indicted For Illegal Payments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DWIGHT WOODWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former aide to Sen. Howard Metzenbaum was
indicted Wednesday on charges of accepting illegal payments from
Polish immigrants trying to become U.S. citizens and enter Ohio
State University's College of Veterinary Medicine, the FBI said.
   Ladd Anthony of Cleveland was indicted by a federal grand jury
for allegedly agreeing to accept $2,000 from Waclaw Pietrzykowsky
for helping get a friend of Pietrzykowsky's admitted to the
veterinary school, FBI Special Agent Marshall Sullivan said.
   The indictment also alleges Anthony accepted $300 for assisting
Irena Boc in gaining U.S. citizenship, Sullivan said. He said no
other Metzenbaum aide was involved in the allegations.
   Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, said Wednesday he had notified the Justice
Department 22 months ago of the allegations a constituent raised
against Anthony.
   ``The FBI informed me that they completed their investigation of
Mr. Anthony in November of 1987,'' the senator said. ``Why has it
taken the Justice Department almost a year to seek the indictment
is a question that remains to be answered.''
   On July 19, 1987, the Justice Department reported the evidence
was credible enough to go to a grand jury and Anthony was fired,
Harris said.
   A spokesman for the Washington, D.C., office of the Justice
Department was unavailable for comment Wednesday night.
   Elmer Giuliani, Anthony's Cleveland attorney, said Wednesday he
had not received a copy of the indictment. ``I have to assume my
client is innocent,'' Giuliani said.
   Anthony lives in a Cleveland suburb but Giuliani declined to
give his address and the Cleveland telephone directory has no
listing for a Ladd Anthony.
