<1ST_LINE>d a BC-Opera     09-29 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Opera,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Met Presents First Ring Cycle Opera</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This season the Metropolitan Opera will stage
all four operas in Wagner's Ring Cycle and on Wednesday, the third
night of the season, it presented the first one, ``Das Rheingold.''
   Casting was carefully done. As the Met chose singers who knew
the Handel style for its second-night ``Guilio Cesare,'' the
singers in ``Das Rheingold'' knew the Wagner style.
   Two were making very fine debuts. Hanna Schwarz of Hamburg,
Germany, sang Fricka, wife of Wotan, leader of the gods. The
mezzo-soprano, who has sung at Bayreuth since 1975, has the needed
volume and has her vibrato under control. Through much of the opera
she is concerned about her sister Freia and her voice always
sounded sympathetic, with a sweet overtone.
   Wotan, sung by Hans Sotin, has a dark voice that sounds full of
compassion, even when he's laying down the law. Seldom does one
hear this couple sound so understanding and kind.
   Mezzo-soprano Birgitta Svenden of Vuollerim, Sweden, made her
debut as Erda, who comes out of a hole in the ground near the end
of the opera to tell Wotan to surrender the ring. Her voice was
very clear and pleasing.
   Miss Svenden has sung at Bayreuth for four seasons. She will
sing Erda with the Seattle Opera in 1989 and for her debut at
Covent Garden in 1990. She has recorded Erda in ``Rheingold'' and
``Siegfried'' with James Levine and the Met Orchestra.
   Clarity ruled the evening. Levine conducted so that singers
could be heard. The Otto Schenk production, with sets and
projections by Gunther Schneider-Siemssen, new last October, is
lighted by Gil Wechsler so that singers can be seen. Almost
everybody sang clearly.
   Franz Mazura was outstanding as Alberich, who steals the gold
from the Rhine River and later puts a curse on anybody who wears
the ring he made from it. Siegfried Jerusalem as Loge had a
much-textured voice, rich but with a con man's inflections. Horst
Hiestermann's Mime was effective, though less squeaky than the
usual interpretation.
   John Macurdy and Matti Salminen were expansive vocally, as the
giants. Kaaren Erickson, Diane Kesling and Meredith Parsons blended
well as the Rhinemaidens.
</TEXT>
