<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 0451EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MedicalWaste     09-29 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Medical Waste,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Moving On Law To Tighten Controls On Medical Waste</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is preparing to force the
Environmental Protection Agency to combat a mounting wave of
infectious medical waste washing up on the nation's shores.
   The latest step in the process came Wednesday when the House
Energy and Commerce Committee gave voice-vote approval to
legislation that would require creation-to-disposal controls on
things such as used syringes.
   The action all but guaranteed that before adjourning next month
Congress will respond to the tides of used syringes and
AIDS-contaminated materials that appeared this summer in Lake Erie
and at beaches in New York and New Jersey.
   The bill, which backers say will be passed next week by the full
House, is similar to legislation approved in August by the Senate.
Staffers on both sides of the Capitol say they expect no problems
resolving differences between the two plans.
   ``The illegal disposal of medical waste is spreading like an
epidemic,'' said Rep. Thomas Luken, D-Ohio, principal sponsor of
the House bill. ``Much of this waste is infectious. It can
literally kill people. All of it is repulsive and frightening.''
   Luken said that in Youngstown, Ohio, a physician put used
syringes in a trash bin. ``Kids found the needles and played
`doctor' with them, giving each other injections that could have
proved fatal.''
   The legislation would require EPA to set up a system to track
infectious medical waste generated in New Jersey, Connecticut and
the eight states bordering the Great Lakes.
   However, the regional demonstration program could become
national in scope because any state would be allowed to opt for
coverage under rules that would require a paper trail from waste
generation to disposal.
   ``Tracking helps stop midnight dumping,'' Luken said.
``Hospitals and clinics will now know where their medical waste is
going, and so will EPA.''
   The bill proposes stiff penalties: a civil fine of up to $25,000
for each day of violation and a maximum criminal penalty of 15
years in prison and a daily violation fine of up to $50,000.
   Committee members said Congress is being forced to act because
EPA had failed to issue regulations _ first proposed 10 years ago
but then quickly dropped _ ensuring proper disposal of waste
created in hospitals, laboratories and clinics.
   ``This is not just a question of a bloody syringe washing up on
a beach on the East Coast,'' said Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore. ``The
medical waste system in this country is broken and inefficient and
is regurgitating what it can't keep down.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
