<DOCNO> AP880929-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 0453EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-InsiderTrading-Defense     09-29 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Insider Trading-Defense,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consultant Said To Have Met With Navy Official</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New Jersey consultant charged with insider
trading involving a Navy contract discussed the project with a Navy
assistant secretary who has been named as a target in the
government's defense procurement probe, according to the
consultant's attorney.
   Charles A. Mills of Beachwood, N.J., who had served as a
consultant to the Navy in a project to develop a new generation of
blimps, agreed Wednesday to pay $9,315 to settle a civil complaint
filed by the Securities and Exchange Commission in U.S. District
Court.
   The SEC said it was continuing its investigation, and its
complaint cited a meeting between Mills and ``a certain then
assistant secretary of the Navy,'' whom it did not identify further.
   However, sources speaking on condition of anonymity indicated it
was Melvyn Paisley, who was assistant secretary of the Navy for
research, engineering and systems, and has since been named as a
target of a Justice Department probe into Pentagon purchasing
practices.
   Lawrence Barcella, Paisley's attorney, said his client has not
been subpoenaed or otherwise notified by the SEC that he is the
subject of an investigation. Moreover, he said the SEC complaint
does not imply that the unidentified assistant secretary did
anything improper.
   According to the SEC complaint, Mills, in his role as a
consultant from February to May 1987, had access to confidential
information about competing bids for a contract worth $168.9
million to develop a prototype of a radar-surveillance blimp to
help protect Navy fleets.
   Through meetings with Naval officials, including one on March
13, 1987 attended by the unidentified assistant secretary, Mills
learned the officials favored a bid from a joint venture of
Westinghouse Electric Co. and Airship Industries Ltd. of
Cardington, England, the SEC alleged.
   John D. Schupper, Mills' attorney, said his client told him
Wednesday that he met once with Paisley and other officials for
five or 10 minutes, but was not certain of the date.
   The Navy announced the contract award June 5. A day earlier,
according to the SEC, Mills purchased receipts on the
over-the-counter market in the United States for the purchase of
Airship Industries stock, which is traded in London and Sydney,
Australia.
   Mills sold the receipts June 8 and 9, earning a profit of
$4,658, the agency said. Without admitting or denying the charges,
Mills agreed to return the profits and pay an equal amount as a
penalty.
   The SEC also said ``certain assistant secretaries of the Navy''
were briefed on the bid award June 3 and 4. By that time, Paisley,
who was appointed assistant secretary in 1981, was out of
government, according to Barcella.
   The blimp contract had a potential value of $3 billion if the
Navy had decided to build a fleet of airships. However, the program
was scrapped following agreement between the Reagan administration
and Congress in late 1987 on a plan to reduce the federal budget
deficit.
   Schupper said Mills had not believed he did anything wrong and
cooperated fully with the SEC.
   ``In light of his health and his financial resources, he
believes that the settlement represents a fair resolution of
conflicting conclusions drawn from basically the same facts,''
Schupper said.
   The Justice Department is investigating whether private
consultants, many of them former Pentagon employees, paid bribes to
Defense Department officials for inside information about
contracts, chiefly within the Navy. The probe became public in June
after subpoenas were issued in the case. No one has been charged
yet.
   Investigators have searched Paisley's home looking for evidence
that he took payments from defense contractors while he was at the
Pentagon. Investigators also have alleged in court papers that
while Paisley was a consultant to McDonnell Douglas Corp., he
improperly provided the company with secret Pentagon documents
about its competitors.
   Through his attorney, Paisley has said the government has
provided no evidence to support such allegations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
