<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 0454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Budget     09-29 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress May Complete Its Spending Bills On Time _ For a Change</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress and the White House may be about to
accomplish something they've not done since Harry Truman was
president _ enact all federal spending bills before the start of
the fiscal year.
   Although it's not likely to spark a giddy citizenry into
launching fireworks, approval by Saturday of all 13 spending bills
would be a political coup for both parties.
   It's already inspired people on both ends of Pennsylvania Avenue
to begin publicly patting themselves on the back.
   ``We're showing that we can govern,'' Rep. Tony Coelho,
D-Calif., the No. 3 House Democratic leader, said Wednesday.
   ``The warning has been taken to heart,'' said President Reagan.
He was referring to a promise he made in January that if the
spending measures were wrapped into a single piece of legislation,
he would veto it.
   As the start of the new fiscal year approaches, lawmakers and
the administration are working out disputes that in ordinary years
could take weeks or months to resolve.
   Thus, Reagan, who signed his first appropriations bill for the
new year on July 19, signed the sixth into law Wednesday, a measure
appropriating $8.8 billion for military construction.
   In addition, a $15 billion spending measure for the Commerce,
Justice and State departments and a $10.8 billion transportation
bill were on his desk. Legislative action on the five remaining
appropriations measures was scheduled for today and Friday.
   This is no ordinary year. It's an election year, and Republicans
and Democrats want to avoid any blame for a replay of last year's
budget embarrassment.
   ``In an election year, neither side wanted to face
responsibility for a massive CR,'' said Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska,
using the initials for ``continuing resolution'' _ legislative
lingo for a giant spending bill.
   ``This helps incumbents, period,'' said Coelho. ``The more you
make the process work, the more you help incumbents.''
   Last December, after a year of inconclusive squabbling between
Congress and the White House, Reagan signed a 1,400-page, $600
billion behemoth that contained all the money federal agencies
needed to function this year. Within hours of receiving it, the
president signed it. The alternative was shutting down the
government.
   In January, an angry Reagan used his nationally televised State
of the Union address to promise to veto any similar bill this year.
Congressional leaders called on the president to work with them to
smooth out any disputes that might arise, and pledged to avoid a
catchall measure for 1989.
   The most serious stumbling block this year had been defense
spending.
   But on Wednesday, Congress and the White House resolved a
long-running dispute over Star Wars and arms control restrictions
with both the House and Senate approving a Pentagon authorization
bill. That made congressional action possible by Friday on a
separate $300 billion Pentagon spending measure.
   The quicker-than-usual action this year is due in part to last
fall's budget summit agreement between Reagan and congressional
leaders. In that pact, both sides agreed to broad spending totals
for 1989, leaving only less-sweeping issues to be worked out.
   Coelho and other Democrats are crediting their own leadership
for the rapid movement of the spending bills.
   ``We announced at the beginning of the year that we'd do it,''
Coelho said.
   Even if all 13 bills are not enacted by 12:01 a.m. Saturday,
there would be little immediate impact. Federal workers deemed
essential _ including the military _ would be permitted to work
over the weekend. Government agencies would not have to shut down
unless spending legislation was not in place by Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
