<DOCNO> AP880929-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 0508EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Shuttle-Schools     09-29 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle-Schools,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mixed Bag of School Events For Shuttle Launch</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Eighty lucky ninth-graders in Florida got front-row seats for
today's launch of Discovery, but some pupils weren't allowed to
watch the live television coverage to spare them possible trauma in
the event something went wrong.
   In Concord, N.H., the home of Challenger teacher-astronaut
Christa McAuliffe, nothing special was planned. And plans for a
nationwide educational project built around America's return to
manned spaceflight fell through.
   Millions of schoolchildren were watching when the last shuttle
lifted off on Jan. 28, 1986, because of McAuliffe, who was to give
lessons from space.
   When Challenger blew up 73 seconds after launch, killing the
seven astronauts aboard, students gathered in a festive assembly at
McAuliffe's Concord High School were watching on live television.
   This time, no organized school events were scheduled in Concord.
   ``Perhaps our relationship to Christa will mean more classrooms
will watch it, but I don't think it's going to be a big deal,''
schools Superintendent Mark Beauvais said Wednesday. ``We certainly
aren't going to push it to make it one.''
   Concord High banned reporters from the school's buildings and
grounds.
   At Kimball Elementary School, where McAuliffe's son, Scott, is
in the sixth grade and daughter, Caroline, is in the third,
Principal Clint Cogswell said he expected some classes would watch
the launch _ but not Scott's or Caroline's.
   The Discovery mission excited teachers and students in Willmar,
Minn., where crew member George ``Pinky'' Nelson grew up.
   ``It's kind of a local hero thing,'' said Jim Christenson,
director of elementary education in the city of 16,000. ``With the
launch, all the TV coverage and the balloons, and some kids are
making colored prints of the launch site which will be on exhibit
... they are getting excited.''
   Tumbleweed Elementary School in Palmdale, Calif., planned to
celebrate the launch by firing model rockets into space, science
teacher Gary Whiddison said. The students, some with parents who
worked on the shuttle, have been studying rocket designs.
   The desert community of Palmdale is south of Edwards Air Force
Base, where the shuttle is to land.
   Geraldine Haracz, a fourth-grade teacher at Edwards Elementary
School in Chicago, wore a space suit and explained mission control
to students watching the Challenger launch. She planned the same
for today.
   ``I think we have helped them understand that this was one
moment of tragedy that will help us go on'' and learn more about
space, said Miss Haracz.
   In Greenwich, Conn., Julian Curtiss School Principal Linda
Hartzer said she planned to videotape the launch and show it to her
elementary school pupils if it succeeds.
   ``Obviously, if it was a deadly experience, we would handle it a
different way,'' she said. Hartzer said a school team of
psychologists, educators, counselors and social workers would
decide what to do in that case.
   The Challenger Center, which was formed by the Challenger
astronauts' families to promote space education, had hoped to
distribute free ``Countdown 5-4-3-2-1'' kits to the nation's 65,000
elementary schools before Discovery's launch, said spokesman
Richard Hutto. But the kits won't be ready to be mailed until late
next week, said Liz Thomas, an administrative assistant for the
Challenger Center's education department in Washington.
   However, all is not lost, Hutto said. ``There were some specific
things about this launch, but the kits are designed to be
generic,'' he said. ``It's written in such a way it could be used
on future flights.''
   For today's flight, 80 students from Lincoln Park Academy in
Fort Pierce, Fla., had a clear view of the launch from the parking
lot of a McDonald's restaurant in Titusville three miles from the
pad.
   Restaurant manager Mike Reed said the students got exclusive
rights to the parking lot, beating out news organizations, because
they asked first.
</TEXT>
