<HEAD>US Troubled by Use of Plastic Bullets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is disturbed by Israel's use
of plastic bullets against Palestinian demonstrators, contending
the policy is leading to rising casualties in the occupied
territories.
   According to published reports, at least three Palestinians have
been killed and 70 wounded since the Israeli Army began using
plastic bullets a month ago. The bullets have been described by
their defenders as non-lethal.
   ``We believe that measures must be taken to reduce rather than
to increase casualties among Palestinian demonstrators,'' State
Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said on Wednesday.
   ``Thus we are disturbed by the rising casualties of Palestinians
in recent clashes with the Israeli military. We can see no
justification for a policy admittedly designed to cause an increase
in casualties.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>More Hurricane Aid Being Sent to Jamaica</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agency for International Development is
providing an additional $20 million in relief aid to Jamaica to
help the nation recover from battering it took from Hurricane
Gilbert earlier this month.
   AID said Wednesday the funds will be used in part to restore
power, water and sewage services which were damaged by the
hurricane.
   Roofing materials, medical supplies, seeds and farming tools
also will be purchased.
   On Sept. 12, Hurricane Gilbert wrecked tens of thousands of
homes and businesses on Jamaica and destroyed crops and power
lines. Shortly thereafter, AID announced it was sending relief
supplies totaling $396,000 to Jamaica.
