<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     09-29 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Shares Down in Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched up against the Japanese yen
Thursday, while share prices lost ground on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 134.35 yen, up 0.15 yen from Wednesday's
finish. It ranged mainly between 133.85 yen and 134.50 yen after
opening the day at 133.98 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 252.45-point
winner Wednesday, lost 51.88 points, or 0.17 percent, to finish at
27,700.13 points.
   A report that Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze had
left a United Nations meeting for the Soviet Union sharply
increased the dollar-buying drive, said a dealer with the Bank of
Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said investors who speculated the departure could indicate
the administration of Mikhail Gorbachev might be getting weaker
started selling the yen to buy more dollars, helping to push the
U.S. currency higher.
   The report alleging a secret meeting in the Soviet Union also
affected the stock market, said an analyst with Nomura Securities,
Japan's largest brokerage.
   ``Although the market has been doing well for the last couple of
days, such news immediately made investors cautious and affected
their trading,'' said the Nomura analyst, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   He also said profit-taking was contributing to the Nikkei's fall.
</TEXT>
