<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Quayle Bjt   09-29 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle, Bjt,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Becomes More Visible In Week Before Debate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Dan Quayle was turning to debate
preparations today after a campaign swing intended to end doubts
about how much support he had from George Bush.
   From the moment Bush gave Quayle words of praise and a
reassuring fatherly pat at a Jackson, Tenn., rally on Monday, the
process of establishing Quayle's campaign credentials was under way.
   The 41-year-old Indiana senator debates his Democratic
counterpart and Senate colleague, Lloyd Bentsen, Wednesday in
Omaha, Neb.
   Top Bush strategists stalked reporters on Quayle's campaign
plane as the Indiana senator made his first foray into Texas, the
state where Bentsen was born and Bush had made his home.
   Their message: Quayle has Bush's confidence despite
controversies over his past military service, academic record and
personal life, not to mention polls showing many voters have doubts
about his qualifications. They claimed Quayle is doing all a vice
presidential candidate could to help out the ticket.
   Rich Bond, Bush's deputy campaign manager and political
director, said that with the completion Wednesday of Quayle's Texas
swing, Quayle has campaigned in 35 states, nine of them targeted by
the campaign as important swing states.
   Quayle's role has been to campaign in safe Republican areas,
hold the party's base for November and get good local media
coverage.
   ``Remember the perspective of what a vice presidential nominee
traditionally does _ hold your base and help out target states,''
Bond said.
   In the Texas cities Quayle visited this week, he got front-page
headlines and often color photographs.
   Although there have been reports that Bush has tried to distance
himself from Quayle because of the negative publicity surrounding
him, aides said that was not a factor in Monday's joint appearance
being the ticket's first since Aug. 20.
   ``Presidential and vice presidential candidates don't spend a
lot of time together on the road,'' Bond said. ``That is no
reflection on Dan Quayle's standing with us.''
   Quayle's mission in Texas, with its 29 electoral votes, was to
raise money and go after Dukakis. Bentsen was largely ignored. In
fact, Quayle never mentioned him publicly by name.
   Quayle continued the GOP strategy of portraying Dukakis as an
unrepentant liberal, out of touch with mainstream views.
   On Tuesday, he called on Dukakis to resign his membership in the
American Civil Liberties Union. On Wednesday, he blasted Dukakis
for being on the advisory board of a group which advocated deep
defense cuts and which has among its supporters ``the extreme left
wing of the Democratic Party.'' The highly partisan crowds jeered.
</TEXT>
