<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 0437EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-29 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Shares Down in Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched up against the Japanese yen
today, and share prices closed lower on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar finished at 134.35 yen, up 0.15 yen from Wednesday's
close of 134.20 yen. After opening lower at 133.98 yen, the
currency rose and traded between 133.85 yen and 134.50 yen.
   The dollar-buying trend in Tokyo began after dealers heard that
Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze left a U.N. meeting in
New York late Wednesday for a secret session in the Soviet Union,
said a dealer with the Bank of Tokyo, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   He said investors who speculated the departure could indicate a
weakening of the administration of Mikhail Gorbachev started
selling yens to buy more dollars, helping to push the U.S. currency
higher.
   Mitsuhiko Kinugasa, an official with Daiwa Bank, also said the
news affected the currency exchange.
   ``Investors began thinking something must be happening in the
Soviet politics, which boosted dollar-buying,'' he said.
``Participants' cautiousness made the dollar-yen rate fluctuate
afterwards, though.''
   The dollar later traded mainly in the lower 134-yen level, he
said.
   Meanwhile, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues ended
trading at 27,700.13, down 51.88 points, or 0.19 percent, from the
previous day's close of 27,752.01. Following Wednesday's
252.45-point gain, the Nikkei rose another 57.07 points shortly
after the market opened but then declined.
   Investors became cautious and remained on the sidelines after
the news about Shevarnadze, a Nomura Securities analyst said.
   ``In addition, after the hectic trading for the last two days,
some investors sold high-priced issues for their profit,'' he said.
   Volume traded on the first section was estimated at 1 billion
shares with steel and shipbuilding stocks falling in value.
</TEXT>
