<HEAD>Boat Evacuating Flood Victims Capsizes, 25 Missing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JALANDHAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boat evacuating residents from a
flooded village in the northern state of Punjab capsized today, and
all 25 people on board were missing, an army spokesman said.
   The boat overturned in strong currents near the village of
Talwandi Butain, said the spokesman, who cannot be identified under
briefing rules.
   The government says at least 282 people have died in flash
floods that have hit villages in Punjab and the neighboring states
of Haryana, Himachal Pradesh and Jammu-Kashmir since Sept. 21.
   Indian newspapers put the death toll at 350.
   Hundreds of people remained marooned in villages and towns in
the central state of Punjab. The government feared the stagnant
muddy water could cause outbreaks of diarrhea and cholera.
   At least 1,500 villages in Punjab were under water. At least
70,000 people have been evacuated from the villages in boats and
helicopters, officials have said.
