<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Quake     09-29 0135</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Quake,0140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moderately Strong Earthquake Strikes Tokyo Region</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderately strong earthquake hit the Tokyo region
today, but there were no immediate reports of damage or injuries.
   The quake struck at 5:17 p.m., registering 5.1 on the open-ended
Richter scale, the Central Meteorological Agency said.
   The temblor occurred about 6 miles below southern Saitama, the
agency said.
   A National Police Agency official said no damage or casualties
had been reported.
   The Richter scale measures the magnitude of a quake at its
epicenter, according to ground motion as recorded on seismographs.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight
damage in the local area and 5 considerable damage. A 7 reading is
a ``major'' earthquake, capable of widespread heavy damage; 8 is a
``great'' quake, capable of tremendous damage.
