<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MagneticLevitation     09-29 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Magnetic Levitation,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Magnetic-Levitation Transport Should Run Along Interstates,
Researchers Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High-speed magnetic-levitation transportation
systems whose cars would appear to float on air could be installed
along interstate highway routes, cutting pollution and saving
millions of barrels of oil a year, scientists say.
   ``Much of the system is very straight and contains adequate
space for both the existing highways and for vehicle guideways,
suitably isolated for mutual safety,'' Gordon Danby, a senior
physicist at Brookhaven National Laboratory, told a congressional
panel Wednesday. ``This interstate approach overcomes the greatest
cost and availability impediment: obtaining guideway real estate.''
   ``Guideways'' are the magnetic tracks along which
magnetic-levitation cars run. The system works on the simple
principle that like magnetic poles repel each other. Cars glide
along, propelled by a traveling magnetic field.
   Danby and James R. Powell, a nuclear engineer at Brookhaven,
have agreed to head an advisory group that will study the
application of magnetic-levitation transportation to the interstate
highway system.
   Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan, D-N.Y., chairman of the Environment
subcommittee on water resources, transportation and infrastructure,
said the advisory panel is slated to complete its work by February
1989 and that he will present its findings to the next president.
   Powell testified that if a ``mag-lev'' train running along the
Long Island Expressway carried 150,000 passengers a day, it could
save 8 million barrels of oil a year, while cutting air pollution
and saving wear on family cars.
   ``If mag-lev were to be applied on a nationwide basis, its total
benefits would be hundreds of times greater than sketched for the
Long Island application,'' he said.
   Danby also predicted that while mag-lev transport will not
replace the automobile or truck, it has a definite edge over
conventional trains.
   ``The mag-lev system is much faster and more energy-efficient,
providing potential for mobility much greater than previously
known,'' he said. ``Long trips in short time can become routine.''
   But Danby warned against buying existing mag-lev systems from
the Japanese and Germans, who quickly took to the American-invented
concept and made it reality.
   ``The existing mag-lev systems are first embodiments,'' he said.
``In the future, these will appear as dated as early automobiles or
airplanes.''
   He said the advisory panel will consider ways in which a U.S.
system could be financed.
   ``Options involving partnerships between public and private
sectors appear particularly interesting,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
