<2ND_LINE>PM-Metzenbaum Aide,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Metzenbaum Aide Indicted For Illegal Payments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DWIGHT WOODWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former aide to Sen. Howard Metzenbaum has
been indicted on charges of accepting bribes from two Polish
immigrants, but the senator, who faces re-election in November,
questioned the indictment's timing.
   U.S. Attorney Patrick McLaughlin said Wednesday that Ladd
Anthony of Cleveland was indicted by a special federal grand jury
for agreeing to accept $2,000 from Waclaw Pietrzykowsky for helping
him get a friend admitted to the Ohio State University College of
Veterinary Medicine.
   The indictment also alleges Anthony accepted $300 to assist
Irena Boc obtain U.S. citizenship.
   ``Why did the Justice Department wait until six weeks before the
election (to indict)?'' asked Peter Harris, an administrative aide
to the Ohio Democrat.
   Metzenbaum, whose re-election is being challenged by Cleveland's
Republican mayor, George Voinovich, said he told the Justice
Department of the allegations against his aide almost two years ago.
   ``I asked the Justice Department to investiate Mr. Anthony 22
months ago in November of 1986, immediately after learning from a
constituent that Anthony might have acted improperly,'' Metzenbaum
said.
   ``The FBI informed me that they completed their investigation of
Mr. Anthony in November of 1987. Why has it taken the Justice
Department almost a year to seek the indictment is a question that
remains to be answered.''
   Marshall L. Sullivan, a spokesman for the Cleveland FBI office,
said the timing of the prosecution was up to the Criminal Division
of the Justice Department.
   ``The FBI expeditiously went about their investigation,''
Sullivan said. ``The U.S. Attorney's office and the Criminal
Division of the Justice Department _ it's their responsibility to
proceed when they decide.''
   A Justice Department spokesman could not be reached for comment
Wednesday night.
   Harris said he completed interviews with constituents on Nov.
20, 1986, that indicated Anthony may have accepted payments.
   ``A woman from Cleveland came in and told one of our case
workers that Anthony was one of a group of people who asked for
money. We found that two other people had similar stories,'' Harris
said.
   On July 19, 1987, the Justice Department reported the evidence
was credible enough to go to a grand jury and Anthony was fired,
Harris said.
   Elmer Giuliani, Anthony's attorney, said Wednesday he had not
received a copy of the indictment. ``I have to assume my client is
innocent,'' Giuliani said.
   Anthony is living in a Cleveland suburb but Giuliani declined to
give his address. The Cleveland telephone directory does not
contain a listing for him and he could not be reached for comment.
</TEXT>
