<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Noriega-Indictment     09-29 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Noriega-Indictment,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Motion Cites Political Motivation, But Not Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Court papers seeking to dismiss a drug indictment
against Panamanian leader Manuel Antonio Noriega did not include
references to Vice President George Bush or his presidential
campaign as prosecutors had feared.
   The 65-page motion, which characterizes the case against the
Panamanian general as a political ploy, was unsealed Wednesday
after the U.S. attorney's office found it contained none of the
possible blackmail they believed Noriega might use to bargain with
the Reagan administration.
   ``My concern was that they would use it as some sort of
political leverage, but they didn't,'' said Richard Gregorie, chief
deputy assistant U.S. attorney. ``I don't think there is anything
in there that is shocking.''
   Noriega had previously claimed he had information that could
hurt the Bush campaign.
   Instead, the motion argues that the U.S. government has no right
to prosecute Noriega as a de facto head of state with diplomatic
immunity. It also says he has been targeted for political reasons
and that pretrial publicity will make it impossible to find an
objective jury.
   ``Whatever information damaging to George Bush that may exist,
that information was not going to be raised in our motion unless it
was relevant to the case,'' said Noriega's attorney, Neal Sonnett.
   The 12-count indictment returned by a federal grand jury in
Miami in February accused Noriega of accepting $4.6 million in
bribes from Colombia's violent Medellin drug cartel. A grand jury
in Tampa indicted Noriega on three marijuana importation counts the
next day.
   The motion filed in Miami and sealed on Sept. 14 claims the
indictment was ``based upon impermissible considerations, including
political and foreign policy considerations.''
   Sonnett said one foreign policy issue was pressure by
conservatives in the Reagan administration to renegotiate the
Panama Canal Treaty, which was signed by President Carter and hands
full control of the waterway to Panama at the end of this century.
   ``There were attempts to modify aspects of the treaty,'' Sonnett
said. ``We argue that it was one of the circumstances leading up to
a decision to attempt to get Noriega out of power.''
   The document contains quotes from the news media made by Reagan
administration officials, such as Undersecretary of State Elliot
Abrams, that the defense says demonstrate the political nature of
the case.
   Abrams, for example, is quoted as saying in May that ``the
indictment drove Noriega crazy and gave us a terrific bargaining
tool.''
   The defense, calling the case against Noriega ``indictment
diplomacy,'' notes that in March the Reagan administration offered
to guarantee it would not seek his extradition if he fled to Spain
and in May offered to drop the indictments altogether if he left
Panama.
   ``There can be no doubt ... that General Noriega has been
singled out for prosecution'' for political reasons, the attorneys
said.
   The defense motion also argues that Noriega is the first head of
state ever indicted in the United States for action taken within
his own country.
   Although Turks and Caicos Islands Prime Minister Norman Saunders
was convicted in Miami in 1985 on drug trafficking charges, the
defense notes that his activities took place here. And the
attorneys say the group of islands he led is not a sovereign nation
but a British colony, making Saunders only a local elected official.
   Saunders served two years of an eight-year prison term.
</TEXT>
