<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CometMistake     09-29 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Comet Mistake,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Suggesting Tiny Comet-Like Objects Flawed by Error,
Scientist Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A clerical error marred a key calculation in a
study suggesting that unseen comet-like objects are traveling near
Earth's orbit, says a scientist who admits, ``I blew it.''
   But the objects may still exist, said Thomas Donahue of the
University of Michigan at Ann Arbor.
   Donahue was one of three authors who published the study last
December in the British journal Nature.
   They suggested the small objects, called ``cometesimals,'' may
strike Earth every 80 years, and may be responsible for many
craters on the moon.
   The cometesimals, ranging in diameter from a few yards to a few
tens of yards, may also be building blocks of ordinary comets, the
researchers wrote. But the objects may not throw off much dust,
making them hard to spot from Earth, they said.
   The work was based on what appeared to be a higher amount of
hydrogen atoms between the orbital paths of Earth and Mars than
could be attributed to known causes. Cometesimals were proposed as
a possible source.
   In today's issue of Nature, however, University of Arizona
researchers said their re-analysis of the same data from the
Voyager 2 spacecraft showed no inexplicable excess of hydrogen
atoms.
   In a telephone interview, Donahue said the mistake in the
original paper occurred because a student misread a number from a
table of data. That caused a crucial calculation to underestimate
the amount of hydrogen that a theory predicts would be found in
outer space.
   The underestimate created the gap that was explained by the
cometesimal proposal.
   ``I don't even want to blame the student. I should have
checked,'' Donahue said. ``I blew it, that's all.''
   He said estimates of the expected concentration of hydrogen in
outer space are not firm, and that revised figures still leave some
room for the existence of cometesimals. Observations by the Galileo
spacecraft, which is scheduled to be launched next year, should
reveal whether they exist, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880929-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 0715EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AbortionPill     09-29 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abortion Pill,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Pill Said Effective in Terminating Early Pregnancies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An abortion pill able to safely end early
pregnancies, much like a pill recently approved for use in France
and China, has been successfully tested by Dutch scientists.
   The latest medicine, called epostane, worked in 84 percent of
women who used it in the fifth through eighth weeks of pregnancy,
researchers reported today.
   Dr. Marinus J. Crooij and colleagues from Elisabeth Gasthuis in
Haarlem, Netherlands, gave the drug to 50 women who were planning
to have abortions. They reported their results in today's New
England Journal of Medicine.
   ``We conclude that epostane taken orally is an effective and
safe method for the non-invasive termination of undesired early
pregnancy,'' they wrote.
   The researchers speculated that using epostane with RU 486 might
be more effective than either alone.
   Tests showed RU 486 or mifepristone, which was approved earlier
this month for use in France and China, was 95 percent effective.
Neither drug is available in the United States, where anti-abortion
activists have threatened to boycott products of any drug company
that produces such a pill.
   Both drugs work by interferring with progesterone, a hormone
essential during the first weeks of pregnancy for the implantation
of a fertilized egg on the uterine wall.
   Proponents of such pills consider them a simpler, safer
alternative to traditional abortions. Opponents, including the
Roman Catholic Church, say they are just another way to kill the
unborn.
   With the new pills, there is no surgical act. No anesthesia is
needed and there is no risk of infection, sterility or of
perforating the uterus, but RU 486 research has turned up
hemorrhaging in a small percentage of users.
</TEXT>
