<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush-Targets 1stLd-Writethru a0471 09-29 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Targets, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0471,540</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Bush Campaign Says South, Rockies Are Solid; adds quote in
lead.</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to raise raise Democratic rebuttal; picks up 2nd
graf pvs, Top campaign.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reports that Michael Dukakis has scaled back
expectations in the South and West have prompted his rival's
campaign to claim the regions for George Bush. A Dukakis aide
dismissed this as ``a Republican fantasy'' and said Democrats have
actually bolstered their staffing in the South.
   Top campaign aides to Bush said the vice president has a lock on
the South and the Rocky Mountain region, leaving him free to
compete with the Democratic presidential nominee in a handful of
key states.
   Bush campaign manager Lee Atwater and political director Rich
Bond, in a telephone news conference Wednesday with Boston
reporters, said they are delighted with comments by anonymous
Dukakis campaign officials who say they have scaled back
expectations in those two regions.
   But Dukakis campaign spokesman Mark Gearan said it was ``a
Republican fantasy that we would pull out of the South.''
   ``Lee has been saying this for some time hoping it would come
true,'' he said. ``It will not. We have more people working in the
South today than this time last week.''
   Gearan said recent polls have shown Dukakis competitive with
Bush across the South.
   Dukakis aides have said privately in recent days they intend to
compete vigorously in several key states while scaling back the
campaign elsewhere.
   ``It's interesting to see a Dukakis 50-state strategy come to an
abrupt halt,'' Atwater said.
   The two Bush strategists said the vice president is banking on a
solid block of support across the South and Rocky Mountain states
and will focus his campaign on nine key states: New Jersey,
Pennsylvania, Michigan, Ohio, Illinois, Missouri, Texas, Washington
and California.
   Bond said the states Bush counts as solidly behind his campaign
account for 200 of the 270 electoral votes needed to win on Nov. 8.
Dukakis, according to Bond, can count on only 170 electoral votes.
   ``We need to win only two or three of those (nine) states while
Dukakis would have to win five to seven depending on whether
California was among that group,'' Bond said. ``So we can
concentrate on fewer states,'' Bond said.
   ``We're going to be concentrating on California, Ohio, Michigan
and states like that and we can feel that the southern and Rocky
Mountain states are intact,'' Bond said.
   Conservative to centrist voters in the key states would disagree
with Dukakis' opposition to the death penalty, his past policy of
furloughs for first-degree murderers, his membership in the
American Civil Liberties Union and his veto of a bill that would
have required teachers to lead their classes in the Pledge of
Allegiance, Atwater said.
   A survey of campaign trips over the past two months published
Wednesday by The Patriot Ledger of Quincy, Mass., indicates that if
appearances by the candidate are any indication, neither Bush nor
Dukakis is running a 50-state campaign.
   The survey listed 20 states that Dukakis has not yet visited and
26 states where Bush has yet to make an appearance.
   California and Texas topped the travel lists of both candidates
for obvious reasons. California carries the most electoral votes
with 47, while Texas carries 29. Dukakis has spent all or part of
eight days in California since accepting the Democratic nomination
July 21 while Bush has spent six days there. Those numbers were
reversed in Texas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
