<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Generally Higher In Listless Trading, Gold Also Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was slightly higher against most
currencies in listless European trading this morning but dealers
said its rise had been capped by Monday's round of central bank
intervention.
   Gold bullion prices were also higher in choppy trading.
   Foreign exchange dealers said that despite the central bank
intervention, market sentiment still favored a higher dollar.
   The Deutsche Bundesbank, the West German central bank, was
rumored to have asked for dollar rates in the foreign exchange
market early in the day, but dealers said they don't expect an
intervention as long as trading is calm.
   A dealer at a U.S. bank in Frankfurt said the dollar was being
supported by concern over the political trend in the Soviet Union,
where party leader Mikhail Gorbachev is facing a key test in a
party meeting this week.
   ``There is nothing coming out of (the joint annual meeting of
the International Monetary Fund and World Bank in) Berlin, so
people are focusing a bit on these political events,'' he said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.15 yen to a closing 134.35 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 134.23 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday's
rates:
   _1.8815 West German marks, up from 1.8785
   _1.5930 Swiss francs, up from 1.5920
   _6.4050 French francs, up from 6.3980
   _2.1200 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1182
   _1,402.50 Italian lire, up from 1,401.00
   _1.2195 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2215
   In London, the British pound rose slightly to $1.6845, compared
with $1.6840 late Wednesday
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $399.60 an ounce and the
city's five major bullion dealers later fixed a recommended price
of $398.60. Both were up from Wednesday's late bid of $396.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $398.40, up from $396.50 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.99 to close at a bid
$403.63. Silver also rose in London where it was quoted at a bid
price of $6.21 a troy ounce, up from Wednesday's $6.15.
</TEXT>
