<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 0834EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Burma     09-29 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burma,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Claims Civil Servants Back At Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military government claims more than
half the personnel at five ministries in Rangoon have quit a
pro-democracy general strike, but a Western diplomat said today
that the workers only planned to pick up their paychecks.
   A general strike that began Aug. 8 has become the most effective
form of protest since Gen. Saw Maung staged a coup Sept. 18 and
brutally suprressed the daily anti-government street demonstrations.
   The state apparatus was crippled because most civil servants
left their posts, and Saw Maung has ordered the employees back to
work by Monday.
   But the National League for Democracy, the main opposition
alliance seeking an end to 26 years of rule by a military
autocracy, has urged workers to remain on strike until democracy is
won.
   State radio said Wednesday that attendance at the Ministry of
Planning and Finance was up to 74 percent.
   Other departments with more than half the workforce showing up
were the ministries of Health, Home and Religious Affairs, Culture
and Trade, the broadcast said.
   ``A lot of people are going back to work now so they can pick up
their paycheck,'' said a Western diplomat in Bangkok, Thailand, who
noted that pay day comes at the end of the month in Burma. ``We've
had reports of people sitting around drinking tea.''
   The diplomat added if the civil servants do not get paid ``that
would be a very inflammatory thing.''
   Prices for several basic commodities, including rice and
gasoline, have skyrocketed during the recent anti-government
protest, making it increasingly difficult for families to get by.
   Troops today drove away sidewalk hawkers in downtown Rangoon who
have been a major form of commerce since large markets closed after
the coup. No reason was given for the move, and similar streetside
shops still were seen in other areas of the capital.
   Residents, meanwhile, say about fifty truckloads of troops left
Rangoon on Monday, possibly to frontier areas where rebel groups
reportedly are mounting offensives. The government has reported
fierce fighting with Communist rebels in northeastern outposts.
   Soldiers had been brought to the capital from outlying regions
to put down the anti-government demonstrations.
   Diplomats say many unarmed civilians were shot to death Sept. 19
by troops breaking up street protests. The official death toll
since the coup is about 350, although the National League for
Democracy says nearly 1,000 were killed.
   The league, led by retired brigadier general Aung Gyi,
officially registered as a political party Wednesday but did not
say if it would participate in elections promised by Saw Maung.
   No date has been set for the vote.
   A second pro-democracy group, made up of followers of one-time
Prime Minister U Nu, also registered, while a third opposition
political party announced its formation.
   The ruling Burma Socialist Program Party, which had been the
sole political party since 1962 earlier, renamed itself the New
Unity Party. Western analysts say Saw Maung is behind the group,
which has a well-established, amply funded nationwide network.
</TEXT>
