<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LATrucks     09-29 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LA Trucks,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>L.A. Mayor Unveils Plan to Cut Truck Traffic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Tom Bradley's plan to ease some of the
nation's worst traffic congestion and air pollution by putting the
brakes on rush-hour truck traffic triggered quick opposition from a
state truckers' organization.
   The plan announced Wednesday is intended to keep out up to 70
percent of the heavy-duty trucks that normally operate on city
streets during peak travel hours.
   ``No one doubts that truck shipments are vital to our economy,''
Bradley said. ``The old saying, `If you got it, a truck brought
it,' still largely applies. But there is no reason so many truck
deliveries must be made during these peak rush-hour travel times.''
   Karen Rasmussen, spokeswoman for the California Trucking
Association, called Bradley's plan unfortunate and suggested it
would not have a significant impact on traffic.
   A recent state Department of Transportation study found that
large trucks make up only 4.4 percent of peak-hour traffic in the
morning and 2.8 percent in the evening, said Ms. Rasmussen, whose
group represents more than 2,500 companies.
   Bradley, who detailed the plan at a smoggy press conference
surrounded by big rigs on the downtown Sports Arena parking lot,
said it has the support of major trucking companies, the South
Coast Air Quality Management District, state Department of
Transportation and the Highway Patrol.
   Under the proposal, which must still be approved by the City
Council, only 30 percent of large truck fleets could operate on
city roadways from 6 a.m. to 9 a.m. and from 4 p.m. to 7 p.m. The
ban does not apply to freeways, although officials expect it to
cause an indirect reduction there.
   The 30 percent of the trucks weighing 29,000 pounds or more that
fleet owners decide to operate would have to pay up to $60 for a
certificate. Stiff fines would be levied if a trucker operated
without the certificate.
   The fees would help fund a multi-agency ``rapid deployment
force'' that Bradley said would be used to clear snarled roadways
of broken-down vehicles.
   The plan allows for case-by-case exemptions, which will likely
cause the actual reduction to be about 50 percent, analysts with
the mayor's office said.
   No one is sure how many trucks operate in the Los Angeles area,
said Bill Bicker, the mayor's transportation policy adviser. He
estimated the number of heavy rigs at 300,000 and said about
100,000 of those could receive peak-hour exemptions under the plan.
   The program is unique because there is no direct effort to
restrict truck travel on freeways and highways, Bicker said. Such
attempts in other cities have been blocked by federal judges who
said they violate interstate commerce regulations.
   Dennis Woerner, manager of Pathfinder Trucking in Los Angeles,
which has a fleet of more than 20 large rigs, predicted truckers
will be able to adapt more readily than shippers and receivers.
   ``Trucking is a 24-hour business. The shippers and receivers
will have to change their hours, and you're looking at a lot of
additional cost there,'' he said.
</TEXT>
