<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDSKids     09-29 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Kids,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Young AIDS Victim To Continue Schooling At Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT LEISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 7-year-old AIDS victim who is incontinent
and mentally disabled will continue her schooling at home while an
appellate panel decides whether to accept a plan allowing her to
attend school in a glass booth.
   An attorney for Eliana Martinez asked a three-judge panel
Wednesday to overturn a ruling by U.S. District Judge Elizabeth
Kovachevich permitting Eliana to attend a school for trainable
mentally disabled children under those conditions.
   Hillsborough County school officials placed the girl in
homebound instruction for fear she would transmit acquired immune
deficiency syndrome to other children, but Rosa Martinez won a
two-year legal battle in August to get her adoptive daughter into
the classroom.
   Refusing to send her daughter ``to sit in a cage,'' Mrs.
Martinez and her attorney Steve Hanlon turned to the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals for an expedited hearing.
   Mrs. Martinez attended the session and later was joined by
Eliana on the courthouse steps.
   ``Eliana will not go into that glass enclosure,'' Mrs. Martinez
vowed. ``She would not be happy there. I want her in a regular
classroom with trainable, mentally handicapped children just like
her.''
   The judges gave no indication when they would rule.
   Hanlon told the appellate panel he wasn't opposed to classroom
restrictions. But he suggested instead a kidney-shaped table as a
precaution to put distance between Eliana and other children.
   ``It's a tough, tough case,'' said Tom Gonzalez, an attorney for
the school board, adding there are no previous cases dealing with a
retarded, incontinent child with AIDS.
   Citing medical testimony from the trial, Hanlon said the risk of
the girl transmitting the disease to classmates was a ``remote,
theoretical potential.''
   But the appeals judges said that testimony referred only to
tears, saliva and urine, not to a condition of mouth sores and
cracked lips called oral thrush that Eliana has experienced. The
condition can result from AIDS.
   Judge Robert S. Vance said children touch each other's tongues
and disabled children are known to bite each other. Open sores in
the mouth could allow the transmission of blood, he said. To put a
child in such a situation ``may be sentencing those children to
death.''
   Hanlon said Eliana's doctors found no evidence of blood in the
mouth, but Eliana would be kept out of class if that occurred.
   Doctors believe Eliana became infected from blood transfusions
after her premature birth in Puerto Rico.
   Meanwhile, in Arcadia, DeSoto County School Board officials said
the family of three AIDS-exposed brothers once barred from the
classroom will receive less than $1 million to settle the family's
lawsuit against the board.
   The settlement with the family of Ricky, Robert and Randy Ray
does not require school officials to admit any negligence in the
way the boys or their family were treated, James Westberry, the
School Board chairman, said Wednesday. Westberry would not be more
specific about the amount of the settlement.
   Details of the out-of-court settlement were expected to be
released today after attorneys for both sides met with Kovachevich
in Tampa.
   Clifford and Louise Rays' suit sought unspecified damages. It
alleged that their sons' civil rights were violated.
   Ricky, 11, Robert, 10, and Randy, 8, have hemophilia. Doctors
say the boys probably came in contact with the AIDS virus from
infected blood-based hemophilia medication.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
