<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BaseballNewspage 1stLd-Writethru a0533 09-29 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baseball Newspage, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0533,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hershiser Breaks Don Drysdale's Record For Consecutive Scoreless
Innings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 1 graf with Dodgers winning NL West, to play Mets in
league championship.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Los Angeles Dodgers pitcher Orel Hershiser
broke Don Drysdale's 20-year-old record of 58 consecutive scoreless
innings by shutting out the San Diego Padres for 10 innings.
   Hershiser extended his streak to 59 innings and then was taken
out of Wednesday night's game after the 10th inning with a
scoreless tie. The Padres eventually won in the 16th inning, 2-1.
   Hershiser, whose won-loss record this season is 23-8, gave up
just four hits and did not allow a runner past first base until the
10th. He was seeking his sixth-straight shutout.
   After finishing the inning, the Dodgers streamed from the dugout
to congratulate their ace right-hander, who broke the major league
baseball mark set by Drysdale in 1968 with the Dodgers.
   ``I really and truly did not want to get the record,'' Hershiser
said in a dugout interview with Drysdale, now a Dodgers'
broadcaster. ``Out of respect of the man next to me, I feel I
should have stopped at two-thirds. I wanted to just put the ball
down out of respect for the guy next to me and baseball records.''
   ``But the guys next to me in the dugout kind of convinced me to
go for it,'' Hershiser said.
   Said Drysdale: ``If I had known that I would have been down
there kicking you by the seat of the pants.''
   Hershiser's arm helped propel the Dodgers to the National League
West title. Beginning Tuesday, they will play the New York Mets,
winner of the eastern division, for the league championship and a
berth in the World Series.
</TEXT>
