<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Philippines 1stLd-Writethhru   09-29 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines, 1st Ld-Writethhru,a0507,0502</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Suspected Rightwing Extremists Arrested, Military Speaks Of
Plot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs to UPDATE with shooting incidents.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces arrested five more
suspected right-wing extremists and uncovered evidence of financial
support for efforts to topple President Corazon Aquino, the
military said today.
   Brig. Gen. Rudolfo Biazon, chief of the National Capital Region
Defense Command, said those arrested included three former soldiers
and two civilians. Four were arrested late Wednesday and the fifth
was captured today, Biazon said.
   Biazon told reporters they included retired Master Sgt. Domingo
Escarcha, alleged founder of the Black Force Commandos. The
commandos, made up of renegade soldiers, took part in the 1986 coup
attempt at the Manila Hotel and in other moves to topple the Aquino
government.
   The arrests brought to nearly 70 the number of suspected
right-wing extremists arrested in recent weeks. They included Lt.
Col. Eduardo Matillano, a leader of last year's bloody coup
attempt, who was arrested Tuesday.
   Biazon said that during the raids, police found copies of
documents pointing to financial support from unidentified ``outside
sources.''
   On Wednesday, Biazon told a House of Representatives committee
that unidentified businessmen and opposition politicians were under
surveillance for possible links to military renegades, including
former Lt. Col. Gregorio ``Gringo'' Honasan.
   Honasan led the failed coup Aug. 28, 1987, which killed at least
53 people and wounded 300. Matillano was one of Honasan's key
lieutenants during the failed coup.
   Both were later arrested but escaped separately last April.
   In Wednesday's congressional testimony, Biazon said the business
executives and politicians were providing ``financial support and a
political component'' to the anti-Aquino movement.
   He said the military was collecting evidence ``before we take up
action.''
   The opposition Union for National Action, led by Vice President
Salvador Laurel, has demanded in a statement that Mrs. Aquino
release immediately the names of all those suspected of links to
Honasan and other rebel soldiers.
   Opposition Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile, the vice chairman of the
union, denied he was personally linked to the mutineers and said he
was ready to defend himself in court if the government tried to
implicate him.
   Enrile was fired as defense minister in 1986 after a failed coup
by his followers. Honasan was Enrile's chief of security when he
held the defense post.
   Also today, police shot and killed four people after they robbed
an American army officer who had just arrived at Manila's airport,
and soldiers killed six other people in another incident near
Manila's airport, officials said.
   Police identified the robbery victim as Army Capt. Michael
Smith. They said four armed men stole his luggage and valuables,
then sped off in a car and were later chased by police officers.
   Soldiers killed six people they said refused to stop at a
checkpoint, officials said. Troops claimed the occupants opened
fire, triggering a shootout near the Manila airport. No casualties
were reported among the soldiers.
</TEXT>
