<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru   09-29 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0464,0675</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Soviet Union Take Dispute Over Afghanistan To The U.N.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with comment from Soviet and
Pakistani officials. Pick up 3rd graf pvs: `Foreign Minister...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S.-Soviet clash over Afghanistan
remains unresolved, but U.S. officials do not expect it to slow the
Red Army's withdrawal from the embattled country.
   Charging Pakistan and, indirectly, the United States with
violating the Geneva accords aimed at ending the Afghan war, the
Soviet Union on Wednesday hinted it might suspend its pullout
unless U.S. aid to Afghan guerrillas ends.
   A senior Soviet official said today neither the Soviet Union nor
the Afghan government would be at fault if the Geneva agreement was
reduced to ``a useless piece of paper.'' Ambassador-at-large
Nicolai Kozyrev made his comment to reporters in New Dehli.
   But a government spokesman in Islamabad said Pakistan is not
worried as long as Moscow meets its Feb. 15 deadline for a complete
withdrawal from Afghanistan.
   ``It does not alarm us. We expect that the Soviet Union will
abide by its obligations,'' said Humayun Khan, secretary of state
for foreign affairs.
   Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze registered the Soviet
complaint at a meeting of the five permanant members of the
Security Council, chaired by Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz leveled a counterclaim that
Soviet and Afghan bombing raids have violated Pakistani airspace.
   Shultz urged that the dispute be explored by United Nations
observers, who so far have not documented violations on either
side, said State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman.
   Shultz then escorted Shevardnadze from the Secretariat building
and the Soviet news agency Tass said the Soviet foreign minister
later flew home for a high-level Communist Party meeting.
   The two appeared grim and did not respond to reporters'
questions.
   But later, Redman said the Soviets ``left the impression'' they
would maintain their troop withdrawal schedule. Under a
U.N.-mediated accord signed in Geneva in April, the Soviets agreed
to pull out all of their troops by February.
   Moscow sent more than 100,000 troops into Afghanistan since
December 1979 to help prop up a Marxist government that is fighting
Moslem guerrillas backed by the United States, Pakistan, Iran,
China and other countries.
   A communique was released after the meeting of Shultz,
Shevardnadze and the foreign ministers of China, Britain and France
that stressed the urgency for ``continuous talks'' to end the war
between Iran and Iraq in the Persian Gulf.
   While State Department officials in Washington said they
expected the troop withdrawal to be completed by Feb. 15, as
specified in the Geneva accords, a Soviet Foreign Ministry
spokesman hinted at a slowdown.
   ``We want to be as good as our word is concerning the Geneva
accords,'' said the spokesman, Gennady Gerasimov. ``But we expect
the other side also to be as good as its word.''
   The Soviet official accused Pakistan of violations in supplying
``so-called freedom fighters'' with weapons. And Gerasimov
broadened the complaint to include the United States.
   ``I guess they come from the American military-industrial
complex, mainly,'' he said. ``The Geneva accords say that Pakistan
must not try to overthrow the government of Kabul. If you encourage
the so-called freedom fighters to use the missiles to kill innocent
people in the (Afghan) cities, I think it is a violation in our
eyes.''
   Gerasimov said the Security Council was ``a good place to
discuss fulfillment'' of the Geneva accords. The session, attended
also by Sir Geoffrey Howe, the British foreign secretary, and
Foreign Ministers Roland Dumas of France and Qian Qichen of China,
was arranged before Shevardnadze's departure for Moscow.
   The Soviet spokesman acknowledged a Soviet pilot crossed the
Pakistan border several weeks ago. But Gerasimov stressed
Pakistan's support for the rebels at war with the Afghan government.
   ``It is a grave situation, and we must do something about it,''
he said.
</TEXT>
