<1ST_LINE>r r PM-Italy-Riot     09-29 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-Riot,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds Revolt Against Docking Of Poison Ship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANFREDONIA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of people today stoned the
town hall, blocked roads and clashed with riot police to protest
the government's decision to allow a ship loaded with toxic waste
to dock in this southern port.
   Most shops, public offices and schools were closed following a
general strike called by local trade unions.
   ``It looks like a serious revolt,'' said one police officer who
spoke on condition of anonymity. He said there were reports of
injuries among police and demonstrators.
   The incidents broke out shortly after the federal government
ruled that the Deep Sea Carrier should be allowed to dock at
Manfredonia, along the Adriatic coast. The ship is carrying 2,500
tons of toxic waste and is expected to arrive at Manfredonia in a
few days.
   The waste, originally shipped by Italian industrial companies to
Nigeria for disposal, has been ordered returned to Italy by
Nigerian authorities.
   Demonstrators shouting anti-government slogans hurled stones at
the town hall, smashing windows and damaging parked cars.
Protesters overturned police cars during scattered clashes with
officers, according to city officials.
   Demonstrators, who are urging local authorities to defy the
government decision and turn back the Deep Sea Carrier, also
blocked several main roads, touching off major traffic jams.
   No Italian port wants to accept the chemical wastes. Two
freighters, the Karin-B and Khiam Fea, also are carrying waste and
have been accompanying the Deep Sea Carrier.
   Karin-B has been moored off the Tyrrhenian port of Leghorn for
10 days. Local authorities and residents don't want to unload it
until the national government announces a plan for disposal of the
waste elsewhere.
   Khiam Fea is sailing toward the Adriatic port of Ravenna, where
protests have also taken place.
   According to Italian companies that shipped the waste through an
agent, Nigeria had originally authorized dumping of it in Koko but
later reneged on the agreement.
</TEXT>
