<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JudgeCensured     09-29 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Judge Censured,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Court Censure's Judge for Rude Behavior Toward Woman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state's highest court has censured a judge for
rudeness to a woman who sought court protection from her violent
husband, but allowed him to continue on the bench, a decision
criticized by the woman's family.
   Somerville District Judge Paul A. Heffernan did grant a
protection order, but the woman, Pamela Nigro Dunn, was later
murdered by her husband.
   The Supreme Judicial Court on Wednesday expressed its
disapproval of Heffernan's ``discourtesy, rudeness and sarcasm''
toward Mrs. Dunn at a 1986 hearing. The decision involves no fine
or reduction in Heffernan's powers and essentially follows the
recommendation more than a year ago of Heffernan's attorney.
   The five justices dismissed allegations of a pattern of
discourteousness by Heffernan toward women. They noted Heffernan
granted Mrs. Dunn the protection she sought from her husband, Paul,
who had beaten her.
   They also said Heffernan's rude behavior toward Mrs. Dunn had
nothing to do with her murder in August 1986.
   Carole Nigro, Mrs. Dunn's mother, said the high court should
have specifically barred Heffernan from hearing domestic cases.
   ``I'm not saying he was the cause of her murder, but just the
way he handles women in court is wrong,'' she said.
   The Nigros initiated the case two years ago by charging that
Heffernan humiliated and belittled Mrs. Dunn.
   The high court recommended private censure of Heffernan,
meaning, in most cases, that its ruling would never be made public.
But the court decided to publicize its decision because of the
publicity the case has received.
   Heffernan, 55, of Boston, did not return phone calls seeking
comment. His attorney, Thomas Dwyer Jr., said the judge accepts the
ruling.
   In its decision, the court proposed creation of a process by
which a judge's performance can be evaluated and improved
confidentially.
   Dwyer said Heffernan considered the matter closed. He said
Heffernan had voluntarily withdrawn from domestic dispute cases and
had no immediate plans to resume hearing them.
</TEXT>
