<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Peacekeeping-Glance     09-29 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peacekeeping-Glance,0651</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Observer Group For Iran-Iraq Joins Six Others Currently At
Work</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Peace Prize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a glance at the seven U.N.
peacekeeping and observer forces around the world:
   
   NAME: U.N. Iran-Iraq Military Observer Group (UNIIMOG).
   CREATED: Aug. 9, 1988.
   LOCATION: Iran-Iraq border war front region.
   HEADQUARTERS: Tehran, Iran; Baghdad, Iraq.
   MISSION: To observe cease-fire that took effect Aug. 20, monitor
Iraqi and Iranian troops withdrawals to their own countries, and
assist the implementation of U.N. Security Council Resolution 598,
which also calls for an exchange of prisoners of war.
   PARTICIPATING COUNTRIES: Argentina, Australia, Austria,
Bangladesh, Canada, Denmark, Finland, Ghana, Hungary, Indonesia,
India, Ireland, Italy, Kenya, Malaysia, New Zealand, Nigeria,
Norway, Poland, Senegal, Sweden, Turkey, Yugoslavia, and Zambia.
   STRENGTH: 350 unarmed observers.
   FINANCING: The group is expected to cost $74 million over a
six-month period. The means of funding is still being worked out.
   
   NAME: U.N. Good Offices Mission in Afghanistan and Pakistan
(UNGOMAP).
   CREATED: April 14, 1988.
   LOCATION: Afghanistan.
   HEADQUARTERS: Kabul, Afghanistan; Islamabad, Pakistan.
   MISSION: To monitor Soviet troop withdrawal from Afghanistan,
which is to be complete by Feb. 15, 1989.
   PARTICIPATING COUNTRIES: The observers were dispatched from
other existing U.N. peacekeeping and military observation groups.
   APPROXIMATE STRENGTH: 50.
   FINANCING: The Afghanistan observer force does not have a
separate budget, and may dissolve in February when all Soviet
troops are to be out of Afghanistan.
   
   NAME: U.N. Disengagement Observer Force (UNDOF).
   CREATED: June 3, 1974.
   LOCATION: Syrian Golan Heights.
   HEADQUARTERS: Damascus.
   MISSION: To supervise cease-fire between Israel and Syria after
the 1974 Mideast war.
   PARTICIPATING COUNTRIES: Austria, Canada, Finland, Poland.
   APPROXIMATE STRENGTH: 1,330.
   FINANCING: The United Nations has assessed its 159 members about
$35 million for the 1988 expenses of the U.N. Disengagement
Observer Force and its subsidiary Arab-Israeli peacekeeping
operations, payable to the U.N.'s special peacekeeping budget.
   
   NAME: U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL).
   CREATED: March 19, 1978.
   LOCATION: Southern Lebanon.
   HEADQUARTERS: Naqoura.
   MISSION: To confirm Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon after the
Israeli invasion, and to ensure peace and security in the area.
   PARTICIPATING COUNTRIES: Fiji, Finland, France, Ghana, Ireland,
Italy, Nepal, Norway, Sweden, United States.
   APPROXIMATE STRENGTH: 5,800.
   FINANCING: The force is budgeted at about $140 million a year.
   
   NAME: U.N. Truce Supervision Organization (UNTSO).
   CREATED: June 11, 1948.
   LOCATION: Beirut and the Sinai.
   HEADQUARTERS: Jerusalem.
   MISSION: Various Arab-Israeli truce missions; currently assists
UNDOF and UNIFUL.
   PARTICIPATING COUNTRIES: Argentina, Australia, Austria, Canada,
Chile, Denmark, Finland, France, Ireland, Italty, Netherlands, New
Zealand, Norway, Sweden, USSR, United States.
   APPROXIMATE STRENGTH: 295.
   FINANCING: UNTSO was estimated to cost $41.5 million in the
1988-89 budget. The funds come from the regular U.N. operating
budget.
   
   NAME: U.N. Military Observer Group In India and Pakistan
(UNMOGIP).
   CREATED: Jan. 24, 1949.
   LOCATION: India-Pakistan border areas.
   HEADQUARTERS: Rawalpindi, Pakistan and Srinagar, India.
   MISSION: To supervise India-Pakistan cease-fire in Jammu-Kashmir
area
   PARTICIPATING COUNTRIES: Australia, Chile, Denmark, Finland,
Italy, New Zealand, Norway, Sweden, Uruguay, United States.
   APPROXIMATE STRENGTH: 36.
   FINANCING: This group also gets its funds from the regular
budget. The world body budgeted almost $7.3 million for its 1988-89
activities.
   
   NAME: U.N. Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP).
   CREATED: March 27, 1964.
   LOCATION: Cyprus.
   HEADQUARTERS: Nicosia.
   MISSION: Maintaining buffer between Greek and Turkish regions of
Cyprus.
   PARTICIPATING COUNTRIES: Australia, Austria, Canada, Denmark,
Finland, Ireland, Sweden, United Kingdom.
   APPROXIMATE STRENGTH: 2,100.
   FINANCING: The Cyprus force receives its funds through appeals
to U.N. members, about half of which provide contributions. The
secretary-general has estimated its 1988 operating costs at more
than $25 million.
</TEXT>
