<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 1013EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Indians-Hostages     09-29 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Indians-Hostages,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boyle Says Necessity Defense Is `Fatally Flawed'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers held hostage by two gunmen at a
newspaper eight months ago say they suffered no physical damage,
but their sense of security is gone forever.
   ``I find myself constantly looking over my shoulder,''
accounting clerk Deborah Adams testified Wednesday. ``I don't feel
safe anywhere now.''
   She was one of 20 people held hostage at The Robesonian in
Lumberton for up to 10 hours Feb. 1 by two Indian activists
demanding an investigation of drug trafficking, racial
discrimination and corruption in Robeson County.
   ``I've had nightmares,'' said Rita Parker, the newspaper's
classified ad manager, who escaped from the newspaper building just
as the incident was getting under way. ``I found myself at work,
even months after that, watching the front door every time it
opened.''
   Defendants Eddie Hatcher, 31, and Timothy Jacobs, 20, are
charged with conspiracy, hostage taking and weapons violations.
They have never denied taking over the newspaper, but say they had
no other choice because their lives were in danger. They claim law
enforcement officers were planning to kill them because of their
charges.
   But the presiding judge in the case Wednesday disallowed
testimony that the takeover was in effect an act of self-defense.
   ``The `necessity defense' is not available to private citizens
who take vigilante action,'' U.S. District Judge Terrence Boyle
said. ``The perpetrator of the harm has to be the object of the
action. ... You cannot randomly choose innocent persons to take
action against.''
   In a telephone call to The Associated Press late Wednesday
night, Hatcher said Boyle should be impeached, calling his decision
``outright wicked behavior.''
   Hatcher has not participated in the trial, claiming his
constitutional rights are being violated because his attorney of
choice, William Kunstler, is not present. Kunstler, the prominent
radical lawyer, is involved in a New York case, but Boyle denied a
request for another delay in the trial here until that trial winds
up.
   The workers who testified Wednesday said they thought they would
be killed when two men drew sawed-off shotguns from under their
long coats and chained the doors.
   ``I really thought we'd had it,'' said Jo Ann Manns, the
receptionist who first saw the gunmen. ``I thought they were going
to get rough. I didn't know if we were going to get out alive or
not.''
   Ms. Adams said Hatcher, angry and nervous ``almost to the point
of being hysterical,'' told his hostages that his life was in
jeopardy.
   ``He said he could not get anyone to listen to him. He said
Sheriff (Hubert) Stone had a contract out on him and he needed to
talk to the governor,'' she said.
   Bob Warren, an attorney for Jacobs, told the jurors the defense
would show ``how cocaine had corrupted law enforcement in the
county, how poor people without jobs were offered quick money to
sell cocaine under the protection of law enforcement.''
</TEXT>
