<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDS-Dental     09-29 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS-Dental,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human Rights Ruling on Health Care for People With AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decision by the city's Human Rights Commission
to force a dental clinic to pay $47,000 to two men it refused to
treat was a victory for those battling AIDS discrimination,
officials say.
   ``It is difficult to measure the kind of misery and suffering
that others inflict on people with AIDS,'' Mayor Edward I. Koch
said. ``There is no way to adequately describe the pain and
humiliation which discrimination adds to the disease.''
   Commission Chairman John E. Brandon said the commission found
Wednesday that Northern Dispensary, a Greenwich Village clinic,
violated the city's human rights law when it refused treatment to
two longtime patients. One has AIDS and the other has tested
positive for the AIDS antibody.
   ``This case is an important step forward in preserving the
rights and dignity of all people,'' he said.
   The commission also ordered the health facility to post a notice
that it does not discriminate against disabled persons, including
those with AIDS or HIV, the virus that causes acquired immune
deficiency syndrome.
   A message for comment left at the clinic was not returned.
   One of the patients, George Whitmore, a free-lance writer, said
he had told a dentist at the dispensary in 1986 to be careful not
to cut his gums while cleaning his teeth because ``when the immune
system is low it takes a long time to heal.''
   He said it was then that he told the dentist he had AIDS.
   ``He continued to clean my teeth, then stopped, talked to
another dentist and the administrator came over and said it was not
their policy to treat people with AIDS,'' he said.
   ``I was very angry,'' he said. ``I was really outraged.''
   Brandon said with infection control techniques already in place
at the dispensary, the men posed no threat of contagion to dentists.
   He said Northern Dispensary claimed it was justified in refusing
to treat the patients for legitimate medical and financial reasons
and thereby did not engage in discriminatory conduct.
   AIDS is spread through sexual contact, needles or syringes
shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from
pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
