<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CTAAttack     09-29 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CTA Attack,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Attacked With Razor for Helping Woman on Subway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 22-year-old man was slashed across the ear with
a straight razor after he came to the aid of a pickpocket victim on
a subway train.
   Dennis Eagan was listed in good condition at Northwestern
Memorial Hospital after surgeons reconstructed his ear, which had
been deeply cut in the incident Wednesday. There have been no
arrests.
   The attack was the lastest in a series of violent incidents on
public transportation. Two people have been killed and a woman
raped on or near Chicago Transit Authority facilities in the last
two weeks.
   Eagan said he spotted a man putting his hand in the purse of a
woman boarding the train and banged on the train window to warn
her. The man stopped for a minute, then began putting his hand in
the woman's purse again, he said. ``I guess I embarrassed him in
front of the others in the car,'' said Eagan, a service
representative for an air freight company. ``I said `Why do you
have to steal? Why don't you get a job and work?' ... He said, `I'm
going to get you.'''
   Eagan said the man whispered to a companion, then ``the second
guy grabs me and holds me while the first guy pulls a big straight
razor and takes a swing and misses. He tries again and I jerk away,
but he got my ear.''
   Two men came to his aid in pushing off the attackers, Eagan
said. The assailants fled.
   The woman whose purse was being picked ``kept thanking me and
thanking me, but I was thinking about my ear,'' said Eagan.
   Meanwhile, Curtis Sliwa, founder of the New York-based Guardian
Angels civilian patrol group, said he would come to Chicago to help
fight violence on the CTA.
   The Angels' current Chicago contingent of 30 part-timers asked
for reinforcements, Sliwa said. He said he and eight others would
come from New York to help patrol CTA trains.
</TEXT>
