<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GrinderEvicted     09-29 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Grinder Evicted,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shopping Mall Gives Organ Grinder The Boot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tony shopping mall has given a 72-year-old
organ grinder the boot after 29 years because he and his monkeys
aren't fancy enough for the upscale stores.
   ``It was purely a business decision,'' said Warren Chaumont,
marketing director for Lenox Square, the Atlanta area's best-known
shopping mall.
   ``Having an organ grinder in the middle of the center was not in
keeping with the caliber of stores. They pay a lot of money to be
here, and we want to protect the upscale image,'' he said Wednesday.
   Organ grinder Sam Ketcham, who had worked at the center since it
opened in 1959, was told July 19 that he is no longer welcome in
the mall, which includes such stores as Brooks Brothers,
Neiman-Marcus and Macy's.
   ``I couldn't get over it,'' said Ketcham, who now sporadically
works nearby county fairs.
   ``We've been getting calls, asking when we're going to be back.
I don't know what to tell them,'' he said.
   ``I remember people being crazy about these monkeys,'' he added.
``But now I guess they're just a novelty of past generations.''
</TEXT>
