<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 1031EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0468 09-29 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0468,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Urges School Kids to Be Space Pioneers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 9 grafs with Bentsen at school, picking up in
4th graf pvs, Bentsen promised</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lloyd Bentsen told Tennessee
schoolchildren today a Dukakis-Bentsen administration would make
the United States the leader in space exploration again, and he
called on them to consider becoming ``part of this new generation
of space pioneers.''
   Bentsen, the Democratic vice presidential nominee, spoke to the
students while waiting with them to watch the scheduled launch of
the space shuttle Discovery on television.
   The launch ``marks a new beginning in our space program,'' the
Texas senator told the middle school students. ``It is a good
beginning but there are more challenges ahead of us.''
   Bentsen told the students that Democratic presidential nominee
Michael Dukakis was committed to the shuttle program and to a
permanently manned U.S. space station. Dukakis has promised to
revive a Cabinet-level space council and put Bentsen in charge of
it.
   ``When Mike Dukakis and I are elected president and vice
president of the United States, we will make sure that America's
space program is first rate. We will work to regain leadership in
the race to new frontiers. We will commit America to a program of
exploration and adventure second to none,'' Bentsen said.
   That program, he said, would depend on a new generation of
scientists and explorers, and he challenged the students to
dedicate themselves to studying math and science.
   ``Machines can go into space, but only men and women explore
space, probing for its secrets and reaching for the stars,''
Bentsen said.
   From Tennessee, Bentsen was heading home to Texas, where he was
to join Dukakis for a Democratic Party fund-raiser.
   At appearances Wednesday night in Nashville, Bentsen said that
if the Republicans win the election, a George Bush administration
would endanger Social Security and provide inadequate ethical
safeguards.
   Bentsen promised that he and Dukakis would ``never, no never,
turn our backs on kickbacks'' to defense contractors and
consultants, a reference to the Pentagon procurement scandal now
unraveling in the nation's capital.
   Also, as Dukakis has recently, Bentsen said Bush might tap the
Social Security trust fund to help balance the federal budget
deficit and recalled Bush's 1985 vote against cost-of-living
adjustments to Social Security recipients.
   ``In Social Security, in whom do you want to put your trust?''
Bentsen said at the second Nashville fund-raiser. Then, turning a
favorite Bush line, Bentsen said: ``My friends, don't just read
their lips, watch what they do.''
   Bentsen said Dukakis had a proven record as a fiscal manager and
challenged Republicans on their use of the nickname
``Taxachusetts'' to describe the Massachusetts governor's home
state.
   ``When they talk about `Taxachusetts,' ask them the date they
called it `Taxachusetts,''' Bentsen said. The nickname was pinned
on the state in the 1970s, when its tax burden was among the
nation's highest. The tax burden now ranks 34th among the 50 states.
   ``It's the difference between an eight-year photo opportunity
and a country on the move again,'' Bentsen said of the stakes of
the November election.
   Dukakis campaign aides in Tennessee said they have not done any
recent polls but that they believe they are trailing Bush by a few
points.
   Former presidential candidate Albert Gore Jr. worked the
fund-raising crowd in an effort to whip up support for Dukakis and
Bentsen, urging his former supporters to work for the Democratic
ticket.
   The Tennessee senator said Bentsen was prepared to step in as
president while Republican vice presidential candidate Dan Quayle
was not. ``America's values and America's future might well be at
stake,'' Gore said.
   That line of attack was similar to one used by Bentsen earlier
Wednesday in Missouri, where he visited the birthplace of Harry
Truman to promise an active vice presidency and question both
Quayle's qualifications and Bush's judgment in selecting the
41-year-old Indiana senator.
   ``If they were elected, I'd pray for the good health of George
Bush every night,'' Bentsen said, painting Quayle as a member of
the far-right ``out of the mainstream of where the American people
find their hopes and their dreams and their aspirations.''
</TEXT>
