<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AcneAward     09-29 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Acne Award,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Reduces Model's Acne Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appellate court has reduced a $2 million
judgment won by a model who claimed that her face was scarred by
acne caused by cosmetics.
   In a decision issued Tuesday, the court gave Teresa Norris, who
had a contract with the Wilhemina modeling agency, the option of
accepting a reduced sum of $400,000 or going through another trial.
   Miss Norris, now 28 and living in Paradise, Calif., bought $147
worth of beauty products from an Erno Laszlo cosmetic seller in a
Utah department store in 1981 after the employee told her she had
oily skin.
   After eight months and an additional $250 in Laszlo products,
Miss Norris' complexion was ``destroyed by deep-pitted scars and
ice-pick-type marks,'' attorney David Jaroslawicz charged in the
model's damage suit.
   During the March 1987 trial in Manhattan, Miss Norris testified
that she became depressed. ``I stayed home alone. I cried a lot,''
she said. She stopped working, her marriage broke up and she lost
her sexual drive, she said during the trial.
   Cosmetic experts backed her claims and testified that the Laszlo
products had ingredients in them that caused acne. The formula was
changed in 1982.
   Laszlo attorney Frank Ameroso argued that Miss Norris had oily
skin and acne before she ever used Laszlo products. He said her
only pain and suffering was depression caused by her acne and that
any lost income could not be accurately projected.
   The jury had awarded Miss Norris $1 million for lost income and
$1 million for pain and suffering. In its four-paragraph decision
reducing the award, the three-judge appellate panel said both sums
were excessive.
</TEXT>
