<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0447 09-29 0932</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0447,900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede NEW YORK</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis Pledges Toxic Waste Site Cleanup Within Eight Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 14 grafs new with environmental speech; pick up 7th graf
pvs bgng ``Shevardnadze met...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis, with actor
and environmentalist Robert Redford at his side, took aim today at
the Reagan administration's environmental record and promised a
toxic waste site cleanup within eight years.
   As for his Republican opponent in the presidential race, Dukakis
said, ``Calling George Bush an environmentalist is like calling Dan
Quayle a statesman.''
   In a speech prepared for delivery at Rutgers University, Dukakis
cited Bush's role as chairman of the Regulatory Relief Task Force
and blamed the vice president for blocking regulations to reduce
lead in the air as well as a plan to control toxic wastes.
   An active environmentalist and Dukakis supporter, Redford joined
the Democratic nominee on the platform at Rutgers.
   Dukakis received the endorsement of the League of Conservation
Voters, Environmental Action, Friends of the Earth and Clean Water
Action.
   ``Mr. Bush's administration has had eight years to clean up
toxic wastes,'' said Dukakis. ``They've started the cleanup on only
137 sites on the National Priorities List out of a total of 1,200.''
   He said that in his administration ``cleanup will be completed
or well under way at every single one of the nearly 1,200 Superfund
sites on the National Priorities List by December 1996.''
   Companies responsible for pollution that want to help in the
cleanup would get government assistance, he said, adding, ``For the
foot-draggers and the chronic polluters I have just one message:
you better vote for Mr. Bush because if I'm elected the game is
over.''
   He also vowed to collect ``every dime we can of the more than
$700 million in cleanup costs that haven't been paid by the
polluters.''
   While blasting the Republican administration's record on the
environment, Dukakis remained defensive about the pollution in his
own back yard.
   ``Let me say a word about my favorite harbor,'' said Dukakis. He
called Boston Harbor the oldest in America and said, ``People
started throwing things into it more than a century before the
Boston Tea Party. And Mr. Bush doesn't know what he's talking about
because we're cleaning up Boston Harbor. And we've had to fight Mr.
Bush and the administration he belongs to every inch of the way.''
   On Wednesday, Dukakis met with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze, who denied he or his government tilted toward the
Republicans in the presidential race. ``It's up to the American
people to elect a president,'' he said. ``That's the main thing.''
   After meeting with Shevardnadze, Dukakis met with West German
Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher. They posed for pictures
but did not discuss their conversation.
   All the foreign officials were in New York for the opening of
the current session of the United Nations General Assembly.
   Shevardnadze met Friday with Bush, and the vice president was
quick to point out: ``It is a pleasure for me to see Mr.
Shevardnadze again. We have met several times.''
   For his part, the Soviet official acted pleased to confirm
Bush's claim and then some.
   ``This is not our first meeting,'' he said. ``He (Bush) has been
involved in all high-level discussions here in Washington and (in)
our talks with the president.''
   For Bush it was a nice political boost, confirmation from the
Soviet officials that the vice president had been more than just an
onlooker in administration discussions with the other superpower.
   Dukakis could make no comparable claim.
   But Shevardnadze did his best to give Dukakis a measure of
equality. He described his discussion with the Massachusetts
governor as ``very interesting, constructive and profound.''
   He had called his talk with Bush ``a very interesting, a very
substantive and a very profound discussion.''
   The recent signing of an arms control treaty and the general
signs of improvement in U.S.-Soviet relations left Dukakis with
little choice but to tip his hat to Reagan.
   ``I made it clear to the foreign minister that I was not here to
negotiate or discuss specific proposals,'' said the Democratic
presidential nominee. ``We have one president and I support
President Reagan's effort to move forward on these issues right up
to the end of his term in office. ... I intend to build on the work
that President Reagan has begun.''
   Shevardnadze welcomed Dukakis' reference to continuity.
   ``He spoke in support of continuity and consistency, having in
mind support for the recent positive trends in Soviet-American
relations. This is very important,'' said the Soviet foreign
minister.
   While Dukakis was willing to give Reagan credit for the warming
in superpower relations, he hammered away at the administration on
ethics and the economy.
   ``In a Dukakis administration, we're not going to turn the White
House into a wheel of fortune for future foreign agents,'' he told
a rally in Greensburg, Pa.
   Dukakis said that on his first day as president he would sign an
executive order barring top administration officials who leave his
administration from lobbying government agencies for the duration
of his administration. Current law prohibits them from lobbying
their former agencies for one year after leaving officce.
   Dukakis also ridiculed Bush's proposal for establishment of
individual savings accounts, a plan Dukakis said would save middle
class taxpayers ``20 bucks a year.''
   At the same, he said Bush's plan to cut capital gains taxes
would give the wealthiest Americans a $30,000 annual tax break.
   ``George Bush plays Santa Claus to the wealthy and Ebenezer
Scrooge to the rest of us,'' said Dukakis.
</TEXT>
