<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BabySwap     09-29 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baby Swap,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks Over Blood Test Collapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer will ask a judge to decide how a
blood sample will be taken from a 9-year-old girl to help determine
if she was switched with another as an infant in a hospital nursery.
   Marvin Ellin, a lawyer representing a Pennsylvania couple who
think the Sarasota girl may be theirs, said he wanted the
sophisticated blood testing done by Johns Hopkins University
technicians and the results made public, two conditions rejected by
the girl's attorney.
   He said he would file a court petition Monday.
   Dale Swope, who represents the girl's father, said Wednesday his
client will seek genetic tests on his own _ under a cloak of
secrecy.
   In a statement, he said, ``If it produces unsettling results,
they will be kept confidential until our client has had a chance to
explain this tragedy to his child. Then, in time, after she has
adjusted to it, we will disclose it to other interested parties.''
   The tests of blood samples identify genetic links between parent
and child.
   Neither side has released the names of the father or girl
involved.
   Regina and Ernest Twigg of Langhorne, Pa., have claimed in a
$100 million lawsuit that three doctors and a nurse at tiny Hardee
Memorial Hospital in Wauchula switched their healthy baby girl with
an infant that was suffering from a congenital heart defect.
   The couple nursed the sick girl, Arlena Twigg, until she died
recently. Tests taken before a heart operation at a New Jersey
hospital indicated Arlena's blood type was different from theirs.
Further sophisticated tests ruled out any biological relationship.
   Birth records on file with the state show only one white girl,
the Sarasota child, shared the nursery with the Twigg baby.
</TEXT>
