<1ST_LINE>u a PM-PhillyRampage 1stLd-Writethru a0506 09-29 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philly Rampage, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0506,0649</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Suspect In Murder That Set Off Rampage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with neighborhood calm last
night; quotes from official on fatal motorcycle accident as
possible motive for Ortiz shooting, picking up 9th graf pvs, `The
first...'. DELETES penultimate graf, now-outdated material on
motive for killing.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was charged in the killing of an
up-and-coming drug gang leader, a slaying that sparked a rampage by
up to 200 youths who flipped and burned cars and torched and looted
a store, authorities said.
   Several of the youths fired shots into the air, but no one was
injured or arrested in Tuesday night's rampage, police said.
   The mayhem came in retaliation for late Monday's killing of Luis
Antonio Ortiz, 20, whom Police Commissioner Willie Williams
described Wednesday as an emerging drug gang leader. Authorities
said the death came after a member of a rival gang was fatally
injured on a motorcycle he had bought from Ortiz.
   Wednesday morning, Andres Albaladejo, 33, surrendered and was
charged with murder and weapons offenses in connection with Ortiz's
death, police said.
   Ortiz's pickup truck was adorned Wednesday with funeral wreaths
and candles.
   ``I was very upset that we still live in an era when the death
of a drug dealer who peddles death, a man who is accused of a
homicide himself, but not convicted, was being made a hero ... in a
neighborhood where drugs are taking more lives than perhaps
anything else,'' Williams said at a news conference.
   ``It indicates that we and the community have a lot of work to
do to correct this.''
   Williams said police would increase patrols in the poor Hunting
Park neighborhood through the weekend.
   Wednesday night and this morning, an ``uneasy calm'' rested over
the neighborhood, Bennie Swans, the city's Crisis Intervention
Network director, said today.
   Swans met with representatives of the two groups Wednesday night
_ Ortiz's OK Corral gang and the rival Gray Tape gang. He said he
is confident ``that the community is continuing to place enough
pressure on the two groups to cool out.''
   Swans said a Gray Tape gang member, Richie Colon, 18, died
Monday from injuries suffered Saturday when he crashed a motorcycle
he had bought from Ortiz. Swans wouldn't comment on published
reports quoting unidentified neighborhood residents as saying the
motorcycle had bad brakes.
   The first signs of trouble came hours after Ortiz's death, when
youths looted and burned a grocery store owned by a brother of
Albaladejo. Williams said the department was investigating reports
that police stayed away from the store even though they knew of the
looting.
   The trouble brewed through the early morning hours Tuesday, and
firefighters were called to the store a second time when another
fire was set, Williams said.
   The melee broke out in full Tuesday evening, when about 20 or 30
men flipped and set afire two cars that police have been told were
owned by relatives of Albaladejo.
   About an hour later, when an officer responded to an unfounded
call about a burglary, an empty beer bottle was thrown through the
rear window of his cruiser, Williams said.
   For five hours, up to 200 people milled around the neighborhood,
some drinking, some firing shots into the air, Williams said.
   During the riot, uniformed police pulled out and plainclothes
negotiators went in to talk with community leaders and restored
calm.
   In January 1987, Ortiz posted $100,000 bail after being charged
with murder, Williams said. In March, he was arrested for
possession with intent to deliver drugs and freed on $3,500 bail.
   More than 60 people were killed in drug-related violence this
summer in Philadelphia, including a 5-year-old boy whose death
triggered a wave of anti-drug protests.
</TEXT>
