<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 1130EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-DebatePrep Bjt   09-29 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Debate Prep, Bjt,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retransmits a0435 to change to `p' category code</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vice Presidential Candidates Prepare With Consultants, Tapes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last time Lloyd Bentsen and Dan Quayle
debated on television, it wasn't exactly a national media event.
But now the two are rival vice presidential candidates and their
performances next week could influence this year's presidential
election.
   Even as argument continues over who won the debate between
George Bush and Michael Dukakis, the two campaigns are priming
their running mates for next Wednesday's scrap in Omaha, Neb.
They're also trying to move public opinion to receive their
candidates favorably.
   Quayle returned to Washington on Wednesday night to begin
cramming for the 90-minute battle. Bentsen planned to finish his
latest campaign trip on Friday in Washington, and then go to back
to his native Texas on Sunday for final preparations.
   They're both reading briefing books, reviewing video tapes,
huddling with top staff and getting tips on talking to the cameras.
   Although the two men disagree over many policies, the main issue
at stake in the debate is Quayle, who the Democrats contend is not
qualified to be next in line to the oval office.
   Dukakis has said ``the notion of `President Quayle' is a very,
very troubling notion.''
   ``I'll tell you, if they were elected, I'd pray for the good
health of George Bush every night,'' Bentsen said Wednesday, trying
to persuade voters who are leaning toward Bush that they can't risk
Quayle.
   Bush defends his choice, saying in Sunday's debate: ``I see a
man who is young and I'm putting my confidence in a whole
generation of people that are in their thirties and their forties.''
   Republicans are more than happy to downplay Quayle's chances of
surviving a debate with Bentsen.
   ``I don't think there's a lot of pressure on Sen. Quayle because
frankly a lot of people have gotten out there and gotten his
expectations so low that I don't think they could be much lower,''
said James Baker, Bush's campaign chief.
   ``We'll be ready for the debate,'' Quayle told reporters.
   Rich Bond, Bush's deputy campaign manager and political
director, said he expects the candidates will not ``concentrate
their fire at each other but at the top of the ticket.''
   ``Quayle will probably ask Bentsen to join him in debating
Dukakis because they have so much in common,'' he said.
   Bentsen ``can't really debate Quayle on the issues. He has to
defend Quayle's position because most of them are his own. I think
he will squirm,'' said Sheila Tate, Bush's spokeswoman.
   Joseph O'Neill, Bentsen's campaign director, said Quayle's
record will matter as the Democrats try to show ``that our team is
better than their team.'' The Dukakis campaign contends that
Bentsen's differences with Dukakis show that Dukakis didn't want a
``clone'' for a running mate.
   The low expectations for Quayle have worried the Dukakis
campaign, because if they're too low Quayle could win simply by
surviving the debate without any major gaffes. So, alongside a
continual knocking of Quayle, the Democrats are trying to portray
him as an able debater with years of practice in the Senate.
   Privately, Bentsen's aides say they're worried Bentsen, 67, will
look and sound old compared with the 41-year-old Quayle. The
Republicans at least imply the same thing.
   ``The contrast between Quayle and Bentsen is going to be
great,'' said Tate. ``Quayle represents the new generation of
leadership, he's bright and engaging.''
   The Bentsen campaign, trying to refute the expectations
imbalance, points to the April 22 broadcast of public television's
MacNeil@Lehrer NewsHour, during which Bentsen and Quayle debated
the issue of giving workers 60 days' notice before a plant could be
closed. Quayle eventually lost the battle on the Senate floor, but
on television he presented his case attractively.
   The Bush campaign reviewed that videotape before picking Quayle
as Bentsen's adversary. Roger Ailes, the Bush campaign's top media
adviser, watched that tape and will be coaching Quayle.
   Bentsen traveled this week with his briefing books and with
extra staff from the Dukakis campaign, carving out time from his
schedule to watch tapes of Quayle, including his 1980 debates with
Sen. Birch Bayh, whom he defeated to first win election to the
Senate.
   That work will be expanded on the weekend in Washington and then
in Austin, Texas, where Bentsen will travel Sunday and work until
Tuesday when he goes to Omaha. Democratic Rep. Dennis Eckart of
Ohio plans to play Quayle for Bentsen's preparation.
   Quayle is receiving issues briefings from Republican staff of
the Senate and from GOP experts such as Labor Secretary Ann
McLaughlin and former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger.
   In mock debates, Quayle is using Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., a
long-time colleague of Bentsen's on the Senate Finance Committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
