<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ALittleRomance     09-29 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-A Little Romance,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Offers Johns An Alternative: A Class in Romance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has offered men arrested for
propositioning an undercover police officer a break in their
sentences, providing they attend a class on romance.
   So far, 17 of the 61 men arrested on promoting prostitution
charges have accepted. Rochester City Court Judge Herman J. Walz
said the program is available only to first offenders.
   Others arrested in the Labor Day weekend roundup will be offered
the seminars during a court session today.
   The program is run by a neighborhood association and also
includes a sentence of two weekends in the Monroe County sheriff
department's work program. The men will cut weeds and pick up
litter on county highways.
   The 2{-hour seminars on sexual behavior will attempt to show the
men how their actions degrade the neighborhood, the judge said.
   The men will be asked to close their eyes and remember their
first kiss, an attempt to get them to associate sex with romance,
said William Sullivan, president of the neighborhood group.
   ``These guys are like every other man in the world,'' said
Sullivan, a professor of religious studies at St. John Fisher
College. ``They are not villains. They are young guys, old guys,
blue-collar, white-collar. We're trying to deal with them as adult,
mature human beings.''
</TEXT>
