<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DefectorHospitalized     09-29 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defector Hospitalized,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Highest-Ranking Soviet Defector Hospitalized After Collapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The highest-ranking Soviet official to
defect to the United States collapsed during a speech and was in
fair condition at a hospital today.
   Arkady N. Shevchenko, who served as a undersecretary general at
the United Nations for the Soviet Union from 1973 to 1978, was
taken to St. Vincent's Medical Center after becoming ill Wednesday
night during a talk at the Florida Community College at
Jacksonville.
   Shevchenko, 57, author of the best-selling ``Breaking With
Moscow,'' was admitted to the hospital in critical condition with
intestinal bleeding, said Bob Arnold, a hospital spokesman. Doctors
worked on Shevchenko for three hours before he was moved to the
intensive care unit in fair condition, Arnold said.
   ``Now he's up, he's alert, he's in good spirits,'' the spokesman
said. Shevchenko will remain in the hospital for at least five days.
   Arnold said he has been told that Shevchenko has had problems
with an ulcer in the past. But it is not known, Arnold said,
whether the ulcer caused Shevchenko to collapse .
   Shevchenko's defection 10 years ago was hailed as a coup for
U.S. intelligence, which had employed the diplomat as a spy from
1976 to 1978. He became a U.S. citizen in February 1986.
   His scheduled one-hour presentation at the college ended
suddenly after about 50 minutes as Shevchenko tried to make it to
his seat to rest, one witness said.
   ``He cut it short, abruptly,'' said William Hamaker, president
of the National Interest Forum, a local education organization that
sponsored the lecture. ``He barely got back to his seat.''
</TEXT>
