<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SchroederMemorial     09-29 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Schroeder Memorial,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Building Memorial To Artificial Heart Recipient Bill
Schroeder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JASPER, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Not long after William Schroeder died two
years ago after spending 21 months with an artificial heart, his
wife wondered if a little plaque could be erected somewhere in the
couple's hometown.
   The plaque could say something about the spirit of a man with an
extraordinary will to live and a willingness to help others do the
same.
   Later this fall, Margaret Schroeder will get her wish and more.
   On Nov. 13, she will help dedicate a 13.5-foot high, 4,000-pound
stainless-steel sculpture titled ``Gateway to the Heart.''
   ``I thought maybe someday there'd be something, but nothing like
this. It's really overwhelming,'' Mrs. Schroeder said recently.
   The memorial, which almost has been completed by Jasper sculptor
Bernard Hagedorn, will be unveiled at the new Bill Schroeder Sports
Complex south of the Jasper High School football stadium. The
complex includes softball and soccer fields.
   Hagedorm says his work is somewhat controversial, but so was
Schroeder's medical experiment.
   ``It wouldn't be fitting to just have a bronze statue of Bill
Schroeder,'' Hagedorn said.
   What he found more fitting is a sculpture with an arch that
represents not only the gateway to the sports complex but also the
gateway to Jasper. Hagedorn said the arch signifies Schroeder's
triumph when he returned to his hometown for its annual
Strassenfest in August 1985, a year before his death.
   ``This symbolizes what he did and what he accomplished, rather
than him as an individual,'' said Bob Hedinger, a former classmate
of Schroeder's at Jasper High. ``But it all blends together.''
   Schroeder's classmates, Jasper High's class of 1950, reunited to
visit Schroeder while he was ill in a Louisville, Ky., hospital,
and to raise money to defray his medical costs.
   They also have raised about $15,000 for the memorial, but more
is needed for landscaping and other details.
   Schroeder, who was 54 when he died, lived longer than any other
patient with an artifical heart _ 620 days.
   His death on Aug. 6, 1986, at Humana Hospital-Audubon in
Louisville was caused by a massive stroke, one of many he suffered
after receiving the Jarvik-7 heart on Nov. 23, 1984.
   ``There's a really wonderful love in this town,'' Mrs. Schroeder
said.
   ``Wherever he is,'' she said of her husband, ``he's happy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
