<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0461 09-29 0658</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0461,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Dukakis Would Create An Aggressive IRS</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with Bush event; pick up 3rd graf pvs bgng
``No matter...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAINT CHARLES, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush observed the
successful launch of the space shuttle Discovery today and told a
campaign rally, ``America is back in space.''
   The vice president had just completed a campaign speech when the
shuttle was launched. He returned to the platform to tell cheering
supporters in a town square rally, ``What a good day. We're back in
space.''
   Earlier, Bush sharpened his criticism of Democrat Michael
Dukakis' tax enforcement proposals, claiming a Democratic victory
in the fall would mean ``a government hand in every pocket and a
tax agent in every home.''
   Bush accused his rival of wanting to double the number of
Internal Revenue Service agents and told his audience, ``I'm not
for a program that would give the IRS more power than it already
has.''
   During a bus tour Wednesday of rural Illinois, the vice
president repeatedly accused Dukakis of seeking to give the IRS new
and unwarranted powers.
   No matter that the IRS is part of the executive branch of
government that Bush has served for most of the past two decades.
The vice president on Wednesday made the IRS a prime new campaign
target anyway.
   ``The IRS has many fine and dedicated individuals,'' Bush told a
rally in Ottawa, Ill. ``Even so ... it can be high-handed.
Sometimes it seems to treat innocent people as if they were
presumed guilty.''
   Specifically, Bush criticized Dukakis's proposals to beef up
enforcement of tax collections and for a college loan program that
would be paid back through income tax withholding.
   In a day of relatively light campaigning, Bush was to attend
rallies here and in two Michigan cities today: Mount Clemens and
Grand Rapids.
   Bush accused Dukakis, in his enforcement plan, of wanting to
``give the IRS even more power than it already has to go after the
people of America.''
   Said Bush: ``He wants to squeeze another $35 billion bucks out
of the taxpayer's pocket. And, even if it were possible, that would
mean the IRS would have to double the number of their employees to
a total of over 200,000 and that is the equivalent of 20 army
divisions.''
   ``I do not want to create an auditor army of IRS agents,'' Bush
told the Ottawa rally.
   ``Faced with that kind of threat, the American people will need
a conventional defense initiative to defend themselves against all
these IRS auditors.''
   The Dukakis campaign countered that Bush was overstating the
number of IRS agents under the Democrat's plan. A statement said
the plan calls for an average 6 percent annual growth in IRS
personnel, not a 100 percent increase.
   Bush vowed that, if elected, he would resurrect a so-called
``Taxpayer Bill of Rights'' previously advocated, without success
in Congress, by President Reagan.
   The proposed ``bill of rights'' would require the IRS to inform
taxpayers of what rights they have during audits, among other
features.
   Earlier, in a speech to students at Illinois State University at
Normal, Ill., Bush criticized a Dukakis student loan plan that
would call for repayment of the loan depending on an individual's
later earning powers. Loan installments would be automatically
added to tax withholding, under the Dukakis plan.
   ``We do not need to put the IRS on your tail for the rest of
your life,'' he said.
   Bush's bus tour in the company of country music singers Loretta
Lynn and Crystal Gayle took him through northern and central
Illinois.
   While on the bus, Bush and Ms. Lynn compared notes of the
hazards of appearing in public. Bush asked her if she had trouble
with hecklers and drunks.
   ``Are you kidding? I've had guns thrown up on the stage,'' Ms.
Lynn said.
   ``Was that a sign of respect?'' the vice president joked.
</TEXT>
