<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Rowan-Trial 1stLd-Writethru a0453 09-29 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rowan-Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0453,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jurors Still Trying to Come to Decision</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: First 3 grafs new, picking up 4th graf pvs, If convicted</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The jury in the handgun trial of syndicated
columnist Carl T. Rowan indicated today it is so far deadlocked on
a verdict.
   The 12-member panel, which has now reviewed the matter for more
than five hours over two days, sent District of Columbia Superior
Court Judge Arthur L. Burnett Sr. a note saying a unanimous verdict
has not yet been reached. Burnett directed the jury to resume
deliberations.
   Rowan, a longtime advocate of strict handgun control, was
charged with using an unregistered pistol and ammunition to wound
18-year-old Benjamin Smith of suburban Chevy Chase, Md., who had
taken an unauthorized swim in Rowan's pool.
   If convicted of both misdemeanor charges, the 63-year-old Rowan
could face up to two years in jail and a $2,000 fine.
   Rowan's attorneys built their case on a little-used legal
principle called ``entrapment by estoppel.'' The principle holds
that a person cannot be convicted if he is prosecuted for following
advice given him by a government official.
   Rowan has maintained that his son, Carl Jr., was rebuffed by
police officials when he attempted to register the weapon that was
used in the June 14 shooting.
   Rowan's son, a former FBI agent, testified that city police told
him he was exempt from the registration requirements because he was
a law enforcement officer, and that others in his family could have
access to the gun as well.
   ``He (Carl Jr.) was depending upon the competence and
intelligence of those people that the District of Columbia put
there (to advise citizens on gun registration),'' argued Raoul
Carroll, Rowan's attorney. ``He was entirely at the mercy of the
District of Columbia.''
   During his two-day trial, Rowan took the stand to say he
obtained the weapon in 1982 after receiving a series of death
threats from people purporting to be members of the Ku Klux Klan.
   Mindful of the charges of hypocrisy leveled at him because of
his strong anti-gun position, the columnist also said his son had
to persuade him to arm himself.
   ``I had never had a gun in this house,'' Rowan told the jury.
``We (Rowan and his son) got into a little hassle about how
sometimes you can let your idealism go so far that you get killed.''
   Rowan said his fears were compounded by frequent intrusions by
area teens who held late-night pool parties, usually with alcohol
and drugs, in his yard.
   Police officers who investigated the shooting testified that a
door at the rear of Rowan's home showed signs that someone had
tried to break in. One officer also testified that the police
investigation revealed Smith had been shot at close range just
outside Rowan's home.
   Rowan maintained that he shot Smith because he was afraid the
intruder was trying to enter the house. Smith said he was trying to
flee when Rowan shot him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
