<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Cheers Astronauts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A beaming President Reagan today took note of
the successful liftoff of the shuttle Discovery, telling a White
House Rose Garden audience that ``America is back in space.''
   Reagan had been scheduled to take part in a ceremony at 11:45
a.m. EDT honoring organizations, businesses and individuals for
outstanding volunteer efforts last year, but he delayed his arrival
to watch the launch from Cape Canaveral, Fla. on a television in
the Oval Office.
   Smiling broadly as he stood before the crowd gathered under
darkening skies, Reagan announced that the shuttle had blasted off
successfully.
   ``We're now looking forward to the successful completion of the
Discovery mission and the safe return of her crew,'' he said, ``
... and we ask God to bless this voyage.''
   As he left the gathering, Reagan was queried as to whether he
had been worried about the fate of the shuttle.
   ``I think I had my fingers crossed like everybody else,'' he
replied.
