<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Escape     09-29 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Escape,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man And Woman Swim To Freedom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An East German man and woman eluded a communist
patrol boat as they swam across the Havel River to reach freedom in
West Berlin on Thursday, police said.
   West Berlin police said the pair started out from the western
bank of the Havel near the East German village of Nieder-Neuendorf.
They swam about 450 yards in the early morning darkness before
reaching the Heiligensee district in the northwestern part of West
Berlin.
   East German border guards in a patrol board used searchlights in
an attempt to track down the pair, police said in a statement
released to the news media.
   The couple's name was not released under West Berlin police
guidelines aimed at protecting relatives still in East Germany. The
man said he was 34 years old, and the woman is 20, police said.
   On Wednesday, East German border guards opened fire on two men
as they fled over the Berlin Wall from East Berlin to West Berlin.
Neither was injured.
   Nearly 330 people people have fled East Germany to West Berlin
or West Germany this year.
</TEXT>
