<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Military     09-29 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Military,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Military Chief Challenges U.S. on Naval Arms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY GERBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's military chief
Thursday proposed major troop reductions in Europe and challenged
the United States to discuss cutting naval and air forces.
   ``The transition from unpredictable zigzags in relations between
the United States and the Soviet Union to more normal and stable
relations is now under way,'' Marshal Sergei F. Akhromeyev said in
a prepared speech.
   ``It appears that a bridge has been erected into the future, to
the next U.S. administration,'' he said.
   Akhromeyev made a ground-breaking visit this summer to the
United States, where he toured an American warship and sat in the
cockpit of a B-1 bomber. Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci later
toured Soviet installations.
   Akhromeyev spoke to scholars and reporters at an annual lecture
sponsored by the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute
in honor of the late Prime Minister Olof Palme. The institute is
funded mostly by the Swedish Parliament.
   He said the Reagan presidency ``was not easy for us.'' But he
praised progress on missile reductions and said the Soviets had now
destroyed 200 of their medium- and short-range rockets under an
agreement signed in December by President Reagan and Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The United States has destroyed 29 of its missiles so far.
   ``What causes concern are the oceans and seas,'' Akhromeyev said.
   ``The United States and some if its allies do not want to extend
verification of the confidence-building measures to the navies and
air forces where they have a superiority over the U.S.S.R.''
   He cited heavy warships, aircraft carriers, sea-based aircraft
and tactical strike aviation, as areas of Soviet disadvantage.
Warsaw Pact navies ``also possess substantial strike
capabilities,'' he acknowledged without going into detail.
   Akhromeyev laid out similar arguments in an article in the
Soviet Communist Party newspaper Pravda this month, and his speech
here seemed intended to step up pressure on the United States for
naval reduction talks.
   Akhromeyev promised Soviet openness in counting troops at new
talks in Vienna on reducing regular forces in Europe.
   The Vienna talks on Mutual and Balanced Force Reductions in
Europe have dragged on with little progress for 15 years, mainly
because the opposing alliances do not trust each other's estimates
of how many soldiers they have.
   When a planned new format for the talks is set, ``we propose not
merely a data exchange, but also thorough verification, including
on-site inspections, at any time convenient for the parties after
the beginning of the talks,'' Akhromeyev said.
   Both alliances should reduce troops by 25 percent or a total of
500,000 men as a further step, he said. Other reductions should
follow ``to make the character of the armed forces of the alliances
generally defensive,'' he said.
   According to Western estimates, the Warsaw Pact holds a 3-to-1
advantage in tanks and artillery and nearly a 2-to-1 edge in combat
aircraft and troops, including reserves in the Soviet Union.
   Western officials have expressed doubts about the Soviet
emphasis in public statements on defensive strategy.
   Carlucci, in Moscow in August, said he had ``difficulty in
reconciling'' Kremlin claims of a defensive strategy with its high
military spending and offensive weapons stocks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
