<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hirohito     09-29 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Hirohito Group Marches; Monarch Receives Two More
Transfusions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito received blood transfusions for
the seventh straight day Thursday, and a citizen's group marched to
protest media portrayals that the entire nation sympathizes with
the ailing monarch.
   The 87-year-old Hirohito was given two transfusions Thursday, a
palace spokesman said, bringing to 7.7 pints the amount he has
received since internal hemorrhaging caused him to vomit blood
Sept. 19.
   ``Fortunately, his majesty has been in stable condition, though
I as chief court physician am always attentive,'' Kenji Maeda was
quoted by Kyodo News Service as saying.
   Maeda said blood in the bedridden monarch's bowel discharge
Thursday morning prompted the first transfusion.
   ``I understand the symptom of continuing jaundice is still
present,'' Maeda said.
   Hirohito's temperature rose from from 98.7 degrees Wednesday
evening to 99.8 degrees Thursday night, Maeda said. His temperature
flared to 102.6 degrees Saturday, but doctors brought it down with
antibiotics.
   About 150 people belonging to a group called the Japan Citizen's
League held a march in Tokyo and criticized Japanese media coverage
that it said implies the whole nation is watching Hirohito's
illness with grave concern.
   ``We were motivated to hold this rally because we didn't want
foreign people ... to think the whole nation of Japan is
sympathizing with the emperor and worried about his illness,'' said
Ryuzo Harada, secretary-general of the organization.
   He said the emperor's limited role should be further restricted
by ``interpreting the Constitution more accurately.'' The postwar
Constitution limits him to a largely powerless symbol of state.
   Satsuki Kase, of the Women's Democratic League, decried
extensive news coverage of the cancellation of sports events and
autumn festivals in view of Hirohito's serious condition.
   ``We knew the media were going to give biased coverage on the
emperor as `X-Day' approaches,'' Ms. Kase said. ``But they're
making it seem as though if your neighbor cancels plans, you have
to as well.''
   A palace official said he did not know if Hirohito was aware of
the cancellations, or whether the monarch was watching television
news or reading newspapers.
   Hirohito, the world's longest reigning living monarch, has not
taken any solid food for 10 days. His eldest son, Crown Prince
Akihito, 54, has taken over all imperial official duties.
   Palace officials have refused to confirm or deny news reports
that Hirohito has cancer and have urged the media to refrain from
such speculation.
   Nearly 2.5 million people have signed registries at the palace
and elsewhwere throughout Japan wishing Hirohito a speedy recovery.
</TEXT>
