<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     09-29 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radical Students Battle Police, Olympic Security Increased</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Korea-US, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students screaming ``Down with
the Olympics!'' bombarded riot police with hundreds of firebombs
Thursday, and security was increased to prevent attacks at the
Games.
   About 1,000 students clashed with police at Korea University in
the worst street clash since the Olympics began Sept. 17. Fighting
erupted after protesters staged a rally to demand the release of a
jailed student leader.
   Radical leaders said they would disrupt the Olympics before they
end Sunday if police do not release Oh Young-shik, who was charged
Tuesday with violating national security laws for organizing
anti-government demonstrations.
   Authorities have further increased the tight security for the
Games to block possible student attacks.
   At Korea University, waves of charging students pelted riot
troopers with rocks and firebombs that exploded in showers of
blazing gasoline. Riot police tried to deflect the missiles with
shields, but the clothes of many caught fire.
   ``Down with the dictators' Olympics!'' and ``Yankee go home!''
radicals yelled as they charged hundreds of riot police blocking
streets with shields.
   Radical leaders charge the government of President Roh Tae-woo
is using the Olympics to impose authoritarian rule and had demanded
that communist North Korea be a host for the Games along with the
South. They are also demanding that the 42,000 U.S. troops
stationed in South Korea be withdrawn.
   Police martial arts squads with batons charged the students,
beating and kicking some protesters. The students pushed back the
police several times. Some police and students were injured by
firebombs and rocks, but police had no casualty figures and no
reports of arrests.
   The fighting was confined to the streets in front of the school
in northeastern Seoul, about 15 miles from where the Games are
being held. The students, who also came from other Seoul colleges,
blocked the main road near the university and tore down part of the
school's walls.
   Firemen tried to douse exploding firebombs with hoses, but
students drove the security forces off with missiles, and police
hosed the clothing of troopers set on fire.
   The police hurled stones and rocks at the students, but could
not fight them with tear gas, which the government has banned
during the Olympics to try to preserve peace.
   Radical leaders said they would disrupt the end of the Olympics,
but security officials said they are taking no chances.
   The Chosun Ilbo newspaper reported in its Friday edition that
authorities deployed 36,000 police to guard the mens' marathon on
the last day, and special checks were being made along the route
for bombs.
   During the Olympics, only small groups of students have turned
out for the mostly peaceful protests and most South Koreans are
critical of the dwindling radical movement.
</TEXT>
