<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Tibet     09-29 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tibet,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dalai Lama Denies No. 2 Spiritual Leader Urged Return</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Panchen Lama, the No. 2 spiritual leader of
Tibet, has urged his superior, the Dalai Lama, to return to China,
according to a newspaper report Thursday.
   But the Dalai Lama, in Helsinki, Finland, denied Thursday that
he was in contact with the Panchen Lama.
   ``I have not spoken to the Panchem Lama for at least a year,''
the Dalai Lama told The Associated Press. He appeared bewildered by
the Panchen Lama's statement that they were in direct telephone
contact.
   In an interview with the official China Daily, the Panchen Lama
also said a new commission on Tibetan Buddhism will be set up this
year.
   The body purportedly will give Tibetan Buddhists, who have long
chafed under Chinese sectarian rule, more autonomy in religious
affairs.
   The interview came on the eve of the first anniversary of
violent anti-Chinese protests in the Tibetan capital of Lhasa and
underscored Chinese attempts to head off further trouble by
adopting a conciliatory stance toward Tibet.
   Last week, China invited the Dalai Lama to hold a ``direct
dialogue'' with Beijing at a place of his choice.
   On Wednesday, the Dalai Lama said he expected talks with the
Chinese government over Tibet in the near future.
   The Dalai Lama, in Finland on a three-day private visit, told a
news conference ``the time was ripe to find a middle way in talks
with the Chinese.'' Earlier this year, he proposed a plan to give
Tibet domestic autonomy while China would control the region's
foreign and military affairs.
   Buddhist monks who led protests on Oct. 1 last year and again on
March 5 that claimed an estimated 38 lives have demanded an
independent Tibet under the Dalai Lama.
</TEXT>
