<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 1251EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Soviet     09-29 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Soviet,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese Hope Moscow Visit Will Lead to Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China said Thursday it hopes the first working
visit to Moscow by a Chinese foreign minister in 32 years will lead
to a summit and normal ties.
   During his visit this year, Foreign Minister Qian Qichen will
continue talks with the Soviets on the main obstacle to normalizing
relations _ Vietnam's occupation of Cambodia, said ministry
spokesman Jin Guihua.
   ``We hope that the Soviet Union will make concrete efforts for
an early settlement of the Kampuchea (Cambodia) question,'' Jin
told a news conference. The Soviet Union is the main ally of
Vietnam, which invaded Cambodia in 1978 and ousted the
Chinese-supported Khmer Rouge.
   The Soviets said their foreign minister, Eduard A. Shevardnadze,
will visit Beijing but gave no date.
   The Soviet and Chinese Communist regimes split in the early
1960s over ideological differences and rivalry for leadership of
the world communist movement.
   Although they retained formal diplomatic relations, their
leaders have not met since Nikita Khruschev visited Mao Tse-tung in
1959. That also was the last time a Soviet foreign minister came to
Beijing.
   Foreign Minister Huang Hua attended Soviet leader Leonid
Brezhnev's funeral in 1982, but the last working visit to Moscow by
a Chinese foreign minister was in 1956.
   The announcement Wednesday at the United Nations that Qian would
go to Moscow this year was seen as a clear signal that both
countries expect to normalize relations soon. A specific date for
Qian's visit was not set.
   ``There is a lot of arduous work to do between (Qian's visit)
and a meeting of the top leaders of China and the Soviet Union,''
Jin said.
   But he added, ``Of course it can be said that the exchange of
visits between the Chinese and Soviet foreign ministers constitutes
a step forward towards the meeting between the leaders of the two
countries. It is our hope that the two sides will work towards this
direction.''
   The official World Economic Herald in Shanghai, meanwhile,
quoted unidentified diplomats in Beijing as saying a Chinese-Soviet
summit could be held this year or early next year. It did not say
if the diplomats were from one of the two countries or give other
details.
   Qian, 60, spent 10 years in the Soviet Union as a student and
diplomat. He headed China's negotiations with the Soviets over
their disputed border from 1982 until becoming foreign minister in
April.
   His appointment as foreign minister was seen as an indication of
the importance China placed on its gradually warming relations with
the Soviet Union.
   China long has maintained that three obstacles exist to normal
relations with Moscow: the Soviet presence in Afghanistan, the
heavy Soviet troop presence in Mongolia on China's border and the
Vietnamese occupation of Cambodia.
   The Soviet Union began pulling out of Afghanistan this year and
reduced its troops in Mongolia in 1987. In recent months China has
indicated that only Vietnam remains a problem.
   ``The Soviet Union must urge Vietnam to withdraw all its troops
from Kampuchea (Cambodia) at an early date,'' Jin said. ``The
Soviet Union is the sole foreign partner of the Vietnamese. The
Vietnamese cannot fight the war a single day'' with Soviet help.
   Vietnam has an estimated 120,000 troops in Cambodia supporting
the regime it set up under Heng Samrin and battling Cambodian
guerrillas aided by China.
   China and the Soviet Union held their first talks devoted to
resolving the Cambodia issue in August, in Beijing. Both sides said
afterward they found common ground but that differences remained.
   Premier Li Peng said this month that a summit can be put on the
agenda once the two sides come closer on Cambodia. He also said
normalization would not mean a restoration of the Chinese-Soviet
alliance of the 1950s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880929-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 1252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Abortion     09-29 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Abortion,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abortion Opponents Mail Anti-Dukakis `Record' to Catholic Parishes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Massachusetts anti-abortion group opposing Gov.
Michael Dukakis' presidential candidacy has mailed copies of his
record on abortion to Roman Catholic parishes in 18 states.
   ``If elected president, he would strongly support and no doubt
accelerate the tax funding of abortion throughout America,''
according to the literature distributed by the group, known as
Campaign Life America.
   Paul DiPersio, the group's leader who runs a heating and
ventilation business near Boston, said he has spent $30,000 to
publicize the Dukakis record.
   ``As governor of Massachusetts, Michael Dukakis has annually
provided the taxpayers' money in his budgets for the brutal
destruction of 8,000 unborn children by abortion-on-demand,'' the
group's literature said.
   Campaign Life America also wrote: ``Each year, 1,100 minor girls
are taken out of state for the purpose of abortion without the
knowledge and consent of their parents!''
   Andrew Dreyfus, spokesman for the state office of Human
Services, said Massachusetts law allows girls under age 18 to
petition courts for permission to have abortions. If a judge finds
that they are ``mature,'' they do not have to have parental
permission.
   Dreyfus said girls who receive court permission are free to seek
an abortion wherever they want, and he said he did not understand
the reference to their being ``taken'' out of state.
   Steven Crawford, a member of the governor's Statehouse press
staff, said Dukakis ``believes someone's right of choice should not
be a function of their economic status.''
   In his debate with Republican George Bush on Sunday, Dukakis
said he personally opposed abortion but believed the decision lies
with the pregnant woman, ``in the exercise of her own conscience
and religious beliefs.''
   At a sparsely attended news conference Wednesday on Boston
Common, DiPersio said the group was sending an ``information
sheet'' to the ``Respect Life'' committees of 28 Catholic dioceses
in 18 states. The group is asking the committees to bring Dukakis'
record to the attention of news media in their areas.
</TEXT>
