<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HurricaneHelene 1stLd-Writethru a0540 09-29 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hurricane Helene, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0540,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hurricane Helene Keeps Hanging On</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with noon positions, Helene's winds down
to 80 mph.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Helene kept hanging on with 80 mph winds
in the middle of the Atlantic Ocean today as forecasters turned
their attention to a newly formed tropical depression.
   National Hurricane Center specialist Gil Clark estimated that
Helene would lose its tropical characteristics and degenerate into
a low-pressure system sometime today or Friday.
   At noon EDT today, the hurricane's center was near 42.5 north
latitude and 41.0 west longitude, or about 540 miles west-northwest
of the westernmost Azores, the hurricane center reported. It was
moving northeast at close to 35 mph, and posed a threat only to
ships.
   Helene will remain a hurricane as long as its winds stay above
73 mph. Spawned last week near the Cape Verde Islands off west
Africa, its winds reached 140 mph before the storm veered north.
   The 16th tropical depression of the Atlantic hurricane season
formed Wednesday in the mid-Atlantic and was strengthening today.
It was located today about 650 miles east-southeast of Barbados.
The system, with highest winds of 35 mph, was moving west at 15 mph.
   The hurricane season started June 1 and ends Nov. 30.
</TEXT>
