<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Nobel 1stLd-Writethru a0616 09-29 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Nobel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0616,340</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: First 6 grafs new to include Reagan quotes, picking up 4th
graf pvs, ``President Reagan</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Peace Prize</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Congratulates U.N. Force</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan congratulated the U.N.
peacekeeping forces today for receiving the Nobel Peace Prize and
said he wasn't disappointed that he had not won.
   ``No, I didn't deserve it as much (as they did),'' Reagan told
reporters asking about the decision.
   ``It was an admirable decision,'' the president said of the
Nobel Peace Prize Committee's grant of the medallion to the
peacekeeping force.
   Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev reportedly were among
the leading contenders for the award for their efforts on behalf of
arms control, including the signing of a treaty eliminating
land-based intermediate- and short-range nuclear missiles.
   The president talked about the decision following a Rose Garden
cermony honoring businesses involved in charitable works.
   Earlier, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said a note was
sent to the president in the Oval Office as soon as the
announcement of the award in Oslo moved on news wires.
   ``President Reagan today congratulates the United Nations for
its recognition by the Nobel Peace Prize Committee of its
peacekeeping work around the world,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``While the committee praised the peacekeeping efforts in the
Middle East, Cyprus and the Indian subcontinent, they have also
seen that effort in Afghanistan, in the Iran-Iraq cease-fire and
the prospect for a role in Southern Africa,'' he added.
   The president paid tribute to these efforts in his speech at the
opening session of the U.N. General Assembly in New York on Monday.
   Fitzwater said the president extended his congratulations to
Secretary General Javier Peres de Cuellar ``for his leadership in
bringing this new vitality to the United Nations peacekeeping
efforts.''
   Asked whether the president was disappointed that he did not
receive the award, Fitzwater said, ``No, he thinks the U.N. has
done an outstanding job.''
   When asked how the president received the news, his spokesman
said, ``He was given a note after it ran on the wires. ... I gave
him a note after that.''
</TEXT>
