<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Kuwait-Iran     09-29 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kuwait-Iran,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kuwait Reopens Tehran Embassy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABDUL-JALIL MUSTAFA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kuwait has reopened its embassy in Tehran and
stationed two diplomats there in a major step toward improving
relations with Iran, a senior Iranian diplomat said Thursday.
   Iran and Cyprus said they will establish full diplomatic
relations. Iran will open an embassy in Nicosia to be headed by a
charge d'affairs and a Cypriot ambassador will be accredited to
Tehran, the two countries announced.
   Mohammad Faroughy, Iran's charge d'affaires in Kuwait, told The
Associated Press that relations between the Persian Gulf neighbors
were warming following the Aug. 20 cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war.
   Iran repeatedly had accused Kuwait of directly aiding Iraq in
the 8-year-long conflict.
   Kuwait expelled five Iranian diplomats last September, reducing
Iran's embassy staff to Faroughy and an aide, after mobs stormed
the Kuwaiti Embassy in Tehran following riots in the holy city of
Mecca in Saudi Arabia.
   But Kuwait stopped short of actually severing ties with Tehran
as Saudi Arabia did later, citing Iranian subversion and terrorism.
   Well informed sources said the Kuwaiti diplomats in Tehran are a
charge d'affaires and a counselor, putting Kuwaiti representation
on a par with Iran's.
   The improvement in relations is part of a trend set in motion by
Iran's July 18 unconditional acceptance of the U.N.-sponsored
cease-fire and peace talks to end the war.
   France and Canada have restored ties with the Islamic republic,
and Britain is moving in that direction. The United States still
has no relations with Iran, which held 52 Americans hostage in the
U.S. Embassy in Tehran from November 1979 to January 1981.
   Relations between Kuwait and Iran hit their lowest point in
August 1987 after more than 400 Moslem pilgrims, 275 of them
Iranians, were killed in what the Saudis said was Iranian-inspired
rioting in Mecca. Iranian mobs stormed the Saudi and Kuwaiti
missions in Tehran.
</TEXT>
