<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 1302EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Shuttle-Edwards 1stLd-Writethru a0487 09-29 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle-Edwards, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0487,340</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 2 grafs with shuttle reaching orbit.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rescue convoy stood by
at the shuttle's Mojave Desert landing site in case of an emergency
today, but once Discovery reached orbit the ground crew settled
down to prepare for the scheduled touchdown in four days.
   The shuttle is to complete its mission with a landing here
Monday morning on the hard, clay-like surface of Rogers Dry
Lakebed, but ``We're ready to support a landing anytime during the
mission,'' NASA spokeswoman Nancy Lovato said Wednesday.
   The lakebed is the prime site for an earlier emergency landing,
including what the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
calls an abort-once-around, a landing after one low orbit spurred
by a premature shutdown of the main shuttle engines following
launch.
   ``The only reason they wouldn't come here (for an
abort-once-around) would be weather _ if there were flooding (of
the lakebed) or severe winds,'' said NASA spokesman Franklin
O'Donnell.
   But the Air Force forecast sunny skies, temperatures climbing to
near 90 degrees and winds up to 17 mph for today _ acceptable
conditions for an emergency landing here.
   Bad weather here during an abort-once-around would force the
shuttle to land at White Sands, N.M., or back at the Kennedy Space
Center launch site in Florida.
   Loss of two main engines soon after launch would dictate a
trans-Atlantic abort landing at Ben Guerir, Morocco; Moron, Spain;
or Banjul, Gambia. A shutdown of the engines even earlier might
require a return-to-launch-site landing in Florida.
   A 110-person recovery convoy of NASA and Air Force rescuers was
ready to wait out the launch in NASA's shuttle operations area
here, then drive numerous rescue and service vehicles onto the
lakebed if an emergency landing was needed, Lovato said.
   After any landing, technicians check for hazardous vapors around
the shuttle orbiter, then connect various cooling and gas-purging
lines to the spacecraft. Plans call for the shuttle crew to emerge
from the orbiter 30 to 40 minutes after landing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
