<2ND_LINE>PM-East St Louis Blues, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0605,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Trouble for East St. Louis
^Eds: SUBS 4th-6th grafs, `In a separate ...,' with 6 grafs to
UPDATE with charges against Officer dismissed.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST ST. LOUIS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government, trying to
settle a 17-year-old dispute over a sewer grant, has tied up the
city's bank accounts.
   The federal court action Wednesday came just as the city was
about to obey another court order and write a check for $82,397 to
pay firefighters' clothing allowances owed for years.
   It was the third time this year a court has frozen the city's
accounts.
   In a separate matter, a judge today dropped civil and contempt
charges against Mayor Carl Officer stemming from an extra $80,000
the mayor received from the cash-strapped city.
   St. Clair County Circuit Judge Robert Craig dismissed the
charges at the request of county prosecutor John Baricevic, who
would not say why he made the request.
   Baricevic ``knows he didn't have a case against him,'' said
Officer's lawyer, Eric Vickers.
   At a hearing Aug. 29, Craig had held Officer and East St. Louis
in contempt of court after they failed to provide him with records
explaining the $80,000 transfer to Officer.
   Baricevic said Officer got the money between 1984 and last year,
in addition to his annual salary of $30,000. But two of the mayor's
top aides told the judge that many of the city's financial records
couldn't be found.
   An arson fire at the old City Hall Annex may have been to blame
for the problem, said Assistant City Attorney Kenwyn Redding. He
also blamed past City Hall workers, whom he did not identify.
   On Wednesday, city Treasurer Charlotte Moore said she expected
to have enough money on hand after paying off the firefighters to
write paychecks for city workers for the first time since Aug. 30.
   But that was before she learned the federal Environmental
Protection Agency had obtained another freeze on the bank accounts.
   Officer told a City Council meeting that the city is going to
have to chop the payroll.
   ``We're going to have to cut and cut deep,'' he said.
   He said the amount sought by the EPA will bring the projected
city deficit for the rest of the year to $700,000.
   U.S. Attorney Frederick Hess said the latest freeze arose out of
the misuse of the EPA sewer grant. The federal government, which is
seeking $221,175, contends the city of 55,000 did not act on the
project in a timely manner.
</TEXT>
