<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Shuttle-MortonThiokol     09-29 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle-Morton Thiokol,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Employees Cheer Shuttle Success</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tearful Mayor Peter Knudson spoke
for many of Morton Thiokol's 8,000 Utah employees when he called
today's successful launch of the shuttle Discovery ``one of the
greatest moments of my life.''
   Employees at the rocket-maker's Wasatch Operations 25 miles west
of here erupted in cheers as they watched the launch on television
monitors. America's return to space followed to 32 months of
corporate agony.
   ``We're all delighted with the launch. There are lot of very
happy people here at Morton Thiokol.'' said Mike Ayers, acting
director of finance and administration for space operations.
   Today's successful launch was in sharp contrast to the Jan. 28,
1986, Challenger disaster which killed seven astronauts. The
tragedy was caused by a faulty joint seal on one of Morton
Thiokol's 126-foot-long boosters, which allowed a plume of fiery
gas to escape, triggering the explosion that doomed Challenger.
   A pair of the company's redesigned boosters hurtled Discovery
spaceward today.
   The mayor, a dentist, was unable to watch the launch because he
was with a patient. But when informed by a reporter it was a
success he struggled to speak through his emotion.
   ``This is one of the greatest moments of my life,'' he said.
``We're not talking jobs here. We're talking emotions, people's
sense of worth.''
   He said about two-thirds of Morton Thiokol's 8,000 Utah
employees reside in the city and its environs.
   Hundreds of Morton Thiokol officials and engineers were at Cape
Canaveral for the launch. Reporters were barred from company
premises in Utah, in part so employees could watch the launch in
private, said spokesman Rocky Raab.
</TEXT>
