<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-Higgins     09-29 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Higgins,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prominent Peacekeeper Remains A Hostage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Peace Prize, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the most prominent members of the
U.N. peacekeeping forces, U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins,
was in captivity Thursday and was unable to celebrate the Nobel
Peace Prize with his comrades.
   Higgins, 43, of Danville, Kentucky, headed a 76-member observer
group attached to the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon before he was
kidnapped Feb. 17, 1988 near this southern coastal city.
   An underground group calling itself the Organization of the
Oppressed on Earth has claimed responsibility for his abduction,
charging he used his U.N. uniform to spy for the United States.
American and U.N. officials denied the charge.
   The kidnappers, believed to be Shiite Moslem zealots loyal to
Iran, have issued four communiques and a videotape since his
abduction, demanding Israel's withdrawal from an occupied enclave
in south Lebanon.
   They also demanded the release of all Lebanese and Palestinian
guerrillas held by Israel. None of their demands have been met.
   The kidnappers have made no statements about Higgins since April
21, when they issued their fourth and last communique. It said he
would be put on trial on espionage charges.
   But on July 8, Palestine Liberation Organization spokesman
Bassam Abu Sharif said in a published interview that Higgins was
abducted to thwart a plan hatched to rescue eight other Americans
held hostage in Lebanon.
   Abu Sharif was quoted by the Beirut daily Ad-Diyar, which is
based in Christian east Beirut, as saying that the PLO obtained ``a
transcript of the interrogation with Higgins.'' He did not say how
the PLO had obtained it.
   According to the alleged transcript, Higgins had headed the
operations department of the anti-terrorist U.S. Delta force,
widely referred to as the Rapid Deployment Force.
   The nine Americans are among 18 foreigners missing and believed
kidnapped in Lebanon. The longest held is American Terry Anderson,
chief Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press. He was
kidnapped March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
