<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Haiti     09-29 0128</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Haiti,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Encouraged by Haitian Leader's Moves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is encouraged by the
decision of Haitian President Prosper Avril to meet with opposition
leaders, calling it ``an essential first step'' toward the
establishment of democracy, the State Department said Thursday.
   Spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said Avril, an Army general who
seized power on Sept. 17, seems to be finding common ground with
opposition figures with whom he has met.
   ``However, dialogue cannot be a substitute for action,'' she
said. ``We believe the Avril government must take concrete steps to
deliver on the promises that it has made to restore democratic
processes, end human rights abuses, cooperate on narcotics
interdictions and create credible plans for economic development to
allieviate the suffering of Haiti's poor.''
</TEXT>
