<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BabySwap     09-29 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baby Swap,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks Over Blood Test Collapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer representing a 9{-year-old girl
wants genetic tests done to settle the question of her biological
parents, but he wants them done in Florida and he wants the results
kept secret, at least for now.
   But Marvin Ellin, a lawyer representing a Pennsylvania couple
who think the Sarasota girl may be their biological daughter, said
he will seek a court-order Monday to have the sophisticated blood
tests conducted by Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore.
   Secrecy for the tests is unacceptable, said Ellin. ``They
wouldn't be able to disclose the fact that she is their daughter,
they wouldn't be able to file evidence of it.''
   Negotiations between Ellin and Tampa lawyer Dale Swope collapsed
Wednesday in a dispute over who will do the testing and the
confidentiality of the results.
   Ernest and Regina Twigg of Langhorne, Pa., claim in a $100
million lawsuit that their healthy baby girl was switched at tiny
Hardee Memorial Hospital in Wauchula in central Florida with a
fatally ill newborn in 1978.
   Birth records show that only one white girl, the Sarasota child,
shared the nursery with the Twigg baby, so the case has focused on
her.
   Swope, who represents the girl's father, said the tests must be
kept secret.
   ``If it produces unsettling results, they will be kept
confidential until our client has had a chance to explain this
tragedy to his child. Then, in time, after she has adjusted to it,
we will disclose it to other interested parties.''
   The baby the Twiggs took home from the Wauchula hospital
suffered from a congenital heart defect. The couple nursed the sick
girl, Arlena Twigg, through a painful life until she died Aug. 23
following surgery.
   Tests taken before a heart operation at a New Jersey hospital
indicated Arlena's blood type was different from theirs. Further
sophisticated protein-matchting tests ruled out any biological
relationship with the Twiggs.
</TEXT>
