<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Sergeant-Lawsuit     09-29 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sergeant-Lawsuit,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gay Ex-Policeman Files $5 Million Discrimination Suit Against LAPD</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ex-police sergeant who finished first in
his academy class has filed a $5 million lawsuit against the Police
Department, claiming he was discriminated against and endangered
because he is homosexual.
   Mitchell Grobeson said Wednesday that he was refused back-up
help when he requested it during life-threatening situations.
Grobeson, 29, also claims co-workers set up an arrested person to
make false charges against him.
   In addition, he claims he met separately with Mayor Tom Bradley,
Police Commission President Robert Talcott, a lieutenant and three
captains, but none investigated his complaints.
   The Police Commission also is named in the suit along with
Police Chief Daryl Gates and numerous officers.
   Lt. Fred Nixon, a department spokesman, said the department does
not comment on litigation.
   However, Nixon said the department has a policy of
non-discrimination for reasons of sexual preference or religion or
ethnicity and added, ``This is something we've stated very clearly
before, and our record would support that.''
   ``The Los Angeles Police Department is one of the best
departments in the United States, if not the world,'' Groebson
said. ``But there are severe problems in management. Changes need
to be made, not necessarily in the people who are there, but in
their policies and practices.''
   In the lawsuit, Grobeson alleges that on several occasions
fellow officers refused to come to his assistance in potentially
life-threatening situations.
   Grobeson's suit also claims he received at his station items
such as a package labeled ``AIDS survival kit'' and a picture of
Rock Hudson, who died of the disease, inscribed, ``To Mitch, Love
Rock Baby.'' The word ``Beware'' was scrawled on his private car
while parked in a locked police lot, the suit alleged.
   The National Gay Rights Advocates, also a plaintiff in the suit,
is seeking a court order barring the department from the alleged
discriminatory practices.
   Grobeson, on the force for nearly seven years before resigning
June 13, finished first in his class at the Police Academy and was
honored for his work in resolving a stand-off last winter between
property owners and the homeless who were camped on Venice Beach.
</TEXT>
