<2ND_LINE>PM-School Shooting, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0599,0880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Child Dies After Being Shot in School Rampage
^Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with second child dying,
corrects her age from 7 to 8, picking up 4th graf pvs, `Leah Holmes
...;' SUBS 19th graf pvs, `Three of ...,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with two teachers, one student in hospital.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BROOKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENWOOD, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second victim of a gunman's rampage at
an elementary school died today, a few hours after students and
teachers returned to class for the first time since the shooting
spree that also left nine people wounded.
   The man accused in Monday's shootings at Oakland Elementary
School said in an interview published today that he was copying a
similar rampage by a woman in Winnetka, Ill., and also thought of
the taunting he suffered as a child.
   James William Wilson, 19, said that as he pulled the trigger on
his grandfather's .22-caliber pistol, he was remembering being
picked on by classmates at other schools for being overweight and
dressing funny, The State newspaper of Columbia reported today.
   Eight-year-old Tequila Thomas, a third-grader hospitalized in
critical condition since she was wounded, died shortly after noon
today at Self Memorial Hospital, said Dan Branyon, a hospital
spokesman.
   Another 8-year-old girl, Shequila Bradley, died at the school.
   ``All of us here at Self Memorial, as well as the community of
Greenwood, the state of South Carolina and, I'm certain, the rest
of the country join in expressing our deepest sympathy to the
family of this little girl who put up such a valiant battle for
life,'' Branyon said.
   ``Tequila never regained consciousness from the time of her
arrival'' at the hospital, Branyon said.
   Children in this city 75 miles northwest of Columbia returned to
classes at the 600-pupil school a bit nervously this morning.
   Leah Holmes, 8, her arm in a sling from a gunshot wound she
suffered Monday, shook her head emphatically and said ``Nope,''
when asked whether she was scared to return to school. But other
children and parents arriving at the school said they were jumpy.
   There was a police officer on every corner of the school grounds
and at least three officers were stationed at the front of the
building as parents and children arrived.
   ``We're a little nervous, but it's just been a shock
primarily,'' said Alan Maxwell, as he walked his daughter Katy to
school.
   Wilson, who is charged with murder, was interviewed Wednesday by
the newspaper by telephone at the State Hospital in Columbia, where
he is undergoing psychological testing. Relatives have described
him as a hyperactive recluse who has been in and out of a hospital
psychiatric unit during the past eight months.
   Witnesses said Wilson shot pupils who screamed during Monday's
incident.
   ``I thought some of the students in the school were after me,''
Wilson said in the interview. ``I was trying to make them be quiet.
   ``I feel real bad about what happened.''
   On May 20, Laurie Dann killed an 8-year-old boy and wounded six
people in and around a school in the affluent Chicago suburb of
Winnetka before killing herself.
   ``I could understand where she was coming from,'' Wilson said.
``I think I may have copied her in a way.''
   He said he was thinking about an article about Dann that he had
torn from a June issue of People magazine. ``I read it every day,''
he said.
   Wilson also said he was up all night before the shootings
reading a book about John Wayne Gacy, who was convicted in 1980 of
killing 33 men and boys, most of whom were buried under his
suburban Chicago house. Gacy is on death row in an Illinois prison.
   Asked if the book was a factor in the shootings, Wilson said,
``It's possible.''
   He said he had contemplated the shootings a couple of times, but
there wss nothing in particular that triggered the act.
   Wilson said he remembered little of the shootings. ``It was like
a fog or a dream,'' he said, recalling pupils fleeing through
windows and blood on a hallway floor where a teacher was shot.
   ``I remember being at the back of the school with my hands up
and the police arresting me,'' he said. ``I don't remember feeling
anything.''
   Two teachers who were wounded remained hospitalized today, and
one of six students treated and released was admitted today in fair
condition, complaining of discomfort from her wounds.
   Physical education teacher Kat Finkbeiner, who was shot in the
hand and mouth while trying to subdue the attacker, and teacher
Eleanor Hodge were in good condition, Branyon said.
   Oakland Elementary Principal Eleanor Rice and other school
officials talked with about 500 students and parents Wednesday
night to help ease the return to school, which has kindergarten
through fourth grade.
   Ms. Rice praised school staff members for trying to protect the
children.
   ``But it wasn't enough,'' she said. ``Each child in Oakland is
loved, and loved dearly. We do everything in our power to make
school a healthyplace and a happy place. But at this time, we feel
helpless.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880929-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 1421EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a BC-Shuttle-Transcript     09-29 1000</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Shuttle-Transcript,990</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of the launch
communications among ground controllers, commentators and Discovery
in the moments before and following Thursday's shuttle launch.
   At 15 seconds before liftoff:
   Kennedy Space Center commentator Hugh Harris: ``T-minus 15, 14,
13, 12, 11, 10 _ we are go for main engines starts _ 7, 6, _ we
have main engine starts _ 3, 2, 1, 0 _ and liftoff! America returns
to space as Discovery clears the tower!''
   Spacecraft: ``Roll program.''
   Mission Control: ``Roger roll, Discovery.''
   Mission Control: ``Houston now controlling.'' (meaning
communications with the astronauts have shifted from the launch
team at KSC to Mission Control at the Johnson Space Center in
Houston.)
   JSC Commentator Steve Nesbitt: ``Three engines are running at
104 percent.'' (the normal rate.) Three good APUs.'' (Auxiliary
Power Units which provide electricit to operate key systems during
launch and landing.) ``Three good fuel cells.'' (Fuel cells are
electrical generators.)
   Nesbitt: ``Standing by to throttle down to 65 percent.''
(Meaning the engines are slowed slightly to reduce the acceleration
stress on the spacecraft.)
   Nesbitt: ``Throttling down now to maintain a certain speed of
the spacecraft as it passes through Max-Q.'' (The point of maximum
dynamic pressure caused by the stress of speed and acceleration
through the atmosphere.) ``Three engines at 65 percent now.''
   Nesbitt: ``Standing by to see the engines throttle back up at
about 59 seconds. Mark one minute, velocity 2,300 feet per second
(1,568 mph), altitude 5.9 nautical miles (6.7 statute miles),
down-range distance 3 nautical miles (3.4 statute miles).''
   Mission Control: ``Discovery, go at throttle up.''
   Discovery commander Frederick Hauck: ``Roger go!''
   Nesbitt: ``Discovery with go at throttle up, three engines at
104 percent, velocity 3,200 feet per second (2,181 mph), altitude
10.8 nautical miles (12.4 statute miles), down range distance eight
nautical miles (5.5 statute miles).''
   Nesbitt: ``Twenty-five seconds from solid rocket booster
separation. One minute, 25 seconds, three engines at 104 percent.
Velocity 4,800 feet per second (3,272 mph), altitude 20 nautical
miles (23 statute miles), down-range distance 19 nautical miles
(21.8 statute miles). Standing by for solid rocket booster
separation.''
   Nesbitt: ``Solid rocket boosters have separated. Two minutes, 20
seconds, three engines still running at 104 percent, 5,600 feet per
second velocity (3,818 mph), 31.8 nautical miles altitude (36.5
statute miles), down-range distance 38 nautical miles (33 statute
miles). Three APUs still running at normal speed. Three good fuel
cells. We'll hear call ups very shortly from the Capcom (the
astronaut in mission control who does the actual communications
with the Discovery astronauts) about the capability to reach
trans-Atlantic sites.''
   Nesbitt: ``Velocity 6,200 feet per second (4,227 mph), altitude
(unintelligible), down-range 60 nautical miles (69 statute miles).''
   Mission Control: ``Discovery, two engine Moron.''
   Hauck: ``Roger.''
   Nesbitt: ``That call indicating Discovery may be able to achieve
a trans-Atlantic abort (emergency landing) at Moron (Spain) if that
were to become necessary. Current status at Mission Control is that
all positions report go. Three engines 104 percent, velocity 7,600
feet per second (5,181 mph), altitude 53 nautical miles (60.9
statute miles), down-range distance 107 nautical miles (123 statute
miles). Standing by for negative return.''
   Mission Control: ``Discovery, negative return.''
   Hauck: ``Negative return.''
   Nesbitt: ``That call up indicates that Discovery now can no
longer turnaround and return to the launch site in the event of an
abort. Four minutes, 20, velocity 8,700 feet per second (5,931
mph), altitude 59 nautical miles (67 statute miles), down-range
distance 148 nautical miles (170 statute miles).''
   Nesbitt: ``Stand by for press to ATO call.''
   Mission Control: ``Press to ATO,select Banjul.''
   Spacecraft: (unintelligible)
   Nesbitt: ``Call indicates Discovery could reach an abort to
orbit on two engines if there were to become necessary. Five
minutes, three seconds, velocity 10,300 feet per second (7,022
mph), altitude 65.7 nautical miles (75 statute miles), down-range
distance 203 miles (233 statute miles.) Standing by for press to
MECO call.''
   Mission Control: ``Press to MECO, (rest unintelligible).''
   Hauck: ``Roger.''
   Nesbitt: ``They have given a press to a main engine cutoff call,
indicating they can proceed to normal main engine cutoff on two
engines if that were to become necessary.''
   Mission Control: ``Discovery, performance nominal.''
   Hauck: ``Roger. Nominal.''
   Nesbittd: ``Six minutes, 10 seconds, velocity 13,900 feet per
second (9,477 mph), altitude 68 nautical miles (78 statute miles),
down-range distance 323 nautical miles (371 statute miles).''
   Mission Control: ``Discovery, single engine Banjul 104.''
   Hauck: ``Roger.''
   Nesbitt: ``Call up indicates Discovery could achieve a single
engine landing at Banjul (International Airport in Gambia, West
Africa) if that were to become necessary. Banjul is one of the
trans-Atlantic abort sites. Six minutes, 50 seconds, velocity
16,400 feet per second (11,181 mph), altitude 66 nautical miles (75
statute miles), down-range distance 405 nautical miles (465 statute
miles). Guidance also reports that good navigation aids and main
engine cutoff is expected at 8:33.''
   Mission Control: ``Discovery, single engine press, 104.''
(meaning the spacecraft had achieved velocity and altitude to reach
a normal orbit on a single engine).
   Hauck: ``Roger.''
   Nesbitt: ``Discovery is told they can press on to main engine
cutoff in the event of a two-engine failure. Three engines running
at 104 percent, three good fuel cells, three good APUs. Engines are
beginning to throttle up now to maintain 3 Gs (acceleration
forces). (unintelligible) minutes, velocity 22,500 feet per second
(15,340 mph), altitude (unintelligble), down-range distance 618
nautical miles (710 statute miles). We've got about 80 percent
throttle down, maintaining 3 Gs on the vehicle, 10 seconds away
from main engine cutoff. Velocity 24,600 feet per second (16,772
mph), altitude 59 nautical miles (67 statute miles), down-range
distance 700 nautical miles (805 statute miles. Standing by for
main engine cutoff. Main engine cutoff confirmed. Discovery's three
main engines now have shut down as programmed.''
   Mission Control: ``Discovery, nominal MECO. OMS one not
required.'' (meaning that the engine shutoff as planned and the
spacecraft was high enough that a firing of the orbital maneuvering
engines was not required to achieve orbit.)
   Hauck: ``OK. Thank you Houston.''
</TEXT>
