<1ST_LINE>u a PM-IntervenerShot 1stLd-Writethru a0566 09-29 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Intervener Shot, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0566,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Intervening In Robbery For Second Time, Man Shot Dead
^Eds: UPDATES throughout with arrest, police saying same man
involved in both robberies; CORRECTS that slaying occurred Tuesday,
not Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 26-year-old man has been charged with
robbing two taverns and shooting to death the man who tried to stop
him both times, police said today.
   Joseph William Riegler, a 67-year-old widower known as Old Joe,
was slain Tuesday night after intervening in the robberies just
hours apart at his two favorite taverns.
   Investigators first believed the robberies were unrelated, but
now have charged Patrick O'Brien Kelly with both, as well as
pistol-whipping Riegler at the first tavern and shooting him to
death at the second, police spokesman Dave Simpson said.
   Riegler was shot to death outside The Table tavern in northeast
Portland by a man who walked into the bar with a knife, cut the
cord on the cash register and walked out with the machine.
   ``It's the ultimate hard-luck story,'' police Detective Steve
Baumgarte said. ``He's at the first tavern when some guy comes in
and robs the place. He tries to stop him and gets pistol-whipped.
   ``He goes to the hospital, is treated and released. He ends up
at a second tavern and that place is robbed,'' Baumgarte said.
   ``Against the warnings of the other patrons, he gets involved.
He follows the robber outside and is shot in the head.''
   Simpson said investigators believe it was a coincidence that
both Kelly and Riegler headed for the same tavern after the first
robbery. The man who robbed The Table wore a ski mask, while the
robber of The Cracker Box tavern did not, however.
   Kelly also was charged with trying to kill a police officer by
ramming his car when officers tried to arrest him, Simpson said.
   Detectives began watching Kelly after receiving information that
implicated him in both robberies and arrested him Wednesday night,
he said.
   He was held without bail pending arraignment this afternoon.
   Friends said Riegler, a regular at both taverns, took the
robberies personally.
   ``He felt someone was breaking into his home,'' said George
Dixon, owner of The Cracker Box. ``He liked coming in here. He was
content to have a beer or two and just visit with friends.''
   In the wake of the killing, Dixon said he was considering
closing his tavern.
   ``My feelings are right now that I'm going to lock this place up
and close the sucker down for good. But when his funeral is over,''
he said, ``I'm going to open it up one more time.
   ``I'm going to invite all his friends in, and we'll drink a
toast to him.''
</TEXT>
