<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChildrenSaved     09-29 0200</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Children Saved,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Children Thrown to Safety From Burning Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three infants were saved from a burning
apartment building when they were tossed from a second-story window
to the waiting arms of a neighbor.
   The neighbor then had to coax the mother of two of the children
to jump, Firefighters credited Odell Espinoza with saving his
neighbors' lives.
   ``I finally said, `This is your last chance. Either jump now or
get burned,''' Ms. Espinoza said after Wednesday's fire.
   Nineteen-year-old Erica Hagens suffered a fractured ankle and
minor back injuries after jumping from the window. Gerod Smith, 16
months, Gerich Smith and Cordaro Hagens, both 4 months, were
uninjured, the fire department reported. One child is Ms. Hagens'
niece.
   Ms. Hagens' mother, Vivian White, 41, also escaped injury when
she climbed out a second-story window to a porch roof and was
lowered down.
   Ms. Hagens said she was asleep with the children when her mother
awoke her and warned her about the smoke. Ms. Hagens couldn't get
downstairs because heat and smoke filled the stairwell.
   Fire officials said the blaze was started by a pile of clothing
left too close to a gas water heater.
