<HEAD>Ueberroth on VP Debates: I'd Rather Watch Baseball</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baseball Commissioner Peter Ueberroth joked
Thursday he'd rather ``watch a baseball game'' than view next
week's televised debate between the vice presidential candidates.
   Ueberroth spoke at Creighton University in Omaha, which will
host the debate Oct. 5 between vice presidential candidates
Republican Dan Quayle and Democrat Lloyd Bentsen.
   The American League and National League playoff starting times
have been adjusted to allow nationally televised coverage of the
vice presidential debate on that date.
   ``The election of leaders in this country is far more important
than a baseball game,'' Ueberroth said at a news conference
following his speech. ``Having said that I'd rather watch a
baseball game. But we're going to accommodate the debate.''
   Ueberroth said he would not pursue a political career following
his final day as baseball commissioner March 31, saying he was too
blunt to be a good politician.
