<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Peacekeepers-Nobel     09-29 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peacekeepers-Nobel,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peacekeepers Say Nobel Prize Gives Boost to Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Peace Prize, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. peacekeeping troops from the
Iran-Iraq border to this war-divided island celebrated their Nobel
Peace Prize on Thursday with champagne and a renewed spirit that
their missions are important.
   ``We are here to keep the peace, but winning the Nobel prize
makes you feel good,'' said Canadian Trooper Tony Mayfield, 22.
   He and Grant Townsend, 22, also of Canada, guarded a crossing
point linking the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sectors of Nicosia.
   The 2,000-strong peace force in Cyprus has been maintaining the
peace since clashes between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities first broke out in 1964.
   ``The Nobel is a feather in the United Nations' cap. It gives us
an incentive to continue,'' Mayfield said.
   Peacekeepers in Jerusalem popped open bottles of champagne as
the word was passed by radio from outpost to outpost.
   Five of the seven U.N. peacekeeping forces worldwide are
stationed in the Middle East _ Cyprus, southern Lebanon, Israel's
northern and southern borders, Syria's Golan Heights and the
Iran-Iraq border.
   The others are along the India-Pakistan border and in
Afghanistan.
   Spokesmen said the prize was a tribute to the thousands who
serve in difficult conditions. Nearly 10,000 peacekeepers wear the
blue beret that has come to symbolize the U.N.'s role in monitoring
truces and trying to prevent bloodshhed.
   ``The Nobel Committee recognizes that the quest for peace is a
universal undertaking involving all the nations and peoples of the
world,'' said Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   Pvt. Mike Mahony, 26, of Cork, Ireland, said he hoped the award
would make UNIFIL's job easier in Lebanon. ``I feel proud. I
suppose we'll get more respect now,'' Mahony said in a telephone
interview.
   ``It is a very happy occasion that our work is appreciated. It
is always good news when people say you are doing good work,'' said
Major J.H. Buhl of the 340-member Danish contingent on Cyprus.
   A duty officer from Bangladesh at the headquarters of the nearly
2-month-old U.N. Iran-Iraq Military Observer Group heard the news
from a reporter.
   ``It is exciting,'' said the officer, who refused to give his
name. He said the men at the front ``will know that their job is
worth doing.''
   Timor Goksel, UNIFIL spokesman in Lebanon, said, ``The
international community has finally given appropriate recognition
to all the sacrifices our people have made.''
   Lt. Gen. Martin Vadset, chief of staff of the U.N. Truce
Supervision Organization in Jerusalem, said the award recognized
the U.N. peacekeepers' success in preventing conflicts from
escalating.
   ``We have lived through all the wars you can think of and one
might say that we have been unsuccessful in preventing them,'' said
Vadset, a Norwegian. ``But we have been successful in being
available to minimize disaster when it first broke out.''
   ``I think the committee chose exactly the right time'' to give
the prize to the peacekeepers, said Brian Urquhart, the British
U.N. undersecretary who set up the peace forces until he retired in
1985.
   U.N. peacekeeping officials in Finland, which contributes more
troops than any other country, said they hoped the Nobel Peace
Prize would induce members to pay their bills for the financially
ailing forces.
   The United Nations is in arrears in payments to countries which
provide soldiers for the peacekeeping forces. It owes Finland $22.5
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880929-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 2105EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i BC-PeacePrize-Text     09-29 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Peace Prize-Text,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Text Of Nobel Peace Prize Announcement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Peace Prize, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the announcement by the Nobel
Committee on Thursday that the U.N. peacekeeping troops won the
1988 Nobel Peace Prize. This is the committee's official
English-language version.
   The Norwegian Nobel Committee has decided that the 1988 Nobel
Peace Prize is to be awarded to the United Nations peacekeeping
forces.
   The peacekeeping forces of the United Nations have under
extremely difficult conditions contributed to reducing tensions
where an armistice has been negotiatied but a peace treaty has yet
to be established.
   In situations of this kind the U.N. forces represent the
manifest will of the community of nations to achieve peace through
negotiations, and the forces have by their presence made a decisive
contribution towards the initiation of actual peace negotiations.
   It is the considered opinion of the committee that the
peacekeeping forces through their efforts have made important
contributions towards the realization of one of the fundamental
tenets of the United Nations.
   Thus the world organization has come to play a more central part
in world affairs and has been invested with increasing trust.
   The peacekeeping forces are recruited from among the young
people of many nations, who, in keeping with their ideals,
voluntarily take on a demanding and hazardous service in the cause
of peace.
   In the opinion of the committee their efforts contribute in a
particularly appropriate way towards the realization of the goals
of the United Nations.
</TEXT>
