<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-Shuttle     09-29 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Shuttle,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators Hail U.S. Return to Space</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Space Shuttle Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relieved members of Congress hailed the
successful launch of the space shuttle Discovery on Thursday as a
rebirth of the nation's exploration of space.
   Several senators watched the launch on television sets in the
Republican and Democratic cloakrooms, then walked to the floor to
applaud the achievement.
   ``After nearly three years of down time, after thousands of
design changes, the U.S. space shuttle Discovery has just blasted
off from Cape Canaveral, returning America to space,'' Sen. Howell
Heflin, D-Ala., said to a gallery filled with visitors.
   He praised the thousands of people involved in the work of
preparing Discovery for launch and said: ``Today their work for
America has succeeded.''
   ``The numbing tragedy of January 28, 1986 ... is still fresh in
ur minds and weighs heavily on our hearts,'' Heflin said in
referecne to the explosion that destroyed the shuttle Challenger
and killed its seven crew members.
   But he said the nation was right in refusing to be discouraged
by the accident, which had grounded the U.S. manned spaceflight
program.
   ``Not exploring the limitless bounds of space would constitute a
tragedy greater than the one we experienced in 1986,'' Heflin said.
``Space is the greatest adventure of our times, and any nation that
sees itself as a great leader cannot and must not ignore it.''
   ``We're back in space,'' said Sen. Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C.,
chairman of the Senate space committee that oversees the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration.
   ``And more than anything else this reaffirms our commitment,''
he said. ``The commitment has been questioned for the last two
years. But now we're back, and with that commitment, we'll attract
the best and the brightest to the program.''
   Sen. Thad Cochran, D-Miss., said ``This is a day when we can all
take pride in our country.''
   ``It is a great day for the exploration of the universe,''
Heflin added.
   Senate Republican leader Bob Dole of Kansas strode from the GOP
cloakroom minutes after the launch to report to Sen. Richard
Shelby, D-Ala., who was presiding.
   ``Straight up, about 100 miles up,'' Dole said with a grin.
   How long is the mission? Shelby asked.
   ``Four days, one hour,'' Dole replied.
   And then referring to Congress' struggle to adjourn for the
year, he added: ``They are going to stay up there until we leave.''
</TEXT>
