<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Shuttle-Press     09-29 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Press,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Press Thrilled At Launch, Disappointed About New Distance
Restrictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 journalists at a
remote press site cheered Discovery's majestic liftoff Thursday,
but also expressed disappointment that new safety rules prevented
them from a closer view.
   ``Tremendous! It's more than I thought,'' said an excited James
Miller with a public television station in Houston, seconds after
viewing his first launch.
   Prompted by Air Force concerns that the Complex 39 press site
could be bombarded by falling debris if the solid rocket boosters
malfunctioned, only 1,800 reporters were allowed to work from the
main press site.
   The new rules forced Miller and other reporters to view the
liftoff at the alternate press site, more than six miles away from
the from Discovery's launchpad.
   Despite the spectacular liftoff, reporters at the remote site
were envious of their colleagues who viewed the launch from only
four miles away and expressed fears that additional restrictions
may follow.
   ``I hope this is not indicative of a trend,'' said Miller, who
called the new measures ``indirect censorship.''
   ``I still wish I was over there (main press site). It was still
a thrill. I'm glad nothing happened,'' said Lynn Occhiuzzo of the
Fort Lauderdale News and Sun-Sentinel.
   Most of the journalists arrived at the mosquito-infested site
before dawn after driving in bumper-to-bumper traffic for up to two
hours from Titusville and Cocoa Beach.
   While awaiting the liftoff, journalists slept, and chatted.
   David Hartman, former host of ABC's ``Good Morning America,''
passed a football to his sons as he awaited the liftoff.
   Reporters complained the lack of telephones, electricity and
work space limited their usefulness at the remote site.
   ``There is no way to get a story filed in a timely manner,''
said Beverly Keneagy of The Florida Times-Union of Jacksonville.
Daily newspapers were allowed to have just two people at the main
press site.
</TEXT>
