<DOCNO> AP880929-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 2115EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SugarProgram     09-29 0161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sugar Program,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Market Stabilization Prices for Sugar Up Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``market stabilization price'' of raw cane
sugar in the 1989 fiscal year that begins Oct. 1 will be up
slightly to 21.8 cents per pound, the Agriculture Department said
Thursday.
   Acting Underscretary Richard W. Goldberg said the new rate
compares with 21.76 cents per pound in the current year.
   The MSP, as it is called, is a market price objective, a
computed level at or above which producers would be more likely to
repay price support loans and sell their sugar in the marketplace.
If market prices are below the MSP, producers are inclined to
forfeit their sugar to the government instead of paying off their
price support loans.
   Included in the computation for the MSP is the government's
price support loan rate of 18 cents per pound, plus allowances for
transportation costs and interests on loans to make the total of
21.8 cents per pound.
</TEXT>
