<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHESTERTON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``There's no place like home,'' said
Dorothy in the ``Wizard of Oz.'' But where's home?
   Not Kansas, says a Chesterton town board, which believes Dorothy
would rather have been a Hoosier.
   The town board has launched a tongue-in-cheek custody battle
with Kansas over Dorothy.
   The board passed a resolution declaring Chesterton, home of one
of the nation's largest Wizard of Oz festivals, as the hometown of
Oz heroine Dorothy Gale.
   Jean Nelson, founder of the Chesterton Oz Festival, gathered 336
signatures on a petition in favor of the resolution, approved
Monday.
   Ms. Nelson, who owns the Yellow Brick Road shop, said she
decided to push for custody of Dorothy after some Kansas officials
said they were shunning Oz publicity because the movie does not
promote Kansas in a favorable light.
   Sonya Woertz, a spokeswoman for the Kansas Department of
Commerce, said the objections arise from scenes in the MGM movie
that portray Dorothy as bored with life in dreary, flat Kansas.
   ``We decided since Dorothy has been trying to go home for the
last 49 years, and since Kansas doesn't want her, we decided to
make her a Hoosier,'' Ms. Nelson said Thursday.
   A copy of the resolution will be forwarded to Kansas Gov. Mike
Hayden.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HALF MOON BAY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Artists upset with a pumpkin
festival have found a way to fight back _ with a squash fete.
   Katie Murdoch and other local artists are angry that
out-of-towners have taken over the 18th Annual Half Moon Bay Art
and Pumpkin Festival. The sponsors include Safeway, Chevrolet,
Budweiser and General Foods.
   ``The pumpkin festival has taken on a corporate life of its
own,'' said Murdoch, a history teacher.
   So, she organized the First Annual Squash Festival.
   The pumpkin festival attracts more than 300,000 people during
its weekend run in mid-October. The main attraction are works of
art made from pumpkins.
   The squash festival will feature 30 local artists displaying
everything from landscape paintings to kelp baskets and something
known as a ``fish print,'' images made from living fish.
   The festivals will go head-to-head. Both are set for the Oct.
15-16 weekend.
</TEXT>
