<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Soviets-Emigration     09-29 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviets-Emigration,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Easing of Emigration Restrictions Planned, Officials Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet officials have informed the United
States they plan to ease restrictions that prevent many Soviet
citizens from emigrating, the State Department said Thursday.
   Spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said the Soviets spelled out their
position last week in two days of talks during the visit here of
Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze.
   ``We welcome the reform process under way in the Soviet Union,''
Mrs. Oakley said, noting that the Soviets promised to allow free
emigration in a 1975 agreement.
   She added, however, with even with these changes, not all
individuals will be able to exercise their right to leave the
Soviet Union.
   She said the United States will continue to urge the Soviets to
uphold their commitments.
   According to U.S. estimates, Soviet Jews have been emigrating at
the rate of 2,000 per month this year and the total for 1988 could
be the highest since 51,000 emigrated in 1979.
   American officials, insisting on anonymity, said the Soviets
plan to repeal a requirement that Soviet citizens receive an
invitation to leave from close family members living abroad as a
condition for their departure.
   Another proposal would waive the current requirement that a
child receive parental approval to leave the country, the officials
said.
</TEXT>
