<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Nobel     09-29 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Nobel,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Officials Praise Nobel-Winning Peacekeepers; Urge Release of
Higgins</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Peace Prize, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. leaders praised the organization's
peacekeeping forces after they won the Nobel Peace Prize on
Thursday, but they pleaded for a U.S. Marine kidnapped while
serving with a U.N. group in Lebanon.
   ``For us, it is a No. 1 priority that this officer who was
serving the United Nations, who was wearing the blue beret when he
was kidnapped, should be released without delay,'' said Marrack
Goulding, who leads the peacekeepers as U.N. undersecretary for
political affairs.
   Lt. Col. William R. Higgins commanded a 76-man group attached to
the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon when he was abducted Feb. 17.
   The pro-Iranian Organization of the Oppressed on Earth claimed
responsibility and said Higgins would be put on trial for spying.
U.S. and U.N. sources deny Higgins was a spy.
   ``He was one of those unarmed observers attached to UNIFIL in
southern Lebanon. I would like to take this opportunity to repeat
an appeal, which has been made so often in the past, to those who
are holding him to release him without delay,'' said Goulding.
   Goulding's call for Higgins' release was the only somber note at
the United Nations.
   ``Everybody from the 38th floor to the basement is delighted''
that the Nobel Committee awarded the Peace Prize to U.N.
peacekeepers worldwide, said U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani.
   Goulding had no comment on how the $390,000 prize will be used.
   If the prize money is donated to U.N. peacekeeping budgets, it
won't make much of a dent in the peacekeeping deficits.
   On Aug. 31, U.N. documents show that members owed $325 million
to the U.N. Interim Force In Lebanon and owed the U.N.
Disengagement Observer Force on the Golan Heights and the U.N.
Emergency Force between Egypt and Israel $45 million.
   Members also owed the U.N. force in Cyprus $158.1 million by the
end of July, said Goulding.
   He estimated 400,000 to 500,000 people have worn the blue helmet
or beret of the U.N. peacekeeping force, and said 9,991 soldiers
now are in the force, supported by about 2,000 civilian personnel.
All were honored by the award.
   ``In awarding the Peace Prize to the peacekeeping forces of the
United Nations today, the Nobel Committee recognizes that the quest
for peace is a universal undertaking involving all the nations and
peoples of the world,'' Perez de Cuellar said in a statement to the
General Assembly.
   Brian Urquhart, the former undersecretary-general in charge of
U.N. peacekeeping who retired in 1986, said the award honors the
733 soldiers who died on observer missions.
   ``But it is also a recognition of this important pioneering
concept, which uses military personnel in a non-violent role to
promote peace, an idea whose time has come and will go far,'' he
said.
   Perez de Cuellar has invited Urquhart and Goulding to accompany
him to Oslo, Norway, to accept the prize Dec. 10 on behalf of the
peacekeepers, said Giuliani.
   Goulding said Perez de Cuellar is making ``continuous and
vigorous efforts with all those who may have influence with those
who are holding Col. Higgins to get him released,'' he added.
   In a separate interview, the chief U.S. representative to the
world body, Vernon A. Walters, also recalled Higgins.
   ``Let us never forget that among those peacekeeping forces that
received the Nobel Peace Prize is Lt. Col. Higgins, and he is
hostage today, and whose liberation we expect,'' Walters said.
</TEXT>
