<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gibraltar-IRA     09-29 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gibraltar-IRA,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spain Keeps Detective From Testifying In IRA Inquest, Witness Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GIBRALTAR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spanish authorities are preventing a police
detective from testifying about three IRA guerrillas he trailed
through Spain before they came to Gibraltar, where British
commandos killed them, a witness said Wednesday.
   Gibraltar police Inspector Manolo Correa told an inquest that
the unidentified Spanish officer had sent him a statement
expressing a desire to testify about the March 6 slayings. But
Correa said the officer told him several days ago his superiors
would not let him testify.
   Spain maintains a long dispute with Britain for the return of
sovereignty over Gibraltar, a British colony at the southern tip of
Spain. It was ceded to Britain in 1713.
   News reports in Spain and Britain have indicated the Spanish
police kept the three IRA members under surveillance until they
crossed into the colony, hours before being shot.
   Correa's testimony came on the 17th day of an inquest by
Gibraltar Coroner Felix Pizzarello and an 11-man jury into the
shooting deaths of Mairead Farrell, 31, Daniel McCann, 30, and Sean
Savage, 24.
   Pizarello, after hearing Correa's testimony, ordered that a new
effort be made to seek the Spanish lawman's testimony.
   The IRA has acknowledged the three victims were on ``active
service,'' meaning they were on a mission to strike at British
targets at the time of their deaths.
   British commandos have claimed that they killed the three
unarmed guerrillas because they feared the guerrillas were about to
detonate a radio-controlled bomb in a car parked about a mile away.
   The inquest has no power of prosecution but is to determine
whether the shootings were lawful.
   If the jury decides upon a verdict of unlawful killing, the
Gibraltar attorney general is expected to hand down criminal
indictments, Gibraltar sources said.
   Critics of British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government
have singled out the Gibraltar IRA shootings as evidence of an
unofficial government ``shoot-to-kill'' policy against the outlawed
Irish Republican Army.
   The predominately Roman Catholic IRA has carried out a violent
campaign to force the end of British rule in mainly Protestant
Northern Ireland. It sharply increased its attacks on British
soldiers after the Gibraltar slayings.
</TEXT>
