<1ST_LINE>u w AM-HousePartisanship Bjt   09-29 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-House Partisanship, Bjt,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wright Claims Republican Vendetta, But GOP Says He's Ducking Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright accused Republicans
on Thursday of carrying out a political vendetta against him, but
the minority countered that Wright was simply trying to duck
charges that he improperly disclosed classified information.
   The comments came as angry personal charges flew back and forth
between leadership figures of both sides of the political aisle.
   ``I've never seen this thing get out of control like it is
now,'' said Rep. Tony Coelho, the Democrats' No. 3 leadership
official in the chamber. Coelho accused GOP leaders of trying to
``tear down the institution'' and of caving in to right-wing
elements of their party who seek to embarrass Wright.
   ``The relationship between the parties is very strained,''
agreed Rep. Dick Cheney of Wyoming, the chamber's third-ranking
Republican. He said exchanges were far more acerbic than normal.
   Wright, D-Texas, told reporters that GOP efforts to have the
ethics committee investigate whether he violated House rules by
talking publicly last week about a CIA covert action in Nicaragua
are groundless and motivated by politics.
   ``It is really very sad that people will try to use the ethics
committee, or any other committee of the House, as a cat's paw to
try to carry out a partisan political vendetta against another
member,'' he said.
   ``I can take it,'' Wright said. ``As speaker, I'm in the
kitchen, and I'm not offering to get out.''
   But Republicans called Democratic counteroffensive a dodge, and
said Wright simply was seeking to escape the consequences of his
mistake by stirring up a partisan smokescreen.
   ``The speaker's most recent transgressions have energized a lot
of us on our side,'' Cheney said. ``I don't think the House can
duck this. They (Democrats) know they've got a problem.''
   Some moderate Democrats were saying privately that while they
were proud of the legislative record of the 100th Congress under
Wright's leadership, they were uncomfortable with his highly
visible role in U.S. diplomacy toward Central America.
   That role assumed center stage again last week when Wright, in
response to a reporter's question, said he had ``clear testimony''
from the Central Intelligence Agency that U.S. agents had sought to
prompt civil unrest in Nicaragua to provoke a crackdown by the
leftist Sandinista government and scuttle peace talks.
   Cheney and House Minority Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill., quickly
asked for intelligence and ethics investigations of Wright to
determine whether he had violated House rules against disclosure of
classified material.
   Members in both parties saw the participation of Michel _ who
for years has taken a less confrontational tack in dealing with the
majority _ as a turning point in Democrat-Republican relations in
the chamber.
   The tensions surfaced on the House floor Thursday after one
Democratic lawmaker, Rep. Pat Williams of Montana, denounced GOP
vice presidential nominee Dan Quayle for ``hypocrisy'' in voting
against the Job Corps, then telling Job Corps recruits at a Texas
campaign appearance that ``We believe in you.''
   Republican members bristled, and demanded that Williams be ruled
out of order. Williams then asked that his remarks be stricken from
the record, but in so doing repeated the hypocrisy charge at least
three times.
   Seeking to deal with the Wright controversy, the Intelligence
Committee met Wednesday and declined, on a party-line vote, to turn
over to the ethics committee relevant classified information.
Democrats reasoned that there was no obligation to do so because
the material had not yet been requested officially.
   In a statement issued Thursday, Michel said the lack of action
compelled him to ask Republican members of the Intelligence
Committee to prepare a confidential report to him outlining their
recommendations on what to do about the allegations concerning
Wright. He said that could lead to a request for unspecified action
by the full House ``to guarantee the integrity of House rules and
procedures.''
   Coelho, D-Calif., said the intelligence meeting was forced by
Republicans, who knew the panel would have to decline to release
the information.
   ``What you have now is an effort that's very political, very
aggressive and loaded with grenades,'' he said, attributing the
whole controversy to Republican frustration over being the minority
party in the House since 1956.
   ``The Republicans' problem in the House is that we don't take
them seriously, Republicans in the Senate don't take them seriously
and the White House doesn't take them seriously,'' Coelho added.
   ``I wonder what Tony's smoking?'' Cheney said when apprised of
the comments. ``The real problem is the speaker, and the way he
operates. ... He's trashed the CIA, damaged U.S. foreign policy in
Nicaragua. ... All of Tony Coelho's blue smoke and mirrors won't
change that.''
</TEXT>
