<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HollywoodTeamsters     09-29 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hollywood Teamsters,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hollywood Drivers Vote to Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Hollywood drivers union voted
overwhelmingly Thursday to strike television and film producers,
with the walkout set to begin Monday.
   Teamsters Local 399 voted 1,441-196 to reject the latest
contract presented by the Alliance of Motion Picture and Television
Producers, according to Teamster secretary-treasurer Earl Bush.
   ``Hopefully, with this kind of rejection, the alliance will take
another look'' at the offer, Bush said.
   He added, however, that he was not optimistic that the two sides
would settle their differences at a Friday bargaining session.
   Both sides have been asked by a federal mediator to resume
negotiations Friday. But the producers contend their terms are
final and that there is no room for more bargaining.
   Key issues include overtime rules, salary rates and guidelines
for the making of non-union films. Bush has called the producers'
offer ``the worst contract offer ever made to a union.''
   If the Teamsters walk out Monday, it will mark the second
entertainment industry strike this year. The Writers Guild of
America struck from March until August, and Hollywood production is
only now returning to full speed.
   Alliance spokesman Herb Steinberg said the strike by the
2,200-member Teamsters union local would not cripple the film and
television industry.
   ``We have trained drivers and we're ready to continue production
under any circumstances,'' Steinberg said. ``I don't think it will
have any impact on production. The studios are very well prepared.''
   He said newspaper advertisements for replacement drivers drew an
overwhelming response.
