<1ST_LINE>r a AM-King-Globe     09-29 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-King-Globe,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Clears Globe Of Libeling Former Governor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boston Globe did not libel then-Gov. Edward J.
King when it said in a 1981 column that he tried to influence a
judge's sentence in a gang rape case, a jury decided Thursday.
   After little more than two hours of deliberations, the Suffolk
Superior Court jury decided that the Globe was wrong when it
published a Nov. 8, 1981, column by David Farrell saying King had
called a judge and demanded harsher sentences in the case.
   But when asked if King had convinced them that the column
``discredited him in the minds of any considerable and respectable
class of the community,'' the jury answered no.
   Sixteen jurors began deliberating in the 6{-year-old case after
Judge James P. Lynch Jr. instructed the panel on libel law.
   The jurors were working on a special verdict slip that posed a
series of questions, beginning with whether the column was true.
King needed to prevail on each question or else lose his lawsuit.
   After the verdict, a composed King left the courtroom with his
wife, Jody, and his attorney, Robert Goldman, and declined to say
how the verdict might affect his political plans. King had said he
would consider running for governor again if he won.
   ``We did the best we could,'' King said, adding he did not
consider the lawsuit a waste of time because ``now we know that
something the Globe never retracted was a false statement.''
   King, who joined the Republican Party after losing the September
1982 Democratic primary to Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, filed suit in
January 1982 against the Globe and several editorial employees,
asking for $3.6 million.
   King said he and his lawyer would decide on an appeal within 30
days.
   ``It's terrific to have been vindicated. This is a victory for
freedom of the press,'' said Boston Globe attorney Joseph Kociubes.
   ``I always felt I did a good job writing the column,'' said
Farrell, who now works as a free-lance public relations agent.
   The jury heard closing arguments Wednesday after six days of
testimony.
   King testified the column amounted to a charge of obstruction of
justice that struck him like ``an ice pick in the ribs'' and caused
him to lose sleep on more than 1,000 nights since publication.
   On cross-examination, King acknowledged that he never publicly
denied making the call, and Kociubes argued that King, who was
thinking of suing the Globe before the column, made no showing of
financial, social or political harm.
   Farrell testified he was told about King's purported call to
Judge Herbert Abrams by state Treasurer Robert Q. Crane, an old
friend and a reliable source about Massachusetts politics.
   Crane testified he was the source, but could not recall who told
him about the call.
   Under libel law, a public figure, such as King, has the burden
of showing not only that a publication was false but also that it
defamed him. Further, the governor must show that the column was
published with ``actual malice'' _ that is, with knowing falsity or
with ``reckless disregard'' for the truth.
   Lynch instructed the jury that ``reckless disregard'' means that
Farrell and the Globe ``entertained serious doubts about the truth
of the statement.''
   The judge said such doubt could concern the source, but he said
that mere failure to investigate Crane's tip by itself did not
constitute libel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
