<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 1655EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Shuttle-BoosterFlash     09-29 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Booster Flash,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mysterious Flash Alarms Some Viewers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some television viewers were alarmed
Thursday to see what looked like flame spewing from the side of a
booster rocket after Discovery blasted off, but experts attributed
it to a phenomenon of physics and said the shuttle was never in
danger.
   At Goddard Flight Space Center in Maryland there were reportedly
gasps and moans at what seemed to be flames licking up the
shuttle's solid rocket boosters less than a minute before
separation from the ship. It looked to some like a ghastly replay
of the Challenger disaster in which a flame from a joint in a
booster rocket blew up the shuttle 73 seconds into flight.
   As reporters and people at home, including former space
employees, watched televised reruns, calls began pouring into
newsrooms while space officials studied tapes to be sure there was
no problem.
   A former NASA employee who didn't want to be identified called
the Beloit, Kan., Daily Call and said NASA apparently was lucky,
said Publisher Gary Hilt.
   ``In terms of flames that somebody might report, I don't have
any information,'' said Steve Nesbitt, the voice of Kennedy Space
Center mission control, where officials who reacted jubilantly to
the launch quickly asked booster experts to analyze tapes of the
launch as the concerned queries began.
   But officials of the Marshall Space Flight Center in Alabama,
who are responsible for the operation of the boosters, said the
flash was no cause for alarm.
   ``It's predictable, repeatable,'' said Royce Mitchell, Solid
Rocket manager from Marshall who was at Kennedy Space Center for
the launch.
   He recalled a similar ``flickering'' after the Discovery's first
liftoff in 1984.
   ``It's just a basic law of physics,'' Mitchell said, terming it
``reverse flow separation.''
   Mitchell said that as shuttle begins to roll, the booster plumes
_ the flame that comes from the bottom of the rockets in normal
operation _ sometimes converge and the hot particles recirculate.
   He compared the visual effect to seeing a man on a speeding
motorcycle. Instead of his jacket flapping out behind, it is
plastered to his back because of the reverse separation principle.
   Marshall center director J.R. Thompson celebrated with a
Jamaican cigar and officials said they were confident about the
boosters' performance.
   ``Everything looks normal ... everything looks good,'' Mitchell
said.
   Divers had reached the reusable boosters and their first ``quick
look'' indicated no problems, he said.
   Mitchell said as soon as the recovery ships towed the boosters
to port Friday night, ``We'll look at them almost immediately.
   ``Everybody wants to look at this first joint, and you're
looking at the guy who wants to look at it first.''
</TEXT>
