<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Shuttle-Ceremonies     09-29 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Ceremonies,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ground Workers Unfurl Flag; Challenger Memorial Planned Aboard
Discovery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA workers unfurled a flag in the
firing room at Kennedy Space Center in the final hours before
Discovery's launch Thursday and said it would remain in place until
the shuttle returns.
   The flag ceremony will be a tradition in the launch control
center from now on, NASA spokesman Hugh Harris said.
   ``It was not a very formal sort of thing,'' he said. ``You don't
take time out of the countdown. It was just as the announcement was
made that the rotating service structure was being retracted that
the string was pulled and the flag rolled down.''
   The rotating service structure was rolled away from Discovery
Wednesday afternoon.
   Discovery's five-man crew plan a special memorial in space for
Challenger's seven astronauts, according to Commander Frederick H.
Hauck. The nature of the memorial will be revealed during a news
conference the astronauts plan to hold on the mission's third day,
he said during a prelaunch interview.
   ``If we ever forget what happened to Challenger, it's going to
be a sad day, because we might become complacent once again,'' said
Marine Lt. Col. David C. Hilmers, one of Discovery's crew members.
