<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 1659EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-WelfareOverhaul     09-29 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Welfare Overhaul,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Approves First Welfare Overhaul in More Than 50 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate gave a near unanimous stamp of
approval Thursday to the first major welfare overhaul in over half
a century, seeking to turn the system into a gate of opportunity
rather than a long-term trap.
   ``For the first time in its half-century existence, the U.S.
Senate has moved to an entire redefinition and overhaul of what
we've come to know as our welfare system,'' said Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., the leader of the effort.
   The vote on the final version of the Family Welfare Reform Act
was 96-1, with Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., the lone opponent. The
bill was headed for House approval Friday and from there to the
White House, where President Reagan has expressed satisfaction with
it.
   The hard-won bipartisan compromise, the result of a summer of
seesaw negotiations, centers on a large-scale work, education and
training program to be aimed primarily at welfare mothers. Support
services such as child care would be available to program
participants and those moving into low-wage jobs.
   ``In early 1987, we had a process that many of us never really
thought would be complete,'' said Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole,
R-Kan. ``Lo and behold, here we are today with a bill we can
support.''
   Moynihan said that under the revamped system, welfare will ``no
longer be a permanent or extended condition.'' Instead, he said,
the new system will stress work, child support and last-resort cash
supplements while encouraging the needy to get the education and
training needed to avert long-term dependence.
   Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., a key supporter of the drive, said
there's no guarantee the bill will work. ``But if it does only half
of what we hope, it's an immense step forward,'' he said. ``What we
have had does not work. That we can say with certainty.''
   The five-year, $3.3 billion compromise plan is modeled largely
on Moynihan's Senate bill, which passed 93-3 in June. Its Job
Opportunities and Basic Skills program starts out at $600 million
in 1989, rising to $1.3 billion by 1995, when states would have to
be serving 20 percent of eligible recipients.
   The bill also requires that starting in 1991, all states provide
benefits to two-parent unemployed households; only 27 now do so.
The other 23 could limit benefits to six months in a 12-month
period.
   The final compromise contains some provisions that House
liberals found hard to swallow, among them a 16-hour-a-week
workfare requirement for one adult in two-parent families receiving
welfare. The requirement, effective in 1994, would kick in for that
relatively small group only if an intensive two-month job search
failed.
   Conservatives called it the first step toward a wider work
requirement while liberals complained bitterly about slavery and
punishment. Some discontented House members were expected to vote
against the bill, but they are a minority.
   The least controversial aspect of the welfare overhaul is its
opening section, designed to step up child support payments from
non-custodial parents. The section requires automatic
wage-withholding when a court awards support and a higher rate of
paternity establishment by states.
   ``It makes a statement about what our society believes the role
of parents should be,'' said Sen. Thad Cochran, R-Miss., an
original sponsor of the Moynihan bill. ``Parents should provide for
their children.''
   The current welfare system, Aid to Families With Dependent
Children, serves 3.7 million families, including 7 million
children. AFDC costs the federal government about $8.5 billion a
year in cash benefits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
