<2ND_LINE>AM-School Shooting, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0750,0813</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Reopens; Second Shooting Victim Dies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 4 grafs after 10th `We're a...' to UPDATE with
superintendent at afternoon news conference commenting on school
activities and absentee rate; picks up 10th graf pvs, `Wilson,
19...' Edits remainder to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY BROOKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENWOOD, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second little girl died Thursday of
wounds received in a gunman's rampage at an elementary school, and
her classmates returned to school to find police guarding the
grounds and teachers ready to help them through the tragedy.
   Tequila Thomas, 8, a third-grader at Oakland Elementary School,
died about 12:30 p.m., never having regained consciousness since
she arrived at Self Memorial Hospital after the shooting three days
earlier, said hospital spokesman Dan Branyon.
   Oakland Principal Eleanor Rice said the parents of the school's
600 students seem to have had most of their fears calmed since
James William Wilson opened fire Monday, reportedly focusing on
children who cried.
   In a newspaper interview published Thursday, Wilson said he was
sorry about what happened and said he was patterning his actions in
part on a Chicago-area woman's rampage in May.
   Pupils, many accompanied by their parents, returned to school
Thursday to find the grounds edged with police officers. At least
one child still wore a sling on her arm from the wound she received
Monday.
   Mrs. Rice said staff members met with counselors Wednesday to
learn how to help their pupils deal with the shootings.
   ``We've not had any calls suggesting students didn't want to
come,'' the principal said. ``Some of our students have some fears,
and we're going to work through that.
   ``Certainly, anything of this magnitude, it's going to take some
time to recover.''
   Leah Holmes, 8, her arm in a sling from a gunshot wound, shook
her head emphatically and said ``Nope,'' when asked Thursday
morning if she was scared to go back to school. But other children
and parents arriving at the school were less sure.
   ``We're a little nervous, but it's just been a shock
primarily,'' said Alan Maxwell, as he walked his daughter Katy to
school. Katy said she didn't hear the gunshots but remembers a
teacher coming into her classroom and telling everyone to duck
under their desks.
   Teachers took the children on tours of the building Thursday,
including the cafeteria where much of the shooting took place, to
satisfy the children's curiosity, schools Superintendent Robert
Watson said at a news conference.
   ``There were a variety of different activities in the classroom
where they allowed the children to act out some of their
feelings,'' Watson said.
   ``Several teachers felt they saw a lot of anger ... a lot of
getting feelings out about the killer,'' he said.
   ``Our absentee rate today was a little bit above normal,'' he
said. Forty-three children were out, including those who were sick,
he said.
   Wilson, 19, of Greenwood is being held on two murder charges and
undergoing psychological testing at the State Hospital in Columbia.
Police and witnesses said he walked calmly through the school
Monday morning, shooting two teachers and nine pupils before
surrendering.
   Relatives have described him as a hyperactive recluse who has
been in and out of a psychiatric ward during the past eight months.
   Self Memorial Hospital spokesman Branyon said Tequila had been
wounded in the neck and chest, and her condition had continued to
deteriorate. She died Thursday with her family at her side. The
other victim, Shequila Bradley, 8, died at the school Monday.
   Two teachers remained hospitalized in good condition Thursday
and one of the students treated and released Monday was readmitted
to the hospital, listed in fair condition. Lashonda Burt, 8, was
hospitalized again because she was complaining of discomfort from
her wounds, Branyon said.
   The State newspaper reported Thursday that Wilson said that
during the shooting he was thinking about other crimes he had read
about, and the teasing he received while in school for being
overweight and dressing funny.
   ``I thought some of the students in the school were after me. I
was trying to make them be quiet. I feel real bad about what
happened,'' Wilson told the newspaper.
   He said he had stayed up all night before the shootings, reading
a book about John Wayne Gacy, who is on Illinois' death row for
killing 33 men and boys. Wilson said ``it's possible'' the book was
a factor in the shootings.
   The newspaper said he also mentioned a magazine article about
Laurie Dann, the 30-year-old baby sitter who shot six children in a
Chicago-area elementary school in May before killing herself. An
8-year-old boy died.
   ``I could understand where she was coming from. I think I may
have copied her in a way,'' Wilson told the newspaper.
</TEXT>
