<1ST_LINE>r p AM-DukakisAd     09-29 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis Ad,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republican Officials Distance Themselves From Negative Ad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Republican Party officials and the
state director of George Bush's presidential campaign are
disavowing any connection with an advertisement against Michael
Dukakis sponsored by a group called Greeks Against Dukakis.
   Republican George Shissias of Columbia said he wanted to welcome
Democratic vice presidential nominee Lloyd Bentsen to town
Wednesday, so he took out the full-page advertisement in The
(Columbia) State headlined ``Hazards of Duke.''
   Bentsen canceled his trip, but the ad ran Wednesday anyway.
   The content of the newspaper ad is based on a Republican
National Committee publication called ``The Hazards of Duke,'' a
312-page volume of issues and quotes to use against Dukakis.
   Shissias said Wednesday he collected money to pay for the ad and
hired a professional agency in Columbia to produce it. The ad,
which appeared only in The State, said: ``Paid for by Greeks
Against Dukakis; Steve Moskos, chairman (Charleston); John
Raftakis, vice chairman (Anderson); George Shissias, treasurer
(Columbia).''
   Shissias said there is no formally organized Greeks Against
Dukakis, and there has been no meeting and no election of officers.
He said the men just agreed to use their names on the ad and to
help pay for it.
   Ginny Wolfe, state director for the George Bush campaign, said
the Bush camp had nothing to do with the ad.
   Tony Denny, executive director of the state Republican Party,
said the party was not involved and that the three men who signed
the ad are not state or local party officers.
   Lt. Gov. Nick Theodore, a co-chairman of Dukakis' state
campaign, said that if there had been many more Greek-Americans
against Dukakis, their names would have appeared on it. Theodore is
of Greek descent.
</TEXT>
