<HEAD>Nine Injured When Eastern Jet Veers Off Runway</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SJO2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Miami-bound Eastern Airlines jet
with 130 people aboard slid off the runway while taxiing for
takeoff Thursday, breaking the landing gear, starting an engine
fire and injuring nine people, officials said.
   The Boeing 727 was quickly evacuated and firefighters soon
extinguished the blaze in the left engine, said a control tower
official.
   The plane, carrying 122 passengers and eight crew members,
apparently had problems with its landing gear shortly before the
accident, said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
None of the Americans aboard was injured.
   ``The plane had started taxiing, then we realized it was bumping
along the runway. It left the tarmac, dropped its nose and ended up
crosswise on the runway,'' the tower official said.
   The jet came to a stop after the front landing gear snapped and
the nose plowed into the ground just off the runway, he said. The
engine fire apparently began when the engine scraped the runway
after the landing gear broke.
   Civil aviation and Eastern officials refused to comment.
   The control tower official said most of the passengers were
Costa Rican.
   An official at the Hospital Mexico said all nine injured were
Costa Rican and they were treated and released. The official
refused to be identified.
   All flights in and out of Juan Santamaria International Airport
were suspended after the 8:40 a.m. (10:40 a.m. EDT) accident. A Pan
American flight had to return to Panama because it could not land.
