<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 2301EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Aegis-Tests     09-29 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aegis-Tests,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Weapons Tester Says Aegis System Adequately Tested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Aegis electronic system was adequately
tested before the Navy began buying the sophisticated ship defense,
the Pentagon chief weapons tester told Congress on Thursday.
   The report by John E. Krings disputed a study by the General
Accounting Office, which had raised questions about the adequacy of
tests of the Aegis system.
   ``The operational testing of Aegis has been adequate to support
the acquisition decisions that have been made and more testing will
be conducted to support future decisions,'' Krings, director of the
Pentagon's new operational test and evaluation program, told a
House subcommittee.
   It was an Aegis-class cruiser, the Vincennes, which shot down an
Iranian commercial airliner in the Persian Gulf on July 3 in the
mistaken belief that the plane was an Iranian military jet. All 290
persons aboard the jetliner were killed.
   Questions were raised in the wake of the incident about Aegis,
which the Navy has touted as the world's most sophisticated air
defense system.
   But a Navy investigation into the shootdown exonerated the Aegis
system, concluding that it worked as designed. The probe concluded
that human error led to the mistakes and said Navy officers on the
Vincennes misread data.
   Krings' office was created by Congress five years ago in the
wake of reports that weapons had performed poorly because they
hadn't been realistically tested before they were purchased by the
Pentagon.
   The Navy is relying heavily on the Aegis system to protect its
surface fleet, putting it aboard a new class of destroyers along
with the Aegis-class cruisers.
   The GAO criticized the Aegis tests, but that criticism was
contained as part of a larger GAO study which pointed out what the
congressional watchdog agency said were shortcomings in the
operation of Krings' office.
   The GAO said atmospheric ducting occurred in April 1984 during
Aegis testing. Ducting could have unfairly biased the reports of
some of the tests, according to GAO.
   Krings disputed the GAO's complaints about the testing of the
Aegis system.
   ``Ducting is a natural phenomenom prevalent in many areas of the
world, including the Mediterranean Sea and the Persian Gulf,'' he
told the Armed Services seapower subcommittee.
   ``The operational tester has no control over whether or not
ducting will be present during a test,'' he said. ``To run
operational tests with a stipulation that they not be run when
ducting occurs would be as unrealistic as a stipulation that tests
only be run when ducting is present.''
</TEXT>
