<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Deaver     09-29 0695</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaver,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deaver Prosecutor Offers To Hit College Talk Circuit for Pay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whitney North Seymour Jr., the independent
counsel who obtained former presidential aide Michael K. Deaver's
perjury conviction, is offering himself as a paid campus speaker on
government ethics.
   A letter that Seymour circulated to colleges and universities in
July _ before Deaver's sentencing this month _ was released by a
former Justice Department official who argued the independent
counsel was being hypocritical about government ethics.
   ``If he's so concerned about ethics, let him take his expenses
and speak for free,'' said Gary L. McDowell, a research fellow at
the National Legal Center for the Public Interest.
   McDowell, who had written speeches for then-Attorney General
Edwin Meese III, said he received the letter from a friend, whom he
would identify only as a college professor who had received the
solicitation before Deaver's sentencing.
   In the letter, Seymour wrote that ``following last December's
guilty verdict in the Michael Deaver case, I was asked to speak to
college and law school audiences about Washington ethics.''
   ``I hope to schedule more campus visits this coming year, and I
am writing to enlist your help.''
   ``As a result of my indoctrination in the ways of Washington as
independent counsel in the Deaver case, I have developed quite
strong views on how to achieve a higher standards of ethics in
government,'' Seymour wrote under the letterhead of his New York
law office.
   Seymour refused to comment about the letter to The Associated
Press.
   But in an interview published in Thursday's editions of The New
York Times, Seymour defended the speaking engagements, saying his
fee of $2,500 to $5,000 per appearance was ``way below market.''
   ``Look at it this way,'' Seymour told the Times. ``This is a way
to try to get a message out to the future leaders of this country
that they ought to be doing something about improving the level of
ethics in the nation's capital.''
   ``The ideal arrangement for visiting a campus is to be invited
to appear as a paid speaker at a scheduled student evening
program,'' wrote Seymour, who told the Times he had sent the letter
to ``several dozen'' colleges in July.
   Seymour's solicitation also was criticized as ``maladroit'' but
not unethical by Geoffrey Hazard, a Yale University professor who
specializes in legal ethics.
   ``It's just kind of tacky'' to solicit speaking engagements,
Hazard said. ``If it's fitting that he give speeches at colleges,
he ought to let them think of the idea.''
   Stephen Gillers, a legal ethics expert who teaches at New York
University Law School, said he would not have solicited the
speaking engagements before Deaver's sentencing to avoid any
misperception of impropriety.
   ``I have no problem with his decision to try to become a
spokesman on government ethics and to charge for it,'' Gillers said.
   The only issue is whether to wait until after Deaver is
sentenced to avoid any appearance of trying to cash in on the case,
Gillers said.
   ``In my view it was a question of judgment. Seymour could
reasonably have concluded that a July announcement would not
reasonably create an appearance of impropriety.''
   Seymour drew criticism last year when he delivered an emotional
attack on what he termed the low state of government ethics in
Washington.
   The speech was delivered on the steps of the U.S. Courthouse a
day after Deaver was convicted of three counts of lying to a grand
jury and a House subcommittee that investigated his lobbying
activities.
   Deaver, former deputy White House chief of staff and a longtime
friend of President Reagan, last week received a suspended
three-year sentence and a $100,000 fine. He also was ordered to
perform 1,500 hours of community service during the three years he
was placed on probation.
   Seymour had sough imprisonment for Deaver, saying such a
sentence would ``have a deterrent effect on the ethics and conduct
of political insiders.''
   In pronouncing sentence, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson rejected this argument, saying Deaver was not found guilty
of illegal lobbying.
   But the judge barred Deaver from lobbying the federal government
for profit for three years.
</TEXT>
