<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Japan-Blacks     09-29 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Japan-Blacks,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Groups Urge Christmas Shoppers To `Buy American,' Not
Japanese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. black organizations announced Thursday a
``Buy American'' drive for the Christmas shopping season in a
campaign against what they called ``Japanese insensitivity to black
Americans.''
   The Japanese have been reacting to U.S. black appeals against
such insensitivity ``in typical Asian fashion _ they have been very
polite, but nothing has happened,'' Rep. Mervyn Dymally, D-Calif.,
chairman of the congressional black caucus, told reporters.
   The campaign was formulated at a meeting of leading U.S. black
political, business and civil rights organizations earlier this
month.
   Part of the Japanese insensitivity is racial, Dymally said,
recalling critical remarks about U.S. blacks by former Prime
Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone and former Finance Minister Michio
Watanabe, for which they later apologized. Watanabe, who told a
party meeting last July that American blacks seem unconcerned about
declaring bankruptcy, may be Japan's next prime minister, the
congressman said.
   With Dymally at a news conference were representatives of the
National Urban League, the National Association for Advancement of
Colored People and the Black Business Council, three of more than
two dozen supporting organizations.
   Black Business Council Representative Kent Amos said the ``Buy
American'' effort called for the heaviest shopping season of the
year is not a boycott but an effort to divert part of American
blacks' $300 billion annual purchasing power to ``companies in
America responsive to our needs....''
   ``We as a black community have been through the process of
sensitizing insensitive communities before,'' Amos said. ``In the
1960s and 1970s, it was corporate America. ... We are much further
along in our understanding of our economic role now, and we won't
be as patient. We are willing to assist anyone willing to listen,
but not enough people are willing ... and until that happens we
will continue to have confrontation.''
   The campaign will include pressure to persuade Japanese-owned
businesses and factories now proliferating in the United States to
hire more blacks at all levels, Dymally said.
   American vice presidents of such firms are failing to convince
their Japanese bosses that ``this is America, and we have
affirmative action goals,'' he said. Japanese auto firms with the
exception of Toyota have no black-owned dealerships and Japanese
investors are giving no business to black real estate firms or
banks, he asserted.
   For new factories, ``every Japanese automobile manufacturer
seeks rural South America or suburban North America, as far as they
can get from urban centers where there is a surplus of labor and
where minorities live,'' Dymally charged.
   ``We want to be conciliatory,'' Dymally said, adding that the
first objective of the campaign is a dialogue between Japanese
government and corporate officials and the U.S. black community.
But Dymally said it has been difficult to engage the Japanese side
in dialogue.
   Racial insensitivity in Japan is being fought by ``some
enlightened people in the government and some corporations are
taking the right steps,'' Amos said.
   ``If all would follow the lead of Sony (electronics) and Toyota,
we would be much further along,'' he said, but did not clarify how
those firms could be spared potential loss caused by a ``Buy
American'' campaign.
   The Black Business Council seeks Japanese investment targeted at
revival of decaying U.S. inner cities and its president, Al Nellum,
will be pursuing this in Tokyo next week, Amos said.
</TEXT>
