<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0784 09-29 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0784,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Say U.N. Peacekeeping Jeopardized By Pakistan-Afghan
Problem</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with Soviets saying future peacekeeping
jeapardized by Pakistan's alleged violations of Afghan pact.
CHANGES byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the day U.N. peacekeepers won the Nobel
Peace Prize, a Soviet official on Thursday said failure to take
seriously Pakistan's alleged violations of the Afghan pact could
mean ``difficulties'' for future peacekeeping.
   Gennady Gerasimov, the spokesman of the Soviet Foreign Ministry,
said U.N. peacekeeping forces in Afghanistan are ``not doing their
job properly'' and should be investigated by the secretary-general
if future peacekeeping forces are to be approved.
   The Soviet Union, one of the five permanent members of the U.N.
Security Council, has the power to veto new U.N. peacekeeping
proposals. The other permanent members are United States, Britain,
France and China.
   The foreign ministers of the permanent members met Wednesday
evening at the request of Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A.
Shevardnadze to discuss Soviet claims that the United States and
Pakistan are violating the U.N.-mediated Afghan accords signed in
Geneva on April 14.
   Those accords call for the Soviets to withdraw more than 100,000
Red Army troops from Afghanistan, and for Afghanistan and Pakistan
to respect each other's territorial integrity.
   ``If we do not succeed in creating an efficient control
mechanism here in Afghanistan, which is kind of a testing ground,
then we will have difficulties in creating this kind of mechanism
in other conflicts,'' said Gerasimov.
   The ``mechanism'' he referred to is the U.N. military observer
group monitoring the Soviet withdrawal and alleged violations of
the accords.
   On Tuesday, Shevardnaze said the Soviets had finished the first
part of their troop withdrawal, but had not yet begun the second
phase, and said it depended on whether the violations of the accord
cease.
   When asked Thursday if the Soviets were slowing their retreat,
Gerasimov said: ``We don't want to be too specific, but we are
worried. ... These violations must be stopped.''
   U.N. observers determined that half the Soviet troops had
withdrawn by Aug. 15, so Shevardnadze's statement meant the Red
Army retreat has stopped for the last six weeks.
   The withdrawal began May 15 and is to be complete by next Feb.
15.
   Gerasimov said Pakistan armed the Afghan guerrillas and was
allowing at least two training camps to operate on its territory
for about 3,400 fighters.
   He said 2,500 Afghan fighters were in training near Islamabad,
the Pakistani capital, and 900 others at a base near the Afghan
border with the assistance of Chinese, American and Pakistani
advisers.
   The Soviet spokesman also accused Pakistani authorities of
patroling refugee camps to stop Afghans from returning to their
homeland.
   The spokesman called for a detailed report from the United
Nations, which has stationed observers in Afghanistan.
   At the U.N. session Wednesday night, Shultz said Soviet and
Afghan pilots violated Pakistani territory with bombing raids.
   Gerasimov acknowledged that a Soviet pilot was downed in
Pakistan a few weeks ago. He thanked the Pakistani government for
returning him.
   Otherwise, the Soviet official said, ``there is no intrusion,
and we are saying it all the time. It is really not true.''
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979 to back a
Marxist government. They stayed on to help the government fight a
Moslem insurgency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
