<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Temptation     09-29 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Temptation,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Last Temptation' Draws Protests, Tear Gas, Clashes With Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters used tear gas and stench bombs at movie
theaters in Paris and several provincial cities Wednesday to
disrupt the French debut of ``The Last Temptation of Christ.''
   About 600 protesters at a demonstration called by followers of
excommunicated Archbishop Marcel Lefebvre, a traditionalist Roman
Catholic, clashed with police in front of a Left Bank movie house
on the Boulevard St. Germain in Paris. One police officer was
reported injured.
   In Marseille, police said demonstrators were led by two
traditionalist priests carrying banners protesting the showing of
film director Martin Scorsese's adaptation of the novel by Nikos
Kazantzakis.
   Showings were disrupted in three cinemas in Marseille, one in
Angers, and one in Paris by tear gas and stench bombs set off by
the protesters. Customers were reimbursed for the price of the
tickets.
   Many other movie houses showed the film without incident, but in
Avignon four people rose shouting from their seats an hour into the
film, barged into the projection room and ripped up the theater's
copy of the film.
   In Rennes, Poitier and Laval, Roman Catholic groups protested
peacefully.
   Two other demonstrations against the film took place Wednesday
on the Right Bank of the Seine in Paris.
   Cardinal Jean-Marie Lustiger, the Roman Catholic archbishop of
Paris, issued a protest against the movie, but said he did not
support banning its showing and would not request or participate in
any public demonstrations.
   The Court of Appeals in Paris refused on Tuesday to order a
nationwide ban on showings of the film, which includes scenes in
which Jesus imagines being intimate with Mary Magdalene.
   The appeals court also overturned a lower court order last week
saying a disclaimer must be projected on the screen and read aloud
at every showing.
   However, the court did order that all advertising for the film
specify that it is not an adaptation of the biblical account, but
of the Kazantzakis novel.
   In Aix-en-Provence, municipal officials banned showing the film.
</TEXT>
