<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Phone,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AT&T Provides Public With A Link To Discovery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BASKING RIDGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   During the four-day manned space
flight of the shuttle Discovery, enthusiasts across the country can
listen to live space-to-ground communications via AT&T, a spokesman
said Thursday.
   The ``Dial-a-Shuttle'' service is sponsored by the National
Space Society, but the organization is using AT&T's DIAL-IT 900
Services to establish the earth-to-space link, said AT&T spokesman
Harry Baumgartner.
   At 7:59 a.m., two hours before the scheduled shuttle launch, the
service became available to callers who dialed 900-909-6272, said
Kip Tarpley, a spokesman for the society.
   Callers can hear live conversations between the five astronauts
and mission control in Houston, Tarpley said. During quiet time,
news updates, commentary, taped interviews and highlights of the
day's activities can be heard, he said.
   It costs $2 for the first minute and 45 cents for each
additional minute callers spend listening to the conversations,
Tarpley said. Money earned from the service will be spent on
space-related programs, he said.
   The service is scheduled to end about two hours after the
shuttle lands Monday at Edwards Air Force Base in California,
Tarpley said.
   K
