<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 2323EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CatholicSeminaries     09-29 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Catholic Seminaries,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vatican Blames Catholic Community for Seminaries' Student Shortage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican said Thursday that some of the 37
Roman Catholic seminaries in America are ``starved of students''
because they are not getting adequate support from the Catholic
community.
   A Vatican commission, after a seven-year investigation and
visits to the college-level seminaries, praised the quality of
education offered to prospective priests but said the institutions
``are not receiving the support which they both need and deserve''
from the Catholic population at large and from America's bishops.
Several American Catholic seminaries have closed in recent years.
   The commission especially deplored the tendency of dioceses to
send priesthood candidates to small, local schools, known as Houses
of Formation, which do not have as high academic standards as
traditional seminaries. Students at the Houses of Formation receive
theological training but must attend secular colleges for their
academic work.
   The practice submits students ``to a philosophical formation
which is inadequate to the needs of the priesthood,'' Cardinal
William Baum reported in a letter read and approved by Pope John
Paul II and sent to every Catholic bishop in the United States.
   Baum heads the Vatican Congregation for Catholic Education,
which was directed in 1981 to investigate the quality of education
offered candidates for the priesthood in America.
   ``We would urge all bishops who maintain Houses of Formation of
this kind to transfer their students to proper college seminaries
and to commit their resources, especially personnel, to these
seminaries,'' the cardinal said.
   ``Such slogans as small-is-beautiful, local-is-best are
disguising a situation in which college level candidates for the
priesthood are being deprived of the quality of priestly formation
which they merit and which the church needs,'' he added.
   ``The college seminaries survive because of the heroic sacrifice
and commitment of the bishops and religious orders who own and
operate them, but many dioceses do not send their priesthood
candidates to proper college seminaries with the result that good
as their formation programs may be many college seminaries are
being starved of students,'' Baum wrote.
   The commission also said that because of the dropoff in the
number of students, ``some seminaries are tempt to lower their
standards and admit students about whom they harbor reservations.''
   Generally, graduates of the seminaries attend theologates, for a
final level of training, before becoming priests.
   On another matter, Baum said seminaries must do job of teaching
future priests the ``theological rationale of celibacy ... based on
the example of Our Lord Himself.'' He said there was too much
emphasis currently on the mere discipline of celibacy without
attention to its theological basis.
   Baum's letter took note of the dropoff in the number of
priesthood candidate and listed reasons for it: ``pressures on the
family, the attraction of material prosperity and social comfort,
the sexual revolution and the growth of insecurity, as well as a
delay in the age of personal career decisions-making.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
