<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-SpaceStation 2ndLd-Writethru a0805 09-29 0651</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Space Station, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0805,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Allies Sign Agreement on Manned Space Station</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 4 grafs after 5th graf pvs, bgng: ``Margaret
Finarelli,'' to UPDATE with comments by Shultz, West German
official. Picks up 6th graf pvs, bgng: ``Twenty-two shuttle''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and 11 allied countries
signed an agreement Thursday to build a $23 billion permanently
manned space station designed to serve as a stepping-stone for
human exploration of the solar system.
   The facility, known as Space Station Freedom, will be designed,
developed, operated and used by all of the partners, which include
nine European allies, Japan and Canada, in addition to the United
States.
   The United States is providing $16 billion to the program and
the other partners are contributing more than $7 billion. The
agreement was formalized at a State Department signing ceremony at
which Secretary of State George P. Shultz presided. Officials said
it was a coincidence that the agreement was signed on the same day
that the Discovery space shuttle was launched at Cape Canaveral,
Fla.
   Richard Smith, a State Department scientist, told reporters the
project is ``clearly the world's largest ever international venture
and certainly one of the most complex.''
   Margaret Finarelli, an official of the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration, said the Europeans countries, all members of
the European Space Agency, will contribute $4.2 billion to the
project, Japan $2 billion and Canada $1 billion.
   At the signing ceremony, Shultz said the station will be used
``to test equipment and techniques for long space voyages and the
development of new materials of great benefit to mankind.
   ``For the United States, Space Station Freedom will be the
centerpience of our civil space program for the 1990s. It is an
essential next step if the United States is to stay on the cutting
edge of space exploration and research,'' Shultz said.
   Earlier, Heinz Riesenhuber, the West German chairman of the
European Space Agency, emphasized that the project will be used
only for peaceful purposes.
   ``Together we can reach for goals that are beyond the reach of
each one of us if he tries to go it alone,'' Riesenhuber said.
   Twenty-two shuttle flights over a period of three years will be
required to place in Earth orbit all the hardware for the station.
Construction will be completed in the first quarter of 1998
although the facility will be permanently inhabited from late 1996
on, according to current plans.
   A State Department summary of the program said a manned space
station is needed to lay the groundwork for a colony on the moon or
a manned mission to Mars.
   ``It will provide a focal point for free world space operations
well into the next century and will serve as a stepping-stone for
human exploration of the solar system,'' the summary said.
   The station will be used to study the effects of prolonged
weightlessness on humans and to create a life support system for
long space voyages.
   ``Because it is being designed to evolve and grow, this station
can become the facility which will serve as a point of assembly,
test and departure for future manned missions to the moon or to
Mars,'' the statement said.
   The project will comprise a combination of permanentlty manned,
man-tended and unmanned elements. According to the current
schedule, the facility will be ready for permanent habitation in
late 1996.
   The basic structure of the manned base, including the power
system and the habitation module, will be provided by the United
States. Canada will provide the hardware for use in station
assembly, maintenance and servicing.
   The United States, Japan and the European countries will
construct pressurized laboratories, allowing astronauts to do
research in a shirt sleeves environment.
   In addition to the United States, Canada and Japan, the other
participants are Belgium, Denmark, France, West Germany, Italy, the
Netherlands, Norway, Spain and Britain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
