<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Lithuania     09-29 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Lithuania,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lithuanian Activists Rally to Protest Police Beatings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Lithuanians rallied in their capital
Thursday to protest beatings by police who broke up two nationalist
demonstrations and arrested at least 100 people, a dissident said.
   Neither the official Tass news agency or Radio Moscow's
international service on Thursday mentioned the reported
disturbances on the main square of Vilnius.
   Valdas Analauskas, a correspondent with the dissident journal
Express-Chronicle, said a prosecutor refused to file charges
against those arrested during a demonstration Wednesday and an
overnight hunger strike on Gediminas Square.
   Most of those arrested were released Thursday, but a large crowd
gathered around the courthouse where the remaining 20 people were
to be tried in a closed court session, Analauskas reported.
Instead, the 20 were released.
   At least 5,000 people gathered on the square Thursday night,
carrying the flag of the independent Lithuanian republic and
banners reading ``Shame on the police,'' he said. A lunch-time
gathering also drew thousands, he reported.
   Nine Lithuanian activists declared a hunger strike Wednesday
night and remained on the square all night after police broke up a
protest earlier that day with armored personnel carriers and rubber
truncheons, Analauskas said.
   About 20 sympathizers had gathered around the hunger strikers,
and dozens of police waded into the crowd, beating, kicking and
pulling hair, Analauskas said. The demonstrators were forced into
two buses and driven away, he said.
   Analauskas estimated that up to 30 people were taken into
custody Thursday morning following earlier arrests.
   The initial protest Wednesday was against Soviet control of
Lithuania, one of three Baltic republics absorbed by the Soviet
Union in 1940. Lithuania, Latvia, and Estonia had been independent
countries from shortly after the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution until
1940.
   On Aug. 23, thousands of people gathered in the three republics
to protest the 1939 non-aggression pact between the Soviet Union
and Nazi Germany that divided Eastern Europe into spheres of
influence and led to the Soviet takeover of the Baltics.
   Baltic activists are seeking more economic and political
freedom. Some are demanding outright independence from the Soviet
Union.
   Analauskas said some protesters threw stones at police Wednesday
night.
</TEXT>
