<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Shuttle-Concord     09-29 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Concord,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christa's Hometown Relieved; Hoping To Leave Shuttle Spotlight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID TIRRELL-WYSOCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's re-entry to space on Thursday
prompted more sighs of relief than cheers in Christa McAuliffe's
hometown, where residents hope Discovery will help heal horrible
memories of the Challenger explosion.
   ``This puts (the bad memories of) Christa McAuliffe behind us,''
said Craig Sargent, 20, a former student of the Concord High School
teacher whose death on Challenger 32 months ago plunged the city
into grief that still lingers. ``I think she'd have wanted it this
way.''
   Sargent watched the launch at Sears on Main Street, where about
15 people gathered in front of a wall of television sets.
   ``I was standing here in the same spot when it blew up,'' he
said. ``It's about time they improved it. It looks like they're
doing things right this time.''
   Sargent said that as a student, he sat next to McAuliffe at
Concord High School the day before she left for Cape Canaveral.
   Fred McLaughlin, who listened to a radio broadcast of the
Discovery launch at Haggett's Bike Shop, said: ``It brought a lump
to my throat, especially when they talked about just getting past
the point of the explosion of the last one.''
   McLaughlin, who outfitted McAuliffe's family with bicycles, said
the Discovery blastoff ``brought back some sad memories.
   ``I don't think that being in Concord, New Hampshire, we'll ever
forget about the shuttle. Every time there's news about the
shuttle, there will be apprehension.''
   But he added that each successful launch ``will make the pain a
little less.''
   Betsey Rogers, who watched the Challenger explosion from the
grandstand at Cape Canaveral, said tears came to her eyes as she
watched Discovery on television at home.
   ``I didn't realize how emotional this would be,'' she said.
``It's really very exciting to see a success _ and such a big
relief.''
   Rogers was in Florida in 1986 as a chaperone for a third-grade
class from Concord, which included McAuliffe's son, Scott.
   She and others hope the successful Discovery launch will help
erase Challenger memories.
   ``The biggest thing that is going to help is that that
(Challenger) is in the past and now everyone is going to move into
the future,'' said Clint Cogswell, principal of the Kimball School,
which the two McAuliffe children attend. ``We'll just be left
alone, which is just the way it should be. We're no longer a
story.''
   Cogswell said no classes at his school watched the launch, and
that he and his staff still feel a duty to shield the McAuliffe
youngsters from shuttle exposure.
   He said both children were in school Thursday and school
officials kept reporters and photographers away.
   Police officers kept the media away from Concord High. There
were no assemblies, though two or three classes watched the launch
on television.
   A hand-made sign in a second-floor window proclaimed: ``Godspeed
Discovery Crew.''
</TEXT>
