<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BrushFires     09-29 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brush Fires,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Residents Flee Homes in Path of Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA METZLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RANCHO CUCAMONGA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wind-driven flames crackled
through 6,700 acres of brush Thursday and roared past homes
abandoned by residents facing Southern California's first major
blaze of the dreaded fall fire season.
   Desert-dry Santa Ana winds blasted through canyons of the San
Gabriel Mountains at up to 60 mph, pushing flames toward an
1,800-home section in the Etiwanda district, and by mid-morning the
fire reached a schoolyard.
   About 150 people fled with belongings they could carry, but by
noon the winds had dropped to less than 5 mph and 10 aircraft were
able to bombard trouble spots.
   ``No structures are now threatened,'' said Capt. Erny O'Keefe of
the California Department of Forestry. None of the $150,000 homes
was damaged when the fire swept by, ``just a few dilapidated
chicken coops,'' she said.
   The evacuation recommendation was withdrawn by midday.
   At dawn, hose-toting homeowners squirted water on rooftops while
others corraled their children, pets and personal possessions and
headed for evacuation centers. But many refused to leave.
   ``They want to be sure it is really coming,'' Rancho Cucamonga
City Manager Lauren Wasserman said.
   The fire moved within 100 yards of Summit Elementary School,
closed earlier because of the danger, forcing officials to relocate
a firefighter staging area set up there, Wasserman said. Flames
later roared past and spared the school.
   While air tankers and helicopters were grounded by the swirling
winds, 1,200 firefighters on the ground made desperate,
often-futile stands on ridge crests they had cleared of brush.
   ``It gets to the top of a ridge and the winds carry it so fast
we lose containment right there,'' said Mary Grisamore, a
spokeswoman for the Department of Forestry.
   The 6,000-acre-plus fire broke out Wednesday, when it burned
down a $445,000 ranch house and two outbuildings in the area 60
miles east of Los Angeles.
   Officials said it was 30 percent contained, but there was no
estimate on how long it would take to put it out.
   Temperatures soaring into the 100s accompanied the Santa Anas,
the ``devil winds'' spawned by high pressure over Nevada that sends
compression-heated wind whistling through the mountain canyons to
sea. They are often at their worst just as fall brings cool weather
and rain to much of the country.
   The winds also temporarily cost firefighters control of a blaze
they started Tuesday to clear overgrown brush. That 675-acre fire
was expected to be contained Thursday night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
