<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Shuttle-Satellite 2ndLd-Writethru a0812 09-29 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Satellite, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0812,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Discovery Deploys Communications Satellite</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs with satellite being deployed; Edits to
conform; Picks up 8th graf pvs ``About an...''
^By LAURA TOLLEY</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Within hours after Discovery
rocketed into orbit Thursday, the astronauts flung open its cargo
bay doors and deployed a $100 million communications satellite that
ground controllers will use to talk to crews on future missions.
   The Tracking and Data Relay Satellite, attached to a two-stage
solid booster rocket, was pushed from a tilt-table that was raised
out of the shuttle bay. The cargo waltzed away at about 2.7 mph
about six hours after Discovery's successful liftoff from Cape
Canaveral, Fla., at 11:37 a.m. EDT.
   About an hour later, the satellite was sent on its way toward
its final orbit with the firing of the rocket's first stage.
   But first, as a safety precaution, the astronauts maneuvered
Discovery 10 miles away and turned its belly toward the TDRS. That
was done to protect the shuttle's windows from particles flying
from the burning rocket propellant.
   Deploying the satellite was the main mission of the first
post-Challenger flight. Another TDRS is in orbit, but a nearly
identical one was destroyed in the Challenger explosion Jan. 28,
1986.
   NASA needs to get the TDRS in orbit because it will nearly
double the time ground controllers can monitor future shuttle
flights. The satellite now in orbit allows controllers to keep
track of shuttle about 45 percent of each orbit, but it has had
some minor breakdowns and is operating at about 98 percent
capacity, space agency officials said.
   The TDRS provides more continuous coverage of manned and
unmanned spacecraft orbiting the Earth than NASA's worldwide
network of ground-based communications tracking systems. The
satellite relays signals and data between a spacecraft and a ground
terminal at White Sands Missile Range, N.M., which then routes it
to the appropriate NASA facility.
   The satellite is thrust into its final orbit 22,300 miles above
Earth by an inertial upper stage rocket.
   A spring-loaded ejection device pushed the TDRS and the booster
from the cargo bay. The first stage of the rocket fired about an
hour after it the satellite was released from the shuttle.
   The second stage ignites about 5{ hours later and the satellite
reaches its final orbit about a half-hour after that. It then
undergoes several weeks of checks before it is considered
operational.
   The satellite and booster and its carrying cradle weigh about
45,000 pounds, making it the heaviest payload to be carried aboard
a shuttle, Johnson Space Center officials said. The satellite
itself weighs about 5,000 pounds and it has two 50-pound antennas
that look like giant umbrellas.
   The TDRS' final stationary orbit will be over the Pacific Ocean
near the Gilbert Islands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
