<HEAD>Shuttle Launch Had to Consider Other Orbiting Craft</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf to CORRECT to 11:37 (sted 11:47)</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the many satellites crowding
the orbital skies above the Earth threatened for a time Thursday to
affect the launch of space shuttle Discovery.
   When liftoff of the spacecraft was delayed, engineers in launch
control at Cape Canaveral announced that though the shuttle could
be launched as late 2:30 p.m. EDT, there were two brief periods
that were restricted because of satellites passing near Discovery's
flight path.
   Officials at the Johnson Space Center said they received a
Collision Avoidance warning from the Air Force Missile Command,
which keeps track of the hundreds of satellites in orbit.
   Flight Director Gary Coen said the warning had no effect on the
Discovery mission because the shuttle was launched at 11:37 a.m.
EDT, almost a half hour before the first of the two resticted times.
   Coen said the satellites that triggered the warnings were not
identifed by the Air Force.
