<1ST_LINE>u i AM-AngolaTalks     09-29 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola Talks,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angolan Talks Fizzle, But Namibian Independence Plan To Proceed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S-mediated peace talks between South
Africa and an Angolan-Cuban delegation, which began with high
expectations, ended without an agreement Thursday and a new round
will be scheduled, a communique said.
   It said the participants will recommend to U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar that plans proceed for
the independence of South-West Africa, or Namibia.
   Thursday was the 10th anniversary of U.N. Resolution 435, a
one-year transition plan for Namibia's independence.
   South Africa has said it will begin implementation of the
resolution on Nov. 1.
   Conference sources said a timetable for withdrawal from Angola
of an estimated 50,000 Cuban troops remained the big obstacle to an
agreement at the talks in Brazzaville, which began Monday. The
sources demanded anonymity.
   The communique released by all four parties _ the United States,
South Africa, Cuba and Angola _ said: ``The delegations have
expressed their firm intention to resolve the remaining problems
after consultations with their respective governments.''
   The sources said South Africa and Angola apparently accepted a
compromise proposal for a phased withdrawal over 24 months, but
Cuban diplomats demanded more time.
   Zaire government sources, who also spoke on condition of
anonymity, meanwhile disclosed that President Mobutu Sese Seko of
Zaire will meet Saturday with South African President P.W. Botha to
discuss a regional peace agreement.
   Botha and South African Prime Minister Roelof Botha, no
relation, were to fly to Mobutu's ancestral village in northern
Zaire near the Central African Republic frontier for the meeting.
   The sources said South Africa requested the meeting, which was
being billed as part of an African-led initiative to negotiate an
end to Angola's 13-year-old civil war.
   Government radio in Bangui, capital of the Central African
Republic, said a South African delegation led by Glenn Babb of the
Foreign Affairs Department met with President Andre Kolinga to
report on the Brazzaville talks.
   U.S. diplomats had hoped the Brazzaville talks would produce a
peace pact which would clear the way for Angola's Marxist
government to begin negotiations with its guerrilla opponents.
Civil war has wracked Angola since it gained independence from
Portugal in 1975.
   President Reagan told the United Nations on Monday that an
agreement resulting in a Cuban withdrawal from Angola was near.
Vice President George Bush cited Angola as an example of a foreign
policy success for the Reagan-Bush administration.
   South Africa has withdrawn its troops from Angola under a truce
negotiated during the present series of talks. It had demanded
withdrawal of Cuban troops within 12 months if it was to go ahead
with its stated aim of granting independence to Namibia, Angola's
southern neighbor.
   Angola and Cuban initially asked four years for the withdrawal.
   At U.N. headquarters in New York, Perez de Cuellar said a team
of 20 U.N. experts left Thursday for Namibia to survey that South
African-ruled territory prior to implementation of the U.N. plan
for independence.
   The Security Council met in formal session to adopt a statement
calling upon South Africa to free Namibia.
   The council noted ``the expressed readiness of the South-West
Africa People's Organization to sign and observe a cease-fire
agreement with South Africa.''
   SWAPO is a guerrilla organization fighting South African
administration of Namibia. South Africa's rule is in violation of
U.N. resolutions.
   Police in Windhoek, capital of South-West Africa, used whips and
batons Thursday to break up a demonstration outside the gates of
the territorial administrator, witnesses said.
   The protest was to commemorate the 10th anniversary of
Resolution 435.
   About 200 demonstrators marched from the main post office to the
administrator's hilltop residence. The noisy, but peaceful group
blocked traffic and police moved in with anti-riot vehicles and
charged the protesters. Some demonstrators and two journalists were
slightly injured, witnesses said. No arrests were reported.
</TEXT>
