<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-TWA     09-29 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-TWA,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TWA Labor Dispute Splits Members of Congressional Panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The battle between Trans World Airlines owner
Carl Icahn and the carrier's unions spilled into Congress on
Thursday, with lawmakers dueling over whether a House subcommittee
should scrutinize the dispute.
   The two sides in the fight over Icahn's financial restructuring
of TWA spelled out their arguments at a hearing by the House Public
Works investigations subcommittee.
   As the session began, Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Pa., said TWA's unions
had asked the subcommittee to hold the hearing. He said that Texaco
Inc. _ of which Icahn is the largest shareholder and whose
management he battled earlier this year in a proxy contest _ has
assisted the unions.
   Texaco spokesman Peter Maneri, speaking from the company's
offices in White Plains, N.Y., would say only that the firm ``takes
no role in these hearings beyond that of an observer.''
   Shuster said the unions had even sought unsuccessfully to have
the panel issue a subpoena to Icahn to force him to appear as a
witness. Icahn did not attend the hearing.
   ``I don't think it's proper people should try to use this
committee as a weapon in this kind of dispute,'' Shuster said.
   He and other Republicans said the hearing should not be
interpreted as supporting a Transportation Department investigation
of TWA.
   Democrats, however, said the internal changes being made at the
airline are worth examining.
   Subcommittee Chairman James L. Oberstar, D-Minn., said there are
``serious and legitimate questions surrounding the financial
maneuverings at TWA.'' He said it was appropriate for the panel to
study the carrier's finances, and the Transportation Department's
procedures for determining whether an airline's management is
qualified to operate the carrier.
   In August, the Independent Federation of Flight Attendants asked
the department to block Icahn's restructuring plan. The union
charged that the corporate raider simply wanted to extract cash
from TWA, ignoring needs for new equipment and threatening
thousands of jobs. The department investigation is continuing.
   Union leaders contended Thursday that Icahn acted for his own
benefit in initiating a plan to buy out public shareholders and
sell off assets, leaving the airline with $2.5 billion worth of
debt and an aging fleet of planes.
   Capt. Thomas Ashwood, chairman of the branch of the Air Line
Pilots Association that represents TWA's 3,200 pilots, said the
restructuring ``signals the beginning of a possibly irreversible
tailspin into bankruptcy.''
   But Mark Buckstein, a TWA senior vice president, said that since
gaining control of the airline in 1986, Icahn has turned around an
ailing company. He said Icahn has been exploring buying new planes,
setting up a domestic hub and adding new flights.
   ``TWA views this as but one step in its evolution as a more
effective competitive force in the airline industry,'' Buckstein
said.
</TEXT>
