<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RoachHunt     09-29 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Roach Hunt,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roach Raffle Offers Cash for Cucarachas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was billed as an effort to ``debug'' the
Lower East Side by getting people to turn in their cockroaches for
prizes Thursday. A sort of Roach Raffle. A Bug Bazaar.
   The big pesticide company that sponsored the Great Cockroach
Contest handed out free samples to make sure the little pests were
brought in dead. Banners were strung. Insect experts were assembled.
   The contest was sponsored by the Raid Center for Insect Control,
in cooperation with some Lower East Side community groups. The aim
wasn't to rid the entire Lower East Side of cockroaches _ just one
block of brick tenements on East 10th Street between Avenues B and
C.
   Raid handed out fumigants _ little canisters designed to flush
out and kill cockroaches _ along with tiny plastic, zip-locked body
bags for the deceased. A ``Countdown Headquarters'' was set up on a
vacant lot, complete with an insect zoo. And the contest officials
waited for the results.
   In the first couple of hours, about 10 people showed up,
gingerly holding their little bags in front of them. The roach
count varied, but generally ranged from about a dozen to 100.
   Each entrant was given a bucket filled with Raid products and a
T-shirt. And they were allowed to enter a raffle with a grand prize
that would range from $200 to $1,000, depending on how many roaches
were brought in by the end of the day.
   ``The main point we're trying to make is, you can't solve your
cockroach problem by just spraying once,'' said entomologist Keith
Kennedy. ``They've just been around too long, it's a sophisticated
insect and it requires some diligence to get rid of it.''
   Kennedy is a man who photographs bugs for a hobby and had no
qualms about letting an inch-and-a-half long Madagascar Hissing
Cockroach _ one of the prize specimens in the insect zoo _ crawl
around on his finger.
   ``That's a cockroach?'' a passerby asked, disbelieving.
   ``That's a cockroach,'' Kennedy replied proudly.
   ``Oh my God!'' gasped a woman, who sounded horrified.
   Kennedy rattled off cockroach facts. Sixty cockroaches weigh one
ounce. Eight-thousand weigh one pound. If a single cockroach gave
birth and all her offspring survived, she would have 10 million
descendants in one year's time.
   Near day's end, a flood of entrants appeared with cockroaches _
11,000 bugs in all. The grand prize _ $1,000 _ went to a man named
Mikal Reich.
   Eleven-thousand cockroaches is nothing to scoff at. Still, one
U.S. Department of Agriculture study in Florida turned up 27,000
cockroaches in a single apartment. At best, Kennedy said, the
contest may have exterminated half the roaches on the one block of
East 10th Street.
   ``We have been waging war against the cockroach for a long
time,'' he said. ``I will not suggest we are winning the war, but
we are winning more of the battles.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
