<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-France     09-29 0811</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-France,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mitterrand Agrees to Host Conference on Chemical Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French President Francois Mitterrand on
Thursday accepted President Reagan's suggestion that France host an
international conference aimed at improving enforcement of a ban on
the use of chemical weapons, a U.S. official said.
   Rozanne Ridgway, assistant secretary of state for Canadian and
European affairs, said Mitterrand had voiced a willingness to have
the conference in Paris, although she emphasized that no date has
been set for such a meeting.
   Mitterrand met with Reagan, and then the pair walked around the
Rose Garden for about 10 minutes before joining top-level aides for
a broad discussion of bilateral issues.
   He stopped by the Capitol, where he urged Americans to observe
the bicentennial of his nation's 1789 revolution, telling an
audience that the two nations ``always go side by side.''
   Mitterrand was joining Reagan for a private dinner Thursday
night in the White House residence before the French president was
to head home.
   During a picture-taking session with Reagan earlier in the Oval
Office, Mitterrand was asked why France had apparently reversed its
previous position of wanting to keep a stock of chemical weapons.
   ``We wanted to contribute to general agreement on the true
cessation of the chemical use,'' the president replied through an
interpreter. There are already conventions (agreements) but they
have not been respected. Therefore, a conference is needed to do
away with that.''
   Reagan, in his farewell speech to the U.N. General Assembly on
Monday, deplored the use of poison gas and chemical warfare, saying
the use of these weapons ``jeopardizes the moral and legal
strictures that have held these weapons in check since World War
I.''
   Reagan said the tragedy of chemical weapon use in the Iran-Iraq
war should ``spark reaffirmation of the (1925) Geneva protocol
outlawing the use of chemical weapons.'' And he called upon the 125
nations who signed the agreement ``to convene a conference to
consider actions that we can take together to reverse the serious
erosion of this treaty.''
   The conference that Mitterrand agreed to host in Paris would
deal only with the treaty protocol outlawing the use of chemical
weapons, and would not confront the question of production of these
weapons. This is being dealt with separately at the Conference on
Disarmament in Geneva.
   Ridgway said the United States believed France should be the
host country for a conference on banning the use of chemical
weapons since the original copies of the 1925 treaty protocol are
kept by the French government.
   She said Mitterrand quickly acceded to Reagan's request, but
that ``there was no discussion of a date.'' Ridgway also said she
did not know whether the conference, likely a one-day affair, would
take place before Reagan leaves office next Jan. 20.
   ``France, of course, has been a very active participant in the
negotiations on banning chemical weapons,'' she said, without
getting into the issue of the separate talks in Geneva on
prohibiting the production of these weapons.
   Ridgway said she did not know whether Reagan had talked with
Mitterrand about the Americans being held hostage by pro-Iranian
elements in Lebanon.
   At the Capitol, where he witnessed the signing of a joint
congressional resolution commemorating both the French revolution
and the proclamation, also in 1789, of the Declaration of the
Rights of Man, Mitterrand stressed the links between France and the
United States.
   ``We were at your side at the very beginning of your history,''
Mitterrand said, invoking France's decision to send military aid to
the United States during the revolutionary war against England.
   Congress approved the Bill of Rights in 1789, and the
congressional resolution signed Thursday states that the two acts
proclaimed ``the sanctity of human rights on both sides of the
Atlantic Ocean ... guaranteeing them for future generations.''
   The signing of the resolution by House Speaker Jim Wright of
Texas and Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., took
place in Statuary Hall, a historic chamber which was the meeting
place of the House in the early 1800's and which now is ringed by a
collection of statues of American heroes.
   Several speakers noted that the Marquis de Lafayette, a
prominent figure in both the American and French revolutions,
addressed the first joint meeting of Congress in the chamber in
1824.
   ``I know this historic chamber is filled with the statues of
famous Americans,'' Mitterrand remarked, peering out into the hall
from a podium draped in red cloth. ``I can't see them because of
the television lights _ but I know they are out there.''
   After the 30-minute ceremony, the president of France went to
see for himself.
   Ignoring attempts to whisk him out a side door, he broke away
from a group of dignitaries and circled the room, peering up at the
statues and shaking the hands of people nearby.
</TEXT>
