<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Friedland     09-29 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Friedland,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former State Senator Pleads Guilty to Racketeering</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: J Imbert cq in 4th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MELANIE BURNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former state senator who authorities said
faked his own drowning and hid out on a remote island pleaded
guilty Thursday in federal court to racketeering.
   David Friedland, 50, entered the plea before Chief U.S. District
Court Judge John F. Gerry just four days after testimony began in
his pension fund fraud trial.
   The former legislator from Jersey City had been charged with
masterminding a plot to defraud $20 million from the pension fund
of North Brunswick Teamsters Local 701.
   In return for the guilty plea, Assistant U.S. Attorney J Imbert
said the government has agreed to drop the remaining charges, which
include mail and wire fraud, against Friedland when he is sentenced
on Oct. 28.
   ``We arrived at an agreement that was suitable to the
government,'' said Imbert, adding that Friedland faces a maximum
sentence of 20 years in prison.
   The plea came during negotiations after Thursday's court session.
   ``Everybody got a fair shake,'' said Peter Willis, one of
Friedland's attorneys.
   Willis said he thinks his client will receive less than the
maximum prison sentence. ``I think he will have a life after
prison,'' he said.
   Federal authorities say Friedland staged a fake drowning in the
Bahamas on Labor Day 1985, just before he was indicted with three
co-defendants _ two union pension fund trustees and the fund's
lawyer.
   Friedland, a disbarred lawyer who had been convicted in 1980 of
taking kickbacks, was the subject of an extensive manhunt until he
was arrested Dec. 12 in the Maldive Islands in the Indian Ocean.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael Chertoff said he was satisfied
with the case's outcome. ``The court and the jury has been spared a
significant amount of time,'' he said.
   Chertoff said he was not entirely surprised by the guilty plea.
   ``In part, as he was confronted with what was unquestionable
evidence of his guilt, I think he was motivated by personal
embarrassment _ if nothing else _ to plead and put an end to the
proceedings,'' Chertoff said. ``A chapter is over in David
Friedland's life.''
   The three co-defendants were convicted in December of accepting
cash kickbacks from Friedland.
   Friedland and former Union County Assemblyman Joseph J. Higgins
were accused of defrauding $20 million from the Local 701 pension
fund through a bogus mortgage company they established in Florida,
according to the indictment. Higgins, already in prison for
racketeering, testified against Friedland.
</TEXT>
