<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-China-Soviet     09-29 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-China-Soviet,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Says Cambodia To Be Top Issue in Moscow Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA CASTANEDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Qian Qichen of China said
Thursday that Cambodia will be the main topic on the agenda when he
visits the Soviet Union later this year.
   ``Of course, we also intend to discuss other matters related to
our bilateral relations,'' Qian said at a luncheon sponsored by the
Foreign Policy Association.
   Qian's trip to Moscow, announced Wednesday, will be the first
working visit by a Chinese foreign minister to the Soviet Union in
more than 20 years. The exact date of the meeting has not been
announced.
   Qian and Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze met
Wednesday at the United Nations to discuss the Cambodia issue and
relations between the two countries.
   China maintains that the presence of Vietnamese troops in
Cambodia and of Soviet forces along the Chinese border and in
Afghanistan are major obstacles to normal relations with the Soviet
Union.
   Qian has asked that an international peacekeeping force
supervise the withdrawal of 140,000 Soviet-backed Vietnamese troops
in Cambodia and ensure free and fair elections.
   ``The four parties of Kampuchea (Cambodia) should reach an
agreement for national reconciliation and form a provisional
government under the leadership of (Cambodian) Prince Norodom
Sihanouk,'' Qian said.
   ``We hope to see Kampuchea become a neutral and non-aligned
country.''
   The four factions include the communist Khmer Rouge; Sihanouk's
followers; the non-communist Khmer People's National Liberation
Front of former Cambodian Prime Minister Son Sann; and the
Vietnamese-installed government of Heng Samrin in Phnom Penh.
   The Khmer Rouge under Pol Pot killed more than 1 million
Cambodians before it was ousted by the communist Vietnamese
invasions in late 1978. Vietnam, the Soviet Union and most other
nations want to guarantee that a Cambodian settlement prevents the
comeback of the Khmer Rouge.
</TEXT>
