<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KrohVerdict     09-29 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kroh Verdict,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Developer John Kroh Found Guilty of Bank Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former millionaire developer John A.
Kroh Jr. was found guilty Thursday of defrauding banks in an
attempt to get loans to keep his failing company afloat.
   A jury deliberated just over five hours before returning the
guilty verdict. Kroh, 47, looked stunned briefly but then remained
impassive.
   Kroh was found guilty of 13 counts of conspiracy, bank fraud,
wire fraud, receiving stolen money and forging his wife's name on
loan application papers.
   U.S. District Judge John Whipple said he would set a sentencing
date after a pre-sentence report was complete, probably within 30
days. Kroh could receive a maximum sentence of more than 80 years
in prison.
   No Kroh family members were present when the verdict was read,
including George P. Kroh, 50, who testified against his brother
under a plea bargain.
   George Kroh, a co-owner of the 77-year-old Kroh Brothers
Development Co., pleaded guilty in April to fraud and conspiracy
and served two months of a three-year sentence.
   The brothers' company collapsed in bankruptcy in February 1987.
   The government had charged that John Kroh falsified financial
statements to banks in order to obtain personal loans and then
funneled the money into his company.
   Much of the government's case was based on testimony by a former
company comptroller, Jacob Mondschein, who was granted immunity.
   Mondschein said John Kroh told him to do whatever necessary to
keep the company afloat. Kroh knew he was ``kiting'' checks between
at least four banks to cover mounting deficits and overdrafts,
Mondschein said.
   Kroh, who testified that he was never aware of the full extent
of his company's troubles, said he didn't know Mondschein was
kiting checks.
   George Kroh said he was unaware of the company's financial
problems until it was on the verge of bankruptcy and said his
brother handled that end of the business.
   Several bank officials testified they didn't question the
figures on the company's loan applications because of its solid
reputation in the area.
</TEXT>
