<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel     09-29 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands Raise Palestinian Flags At Former Mayor's Funeral</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of mourners waving Palestinian flags
and chanting ``PLO yes, Israel no!'' bore the body of former Gaza
City Mayor Rashad Shawwa to his grave Thursday.
   The army imposed a curfew on about 210,000 Palestinians in eight
Gaza Strip refugee camps and in Gaza City neighborhoods to prevent
riots during the funeral. Hundreds of Israeli soldiers stood guard
on rooftops along the central Omar El Mukhtar street in Gaza City
and watched the funeral procession without intervening.
   Shawwa, 79, an outspoken critic of the 21-year Israeli
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip, died of a heart attack
Tuesday. Shawwa was twice deposed as mayor by Israeli military
authorities but was considered a moderate by Israeli politicians.
   About 2,000 youths followed the coffin, carrying a large
outlawed Palestinian flag and chanting such slogans as ``We shall
die and Palestine will live!'' and ``God is great!,'' an Arab
reporter in Gaza said.
   At the entrance to the Amari Mosque, the largest in Gaza, youths
draped the coffin in a Palestinian flag. Five masked Arabs, waving
another flag, climbed to the roof of the mosque, cheered by the
crowd.
   At one point, dozens of youths started stoning Israeli soldiers
and reporters, but adults ordered them to stop.
   At Gaza's Maghazi refugee camp, two boys, ages 12 and 13, were
wounded in the legs during a clash with troops, hospital officials
said. The army confirmed the injuries.
   Another 12-year-old Palestinian was shot and wounded in the
stomach in a clash in the West Bank city of Nablus, Ittihad
Hospital officials said. A 23-year-old man was wounded in the leg
in the West Bank's Tulkarm, they said. The army said it was
checking the reports.
   Since the uprising against Israeli rule began Dec. 8 in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip, 278 Palestinians have been killed. Six
Israelis also have died. Israel took the territories from Jordan
and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
   On Israel radio Thursday, Chief of Staff Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron
defended the army's use of plastic bullets against Palestinian
demonstrators, saying it enabled soldiers ``to break up protests
with minimal casualties.''
   His comments followed sharp rebukes by the United States and
Britain and charges by United Nations officials that plastic
bullets caused casualties to soar.
   The army introduced plastic bullets last month to allow soldiers
to shoot at ringleaders while keeping out of the range of the
stones.
   Palestinian hospital officials in Gaza Strip said three
Palestinians were killed by plastic bullets on Tuesday. Israeli
army officials, speaking anonymously, confirmed the new weapon
caused at least two of the deaths.
   Hundreds of Palestinian prisoners rioted Wednesday at Ketziot
prison camp in Israel's Negev desert, hurling rocks at two lookout
posts and injuring an Israeli soldier, the daily Haaretz reported.
   It said the riot broke out after soldiers tried to handcuff a
prisoner caught outside his tent at night, allegedly without
permission.
   ``They (the prisoners) just raised their voices and fists. Then
they calmed down. Nobody was hurt,'' said an army spokesman,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
