<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0828 09-29 1050</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0828,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says Dukakis Took Same Social Security Position He Did</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Dukakis comment, SUB 3rd graf pvs, A Dukakis
... the list, with three grafs, picking up 4th pvs, Bush commented
... Democratic candidate.
^By TERENCE HUNT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNT CLEMENS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush accused
presidential rival Michael Dukakis of ``demagoguery'' Thursday,
saying the Democrat had criticized him for taking a Social Security
stance Dukakis himself had taken.
   Bush, who cast a tie-breaking Senate vote in 1985 to approve
legislation that included a one-year freeze on Social Security
cost-of-living adjustments, said that Dukakis, in a vote on a
National Governors Conference resolution, supported ``exactly the
same thing he was attacking me on the other night.''
   Dukakis acknowledged Thursday night that at a National Governors
Association meeting in 1985, he first voted to drop Social Security
from a list of programs to be covered by a proposed one-year freeze
in cost-of-living increases. Dukakis said he lent his support for
the overall freeze after the attempt to protect Social Security
increases was voted down.
   The Massachusetts governor said in Dallas that he cast the vote
``as a general expression of my concern for the deficit, but I made
it very, very clear that I was opposed to cutting cost-of-living
increases for Social Security recipients.''
   ``There were a great many of us (governors) who opposed any cut
in Social Security, but we at least wanted to give the
administration a message that we were concerned about the
deficit,'' he said.
   Bush commented in a news conference, his first in two weeks, and
also hit back at Dukakis on other recent criticism leveled by the
Democratic candidate:
   _Bush defended running mate Dan Quayle, suggesting it ``shows a
certain insecurity, a certain weakness'' for Dukakis to attack the
No. 2 man on the presidential ticket.
   _He also rejected Dukakis' reference to a ``Hall of Shame'' in
the Reagan-Bush administration of officials who have been convicted
of crimes or otherwise left office under a cloud. The vice
president said, ``How indelicate of him to mention such a subject.
... I could hardly believe it, but this from the same man that
attacked our president by that vicious, horrible analogy of a fish
rotting from the head down.''
   Dukakis said last summer that President Reagan and Bush must
both accept responsibility for the Pentagon procurement scandal and
other administration problems. He said, ``There's an old Greek
saying and I suspect the Italians have the same one. You know: `The
fish rots from the head first.' It starts from the top.''
   On Social Security, Bush denied he would ``raid'' the system as
Dukakis has suggested. And he said, ``I was a little surprised to
see this demagoguery from the man who had exactly the same position
that the president had on that one-year slipping of the COLAs.''
   Bush opened his campaign day by seizing the space shuttle launch
as a symbol for his campaign, telling a flag-waving crowd in St.
Charles, Mo., that ``We're back. America is back.''
   Bush later said he hoped he could attend next week's shuttle
landing in California, which would be a telegenic event for his
campaign.
   Asked if he would invite Dukakis to also be at the landing, Bush
said, ``That would be making a political event of it _ the two of
us there. I certainly have no plans to do that, gracious though it
may be.''
   Bush also put some distance between himself and the idea of a
quick manned mission to Mars _ a mission endorsed in the GOP
platform _ and a proposal for a ``Mission to Planet Earth''
orbiting observation platform.
   ``I would stop well short of saying the first thing I will do as
president is going to Mars. As a long-term goal and objective, it
is an outstanding goal and objective,'' he said.
   Dukakis has made Bush's running mate, Quayle, a prime target,
questioning his competence and his readiness to step into the
presidency if necessary.
   Bush, who rarely mentions Quayle in the campaign, said, ``I
think it's rather demeaning for their head of the ticket to keep
going after Dan Quayle. It shows a certain insecurity, a certain
weakness on his part.''
   Bush said Quayle ``will do just fine'' in his debate next
Wednesday with Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, Dukakis' running mate.
   Among the questions Bush was asked during his news conference
was whether homosexual couples should be allowed to adopt children,
to which he responded, ``No. I don't think they should.''
   He said a child should have a mother and a father, adding that
there was ``much more love in a situation like that, lasting love.''
   Dukakis has stated similar views and has been criticized by
homosexual-rights groups for a Massachusetts state policy favoring
married couples in granting adoptions.
   For the first time, Bush suggested in a speech that Dukakis
would follow the recommendations of the American Civil Liberties
Union in picking Supreme Court judges, if he is elected.
   Asked later to explain why he said that, Bush said merely, ``I
think it's a good question to ask. All he has to do is say no, they
won't have any influence on him.''
   Bush spoke to a crowd of nearly a thousand people in St.
Charles, which boasts it is the oldest city on the Missouri River,
and then flew to Michigan for a rally at Macomb County Community
College in Mount Clemens and another one in Grand Rapids.
   Bush hammered Dukakis with one-liners.
   ``This is the show-me state,'' he told the Missouri rally. ``My
opponent acts as if it's the snow-me state.'' He said that when
Dukakis ended their debate last Sunday, ``It was so thick I wanted
to borrow that 24-year-old snowblower that he has in his garage.''
   He criticized Dukakis anew for his plan to cut the budget
deficit by collecting delinquent and evaded taxes.
   Bush said Dukakis would have to double the number of IRS agents
and ``set 'em loose on the American people'' to collect those
taxes. Dukakis has said he would add 6 percent more agents each
year.
   ``I just don't agree with his vision of America where the
government has a hand in every pocket and a tax agent in every
home,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
