<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-29 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another Gray Day For The Nation's Midsection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms brought heavy rain to parts of the
Gulf Coast and Texas, and much of Mississippi and Alabama on
Thursday, while scatter showers prevailed over much of the nation's
midsection.
   Almost 3 inches of rain in six hours at Meridian Naval Air
Station, Miss. Two to 4 inches of rain fell in Waco, Texas,
although the area is still more than 7 inches below normal for the
year, the weather bureau said.
   Scattered showers ranged over the lower Ohio Valley, the middle
Mississippi Valley and the central plains. Overcast and fog hung
over the upper Mississippi Valley, western Iowa, much of Nebraska
and northwest Kansas.
   Showers and thunderstorms developed over southeast Georgia and
northeast Florida with cloudy skies over the mid-Atlantic coast and
partly cloudy elsewhere across the East Coast.
   Dry weather prevailed from the Rockies to the West Coast.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 45
degrees at Mullen, Neb., to 104 degrees at Norton Air Force Base,
California.
   The low in the nation was 5 degrees above zero at Gunnison, Colo.
   Friday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
southeast Michigan across the lower Ohio and Mississippi valleys to
Oklahoma and Texas.
   Showers and thunderstorms were expected to be most numerous over
southwest Missouri, Oklahoma and southwest Texas. Widely scattered
showers and thunderstorms were forecast for Florida and a few
showers in northern Maine.
   High temperatures were expected in the 70s and 80s across most
of the nation; in the 60s to 70 degrees from northern Michigan
across the upper Mississippi Valley and the central Great Plains to
most of Oklahoma, the Texas Panhandle and Colorado; in the 60s for
northern and eastern New England with some 50s over northern Maine;
in the 90s for central Florida and southwest Texas and up to 100
degrees for the desert Southwest and the interior valleys of
California and southwest Oregon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
