<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 2057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Shuttle-SpaceCold     09-29 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle-Space Cold,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Astronauts Swelter While Engineers Thaw Pipes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mission Control turned the heat on
the Discovery astronauts Thursday in an attempt to melt ice out of
a cabin air-conditioning system.
   The ice formed in ducts that feed an evaporator system used to
cool the cabin air while the space shuttle is rocketing into orbit.
   Another cooling system is used by the astronauts while they are
in orbit, but Mission Control set the cabin thermostat at a high
point in hopes of melting the ice out of the evaporator system.
   The temperatures climbed to 88 degrees, and the humidity
remained at a dry 43 percent. The astronauts were told to drink
water to avoid dehydration, but the crew members said the
sweltering temperatures presented no problems.
   ``We're not sure how much of an ice buildup we have,'' said
Lacey Veach, an astronaut who does the talking to Discovery from
Mission Control.
   ``We have the heaters on to help out with that problem,'' he
said. ``We're going to stay in that configuration overnight at
least and look at it again in the morning.''
   Veach asked the astronauts for their comments ``on the comfort
level in the cabin right now.''
   ``I think we're pretty comfortable right now, Lacey,'' said
Frederick Hauck, the Discovery commander.
   He said the crew had found that the two-story cabin of Discovery
had a cold room and a warm room, just as do many houses on Earth in
the winter.
   ``If we want to be a little warmer than normal, we come topside
(the flight deck) and if we want to be a little cooler, we go down
to the middeck. So far, we're in good shape.''
   If the crew follows the pattern of past shuttle crews, Hauck and
pilot Richard Covey will sleep in their couches in the warm part of
the cabin, and the rest of the crew will sleep in the larger and
cooler middeck area below.
   Among the crew equipment are sleeping bags to help keep protect
the astronauts from cold during their rest periods. But if it gets
too warm, the astronauts can change out of their flight coveralls
and work in shorts and knit shirts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
