<DOCNO> AP880929-0229 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 2137EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0736 09-29 0865</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0736,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Polluters ``Better Vote for Bush''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Mitterrand in 13th graf, He began...York
City, and SUBS 4 grafs for 16th pvs, From Newark...waste site, to
UPDATE with Social Security remarks, picking up 17th pvs, In
his...been completed.
^With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis sternly
denounced the Reagan administration's environmental record Thursday
and said toxic waste polluters ``better vote for Mr. Bush because
if I'm elected the game is over.''
   The Massachusetts governor defended his own record on pollution
in Boston Harbor _ an object of intense attack by Republican rival
George Bush _ and said in his cleanup efforts he'd had to fight
Bush and the administration ``every inch of the way.''
   Dukakis pledged an eight-year cleanup of toxic waste sites as he
accepted the endorsement of several environmental groups during an
appearance on the Rutgers University campus.
   He was accompanied by actor Robert Redford, who drew squeals and
cheers from the large outdoor crowd.
   ``Hello everybody, I'm Dan Quayle,'' joked Redford, whom Quayle
has been said to resemble.
   Redford, known for his outspokenness on environmental issues,
said Bush was ``co-captain'' of an administration that has
``consistently stalled or blocked efforts to clean up our
environment.''
   A crowd of students, kept to the side of the rally, chanted
``Bush'' and ``Boring'' as Dukakis spoke. Dukakis paused once and
said, ``We've got a certain amount of noise pollution over here.''
   Dukakis blamed the administration for environmental failures and
embarrassments, including the medical wastes that washed up on New
Jersey shores this summer, as he delivered a stinging assault on
Bush.
   ``For the foot-draggers and chronic polluters, I have just one
message,'' Dukakis said. ``You better vote for Mr. Bush, because if
I'm elected the game is over _ no more of the sweetheart deals and
delayed cleanups and half-baked compromises that we've seen over
the past seven and a half years.''
   ``If you're satisfied with oceans you can't swim in, air you
have trouble breathing and toxic waste dumps that threaten your
health, then vote for Mr. Bush,'' he said.
   Dukakis' barbs followed Bush's declaration in New Jersey several
weeks ago that ``I am an environmentalist.'' At the same time,
Dukakis ridiculed Quayle, Bush's running mate.
   ``Calling George Bush an environmentalist is like calling Dan
Quayle a statesman `because George Bush has been part of an
administration whose environmental policies are hazardous to our
health,'' Dukakis said.
   He began the day with a private meeting with French President
Francois Mitterrand in New York City.
   His trip by motorcade to New Brunswick was interrupted when the
limousine he was traveling in had a flat tire on the New Jersey
Turnpike.
   After a five-minute pause, Dukakis was moved to another vehicle
and the Cadillac limo, its right front tire in shreds, was left
behind.
   From New Jersey, Dukakis flew to Dallas for a fund-raiser and
private meeting with Hispanic leaders. At a news conference upon
his arrival, Dukakis explained his support of a National Governors
Association resolution in 1985 that included a one-year-freeze on
Social Security cost-of-living increases.
   The vice president, campaigning in Michigan, accused Dukakis of
``demagoguery'' for criticizing Bush for casting a tie-breaking
vote in 1985 in support of legislation imposing such a freeze.
   Dukakis said he wanted to protect Social Security from the
freeze on a number of programs. He said he cast the vote ``as a
general expression of my concern for the deficit, but I made it
very, very clear that I was opposed to cutting cost-of-living
increases for Social Security recipients.''
   ``There were a great many of us (governors) who opposed any cut
in Social Security, but we at least wanted to give the
administration a message that we were concerned about the
deficit,'' he said.
   In his speech Thursday, Dukakis blasted the administration,
saying cleanup efforts had been begun at only 137 toxic waste sites
of the 1,200 sites on the priority list under the Superfund law. He
said only 36 had been completed.
   He pledged that if he is elected cleanup would be completed or
``well under way'' at all the sites within eight years. He offered
no estimate of cost but promised to make polluters pay. Issues
adviser Victoria Rideout estimated a $13 billion cost to begin the
cleanup efforts.
   In a separate statement, the camapign said Bush, as head of an
administration Task Force on Regulatory Relief, led efforts to
weaken, suspend or kill environmental regulations.
   Dukakis defended his own actions as governor of Massachusetts in
regard to Boston Harbor.
   ``Today, my friends, we're cleaning it up,'' Dukakis said. ``In
the course of that cleanup, we've had to fight Mr. Bush and the
administration he belongs to every inch of he way.''
   He said the administration ``vetoed the clean water act twice
and cut the funding for our cleanup project'' and said the
Environmental Protection Agency ``took forever to approve our
cleanup plan.''
   Boston Harbor remains badly polluted and continues to have
barely treated sewage dumped in it. With Dukakis as governor,
Massachusetts officials filed for waivers to the federally mandated
cleanup of the harbor.
</TEXT>
