<DOCNO> AP880929-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 2210EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Rowan-Trial 2ndLd-Writethru a0827 09-29 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rowan-Trial, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0827,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rowan Trial Ends in Hung Jury; Judge Declares Mistrial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 8th graf bgng, `Rowan, 63,' to UPDATE
with comments from shooting victim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Thursday declared a mistrial in the
weapons-possesion case of syndicated columnist Carl T. Rowan after
the jury reported it was hopelessly deadlocked.
   Earlier in the day, Judge Arthur L. Burnett of District of
Columbia Superior Court had re-read his instructions to the jury
after the 12-member panel said it was unable to reach a verdict.
   Rowan has been charged with using an unregistered handgun and
ammunition to wound a teen-aged intruder in the back yard of his
home last June. He faced a maximum penalty of two years in prison
and a $2,000 fine if convicted.
   Burnett said he was convinced that further deliberations would
not lead to a verdict. The jury had deliberated about nine hours
over two days.
   One juror, who declined to be identified, told reporters the
panel had been in favor of acquittal by a 9-3 margin. A unanimous
verdict was required.
   As Burnett announced his decision, Rowan, who was seated at the
defense table, smiled at his attorneys and then at his wife Vivian.
He had no comment as he left the courtroom.
   Claude Bailey, a spokesman for city Corporation Counsel
Frederick Cooke, said city officials had not discussed what action
to take if the trial ended in a hung jury.
   Rowan, 63, shot 18-year-old Benjamin Smith in the wrist after
Smith and friends had taken an uninvited swim in his backyard pool
in the pre-dawn hours of June 14.
   Smith, interviewed by Washington television station WRC-TV in
Massachusetts, where he attends college, said Thursday, ``My mind
is pretty clear as to whether or not he had an unregistered weapon
because he shot me with it, and there's not a whole lot of
confusion about that....
   ``I'm not gonna go pool hopping again,'' he said when asked what
lessons he had learned from the incident. ``My feelings toward
handguns actually have been a lot stronger since this incident.''
   The defense built its case around a little-used legal principle
called ``entrapment by estoppel.'' The principle holds that a
person cannot be convicted if he is prosecuted for following advice
given him by a government official.
   Rowan had testified that his son, Carl Jr., a former FBI agent,
was repeatedly rebuffed by police officials when he tried to
register the .22 caliber revolver used in the shooting.
   The city's handgun ordinance allows only security officers to
register weapons, although exemptions commonly are made for law
enforcement officers.
   Rowan's son also testified that city police told him he was
exempt from the registration requirements because he was a law
enforcement officer, and that others in his family could have
access to the gun as well.
   ``He (Carl Jr.) was depending upon the competence and
intelligence of those people that the District of Columbia put
there (to advise citizens on gun registration),'' Raoul Carroll,
Rowan's attorney, argued during the trial. ``He was entirely at the
mercy of the District of Columbia.''
   One juror who declined to reveal his name said that ``wrong
information was given to Carl Rowan Jr. and Carl Rowan Sr.'' by
authorities.
   Rowan, who is black, testified that he obtained the weapon from
his son in 1982 after receiving a series of death threats from
people purporting to be members of the Ku Klux Klan.
   He said his fears were compounded by frequent intrusions by
teen-agers who held late-night pool parties, usually with alcohol
and drugs, in his yard.
   Prosecutors contended, however, that Rowan was not authorized to
handle a weapon not registered to him.
   ``We are here simply because the handgun is not registered,''
prosecutor Thomas C. Collier told the court. ``The death threats,
the shooting and the issue of trespassing have nothing to do with
this case.''
   Police officers who investigated the shooting testified that a
door at the rear of Rowan's home showed signs that someone had
tried to break in. One officer also said Smith had been shot at
close range just outside the home.
   Rowan maintained that he shot Smith because he was afraid the
intruder was trying to enter the house.
</TEXT>
