<1ST_LINE>s a BC-Crash-NewYork ADV02   09-29 0807</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Crash-New York, ADV 02,0830</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Oct. 2 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>NYC Makes Soft Landing After Wall Street Crash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite grim predictions, the city escaped
economic disaster following the 1987 stock market crash and made a
``relatively soft landing,'' officials and economic experts say.
   Though the financial sector was hit with layoffs and the city
responded with budgetary belt tightening in the form of a hiring
freeze and tax increases, worst-case scenarios never materialized.
   ``This was the year that everyone predicted would be a downer,''
said Samuel Ehrenhalt, regional commissioner of the federal Bureau
of Labor Statistics. ``But the city's economy did not go over the
cliff.''
   Paul Dickstein, director of the city's Office of Management and
Budget, agrees the crash did not bring on the economic disaster
predicted by some, but he said, ``We've paid for it ... and will
continue paying for it.''
   Dickstein cited the 6,000 jobs left vacant as a result of the
three-month hiring freeze and another 5,827 positions eliminated
under a subsequent reduction program aimed at saving $270 million.
   Officials were also forced to raise property taxes and to
eliminate an energy tax break for businesses. The object: to raise
$115 million to make up part of a projected $300 million in lost
tax and sales revenues.
   Though the city's economy remains ``basically healthy,''
Dickstein said, ``Things are going to be much tighter for the next
few years than it has been in some time.''
   ``We had been experiencing an unprecedented boom for a long
period of time'' because of the pre-crash bull market, Dickstein
said. ``We have to recognize that that's over and, therefore, city
expenditures have to be moderated.''
   ``After all, that was the most important industry in this
town,'' he said. ``Every town has one and ours was financial
services, and still is. You would expect then if your most
important industry is in the midst of shrinking _ jobs and revenue
_ that your tax revenues will decline with it.''
   For city residents, evidence of the crash of '87 will be seen in
the form of dirtier streets due to a smaller sanitation staff;
shorter library hours; more potholes; a police force whose ranks
are frozen.
   ``It's clear that New York City is in a very different
(economic) environment now,'' Ehrenhalt said. ``But on the whole,
if you consider the projections that had been made, this is a
relatively soft landing.''
   Ehrenhalt said one analyst predicted 70,000 jobs would be lost,
20,000 of them on Wall Street alone.
   In reality, unemployment in the city for the first half of 1988
was at a 19-year low of 4 percent, according to Ehrenhalt, and
there was a net decline of 12,000 jobs in the financial sector and
another 3,000 in banking.
   Those losses were offset by a gain of 16,000 jobs in the service
sector, which includes the legal profession, advertising, health
care and educational services.
   ``Normal growth for the city is about 1.8 percent to 2 percent.
So 1 percent after the crash is very good,'' said Rae Rosen, an
economist for the Federal Home Loan Bank of New York.
   Predictions that other industries would feel tremors after the
crash didn't prove true, either.
   The hotel and restaurant industry emerged virtually unscathed,
thanks largely to the devalued U.S. dollar, which has made New York
``a bargain hunter's paradise'' for foreigners, Ehrenhalt said.
   The construction industry ``has held up well, though it's not as
strong as it was last year,'' Ehrenhalt said.
   And the real estate industry survived predictions that property
values would plunge as panicked executives unloaded condominiums
and suburban estates.
   ``I think most people held off looking (at properties) in the
first few months to see what would happen,'' said Steven Spinola,
head of the New York Real Estate Board. ``We've now got a healthier
residential market than before.''
   The Corcoran Group, which specializes in luxury residential
sales, reported that the average price of a two-bedroom apartment
in Manhattan rose 3.25 percent in August to $489,400.
   Spinola said office vacancy rates, up about 13 percent, are
``higher than we'd like'' but even that market remains relatively
strong.
   Thomas Purcell, executive director of the Stamford Board of
Realtors in Connecticut, said big-ticket estates, those in the
$900,000 to $2 million range, may have stayed on the market longer
than usual, but overall ``sales are equally as good as they've been
in other years.''
   Though some complained the real estate market was soft, Ms.
Rosen said it was ``only in the sense that people are no longer
getting 20 percent gains in prices each year ... The gains are
closer to 5 percent, which is a more normal market.''
   ``It's been a surprising year,'' said Ehrenhalt.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sun Oct. 2</NOTE>
