<1ST_LINE>s w BC-ScotusTerm ADV02   09-29 1185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Scotus Term, ADV 02,1245</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 2, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Kennedy May Hold Decisive Vote as Supreme Court Opens New Term</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court begins its 1988-89 term
Monday with its newest justice, Anthony M. Kennedy, holding what
may be the decisive vote in major controversies over civil rights,
affirmative action, capital punishment and drug-testing.
   Many experts say Kennedy, beginning his first full term since
becoming a justice last February, could determine whether the
court's erratic 20-year drift toward conservatism will accelerate
dramatically.
   ``We're not sure where he lines up,'' said Thomas Krattenmaker,
dean of the Georgetown University Law School. ``It will be
interesting to see whether Kennedy takes the middle road or opts
for a more ideological route.''
   Over the next nine months, the court has agreed to rule on these
issues:
   _The death penalty for convicted murderers who committed their
crimes before reaching the age of 18.
   _The death penalty for mentally retarded killers.
   _The power of local governments to require that a certain
percentage of public works projects be awarded to minority-owned
construction businesses.
   _Mandatory drug testing for railroad employees involved in
serious accidents and for people seeking drug-enforcement jobs
within the U.S. Customs Service.
   _The continued vitality of a 1976 Supreme Court decision used to
fight private, or non-governmental, racial discrimination.
   The court could be deeply divided on each issue.
   An anticipated bellwether for Kennedy and the court is a North
Carolina case involving charges of on-the-job racial harassment.
The justices, with Kennedy on the side of the majority, voted 5-4
last April to use the case to reconsider a 1976 decision called
Runyon vs. McCrary.
   In the 1976 decision, the court said racially segregated private
schools violate a federal civil rights law when they refuse to
admit black students. The ruling let civil rights groups use that
law as a weapon in attacking other forms of private bias as well.
   Justice Harry A. Blackmun recently told a group of law students
in Arkansas, ``I think the outcome of the case will be of some
significance as to the movement of the court during the balance of
the 20th Century.''
   Marsha Levick, executive director of the National Organization
for Women's legal arm, said Kennedy's votes in the North Carolina
case and other pending civil rights disputes are key.
   ``Anthony Kennedy is absolutely someone to watch. He has not
been generous in his reading of civil rights laws'' as a federal
appeals court judge, she said.
   Blackmun, author of the high court's 1973 decision legalizing
abortion, told his Arkansas audience that Kennedy's views on the
issue _ as yet unknown _ could put the landmark Roe vs. Wade ruling
in jeopardy if a new abortion case wins the court's review.
   ``The next question is, `Will Roe vs. Wade go down the drain?' I
think there's a very distinct possibility it will _ this term,''
Blackmun said.
   Four court members _ Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and
Justices Byron R. White, Antonin Scalia and Sandra Day O'Connor _
have criticized the 1973 decision.
   In an apparent reference to Kennedy, Blackmun added, ``One never
knows what a new justice's attitude is (toward overturning past
decisions).''
   Krattenmaker warned against judging Kennedy by his initial
votes, noting that in his early years on the court Blackmun was
considered a staunch conservative but is now viewed as a leading
liberal on many issues.
   ``We may not learn anything this term (about Kennedy) that turns
out to be enduring,'' Krattenmaker said.
   Noting that Blackmun soon will be 80 and that the court's two
leading liberals, Justices William J. Brennan and Thurgood
Marshall, are in their 80s, Krattenmaker said, ``We must look for
signs or signals that one or more of the justices is considering
retirement.''
   The court's conservatives are much younger. Rehnquist is 63,
White 71, Scalia 52, O'Connor 58, and Kennedy 52.
   The court's ninth member, Justice John Paul Stevens, is 68.
   Here, in summary form, are some of the cases the Supreme Court
is expected to decide this term:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEATH PENALTY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Should capital punishment be banned for all murderers not yet
18 when they committed their crime? The court came close to
deciding the issue last June but its deliberations in an Oklahoma
case yielded no clear majority position. Kennedy did not
participate in that case but will take part in deciding similar
cases from Georgia and Missouri this term.
   _Should mentally retarded killers be executed for their crimes?
The court is studying the case of a Texas murderer who has the
mental capacity of a 7-year-old.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>AFFIRMATIVE ACTION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _May local governments require minority participation in public
works projects? The justices will resolve an attempt by Richmond,
Va., authorities to revive a so-called set-aside program that
required the prime contractor on any city building contract to
subcontract at least 30 percent of the project's value to firms
that are at least one-half minority owned.
   _May whites who claim they are the victims of ``reverse
discrimination'' challenge a court-approved plan between the
Birmingham, Ala., Fire Department and black firefighters to promote
more blacks?
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DRUG TESTING</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Is it an impermissible invasion of privacy rights to require
people seeking drug-enforcement jobs with the U.S. Customs Service
to undergo drug tests in which urine samples are taken?
   _May the nation's railroads require all employees involved in
serious accidents to undergo mandatory drug tests?
   Other drug-testing controversies, affecting many more people,
are waiting in the wings.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CRIMINAL LAW</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Is a new sentencing system for people convicted of federal
crimes valid? The validity of the U.S. Sentencing Commission that
fashioned those rules also is at issue _ and at stake are sentences
already meted out for tens of thousands of convicted criminals.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FREE SPEECH</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _May states use anti-racketeering laws to close down adult
bookstores accused of selling obscene materials even before those
materials are officially judged to be obscene? The court's ruling
in an Indiana case could affect anti-pornography efforts in other
states as well.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FAMILIES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _May states block a man from trying to prove he fathered the
child of a woman married to someone else? California, as do most
other states, gives a conclusive presumption of fatherhood to a
wife's husband and thus blocks others from claiming paternity.
   _May unwed fathers who actively seek custody of their children
be stripped of all parental rights if adoption is deemed to be in
the child's best interests? A case from California.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>LIABILITY OF PUBLIC OFFICIALS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _May public officials be sued for their alleged negligence in
permitting a child to be abused by a parent? The Wisconsin case
gives the court an opportunity to study the phenomenon of holding
public officials accountable for their failure to take certain
actions.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SEXUAL BIAS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _How difficult should it be for a woman to prove she was
illegally discriminated against because of her employer's
``unconscious stereotyping.'' The court will study the District of
Columbia case of a woman who says she was denied an accounting firm
partnership because her bosses believed she acted too aggressively
for a woman.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for AMs Sun Oct. 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
