<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has vetoed legislation
designed to toughen curbs on textile, apparel and shoe imports,
arguing it would have ``disastrous effects'' on the economy at a
time when exports are booming.
   After rejecting the textile measure Wednesday, Reagan signed a
bill paving the way for a multibillion-dollar free-trade zone with
Canada. In both cases, Reagan said he was acting to lower consumer
prices and protect jobs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warner Communication Inc. has vowed to fight a
state court ruling blocking its $1.2 billion acquisition of Lorimar
Telepictures Corp., and some analysts predicted the deal eventually
would succeed.
   Nevertheless, the analysts said Wednesday, court action could
delay the acquisition, which would create one of the biggest
entertainment companies in the industry.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president's chief economic adviser says a
slowdown in the second half of the year should ease inflationary
pressures and help reduce interest rates.
   Beryl Sprinkel, chairman of the president's Council of Economic
Advisers, said in a forecast Wednesday he expected overall economic
growth to drop below 3 percent in the second half of 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finance leaders of industrial nations have
questioned a Japanese plan for easing the Third World debt problem,
while poor countries renewed their appeals for more aid.
   The controversy over the Japanese plan emerged Wednesday at the
annual meeting of the International Monetary Fund and World Bank.
The plan calls for converting the debts of poor countries into
bonds, with interest payable into an escrow account managed by the
IMF, but some finance chiefs said the Japanese have not yet given
enough detailed information about how the plan would work.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reorganization of physician fees requested by
Congress could raise the pay of general practitioners by 70 percent
while cutting some surgeons' income in half, its author says.
   A summary of the plan by economist William C. Hsiao was
published in Thursday's issue of The New England Journal of
Medicine. Dr. William L. Roper, head of the federal agency that
runs Medicare, called Hsiao's study ``pioneering work'' in a
commentary accompanying the study.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private economists have reacted skeptically to
George Bush's proposal for new tax-deferred savings accounts for
the middle class, calling the tax savings inconsequential.
   Democrat Michael Dukakis already was using the proposal as
ammunition on Wednesday, contending that a Bush presidency would
favor the rich. The vice president's proposal, disclosed Tuesday,
would allow people to deposit up to $1,000 annually in a special
savings account and defer taxes on the interest if the money was
kept in the account for a minimum of five years.
</TEXT>
