<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 0418EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     09-29 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bullish American Petroleum Institute statistics
on domestic oil inventories have produced mixed results in the
futures market.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the November contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, settled 3 cents
lower at $14.11 a barrel Wednesday after trading between $14.06 and
$14.27 during the day.
   Other contract months closed lower.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for October delivery gained 0.58
cent to settle at 46.17 cents a gallon, while other contract months
closed mixed.
   October heating oil edged down 0.01 cent to 39.50 cents a
gallon, with other contract months declining.
   API statistics released after the close of trading Tuesday
showed that although gasoline inventories were up 2.2 million
barrels on a weekly basis to 219 million barrels, they 10 million
barrels below the same period a year earlier.
   Heating oil stocks were up 3 million barrels from a year
earlier, while crude oil was down 4 million barrels to 319 million
barrels, below the 337 million barrels of inventory last year,
according to API.
   Analysts said the lower crude statistics were considered
bullish, but the decline wasn't enough to offset concerns about the
oversupply of oil on world markets that has depressed prices
recently.
   Wednesday's gains, they said, stemmed from the combination of
lower gasoline stocks and API figures showing a drop in refinery
runs, down 550,000 barrels a day to 12.79 million barrels.
   ``When refinery runs go down then less gasoline will be coming
out,'' said Stephen Smith, research analyst with Bear, Stearns & Co.
   Brokers said some seasonal slowdown in refinery runs is expected
at the end of the summer, but the current drop was larger than
usual.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
