<DOCNO> AP880929-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 0246EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Warner-Lorimar Bjt   09-29 0573</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Warner-Lorimar, Bjt,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warner-Lorimar Merger Blocked by State Judge; Appeal Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warner Communication Inc.'s $1.2 billion
acquisition of Lorimar Telepictures Corp. eventually will be
completed even though a state court has blocked the planned merger,
analysts predict.
   New York Supreme Court Justice Walter Schackman granted an
injunction against the deal Tuesday, ruling it violated a 1984 pact
between Warner and its biggest shareholder, Chris-Craft Industries
Inc., a broadcasting and manufacturing company.
   Warner says it will appeal the ruling.
   At issue are Lorimar's televison stations. Chris-Craft claimed
in a suit filed in July that because Lorimar owned six stations,
the merger violated a 4-year-old pact prohibiting Warner from
owning any TV station so long as it owned 25 percent or more of
Chris-Craft's BHC Inc. broadcasting subsidiary.
   Warner acquired a 42.5 percent stake in BHC in 1984 in exchange
for Chris-Craft getting 23 percent of Warner's voting stock.
   In his 13-page decision Tuesday, Schackman said Warner could not
acquire any Lorimar stock until the TV stations were sold or it
reduced its stake in BHC.
   Since the Chris-Craft suit was filed, Lorimar completed the sale
of network-affiliated television stations in Odessa, Texas;
Springfield, Mo.; and Redding, Calif., to a partnership that
includes a former Lorimar executive. It also reached an agreement
in principle to sell a fourth station in Pittsburgh, but two
independent stations in Puerto Rico remain on the auction block.
   Some analysts familiar with the case predicted the dispute would
be settled before the appeal process was concluded, because the
only remaining issue was the sale of the two Puerto Rico stations.
   ``The stations have been on the market for over a year and a
half and they've yet to see a buyer,'' said Christopher P. Dixon,
an analyst with the investment firm Kidder Peabody & Co. ``I expect
to find a buyer ... they (Lorimar) will have to consider bids that
they were not willing to consider before.
   ``I expect the Lorimar deal to close, but obviously the time
frame has become extended.''
   The Warner-Lorimar deal was reached last spring. Warner said it
would pay $630 million in cash and stock for all the outstanding
shares of Lorimar and assume $550 million in debt, giving the deal
a total value of $1.18 billion.
   Lorimar, based in Culver City, Calif., produces several hit TV
shows, including ``Dallas,'' ``Knots Landing'' and ``Alf.'' It also
has a strong lineup of syndicated shows sold directly to individual
television stations.
   New York-based Warner's interests include movies, cable
television and magazine publishing.
   Warner stock rose 50 cents a share to $36 New York Stock
Exchange trading. Lorimar fell $1.50 a share to $12.50 on the
American Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Warner spokesman Geoffrey Holmes said the company actively is
looking for buyers for the Puerto Rican stations and would not sell
any shares of BHC. The company had maintained in court filings that
it would be hurt financially if it was forced to sell its BHC stake
at ``fire sale'' prices.
   Warner contends the proposed merger would not violate the
agreement with Chris-Craft because Warner planned to set up an
independent trust, pending approval from the Federal Communications
Commission, to run the remaining Lorimar TV stations.
   The Warner-Lorimar deal also needs approval from Lorimar
shareholders. A special meeting was scheduled for Oct. 3, although
a Lorimar spokeswoman declined to say whether Tuesday's court
decision would force a postponement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
