<DOCNO> AP880929-0247 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 0347EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-WorldBank-IMF Bjt   09-29 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-World Bank-IMF, Bjt,0693</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interest Rate Rise Seen as Threat to Third World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finance officials from 151 countries, wrapping up
the annual World Bank-International Monetary Fund meeting today,
heard some grim warnings about the threat of high interest rates on
the Third World, which already is reeling under a $1.2 trillion
debt.
   Industrialized nations see higher interest rates as a way to
curb inflation, and in the United States, to attract money from
abroad to finance the federal budget deficit.
   But higher rates also mean higher debt payments for Third World
countries.
   ``Every rise of one percentage point in interest rates costs the
debtors another $6 billion a year,'' said Stanley Fischer, vice
president and chief economist of the World Bank.
   Developing nations already pay more than $50 billion a year on
loans subject to variable interest rates, and complain that too
large a share of their earnings go to pay interest, leaving little
to improve living standards.
   In many of debtors, especially in sub-Saharan Africa, incomes
have been declining for 20 years.
   ``It would be highly undesirable if an excessive concern for
inflation were to bring about a spiral of interest rate rises,''
said Giuliano Amato, Italy's treasury minister.
   The World Bank is the chief source of aid for Third World
countries, lending about $17 billion annually.
   The IMF, which lends about $8 billion a year, originally was
concerned with keeping currency rates stable. Now both bodies
devote most of their efforts to helping arrange new loans for Third
World countries, in the hope that the money will be more wisely
invested and help debtors ``grow out'' of their troubles.
   Delegates to the meetings from rich and poor countries have been
searching for new ways to lighten the debt burden.
   Attention has concentrated on a proposal from Japan outlined
Tuesday by Satoshi Sumita, governor of the Bank of Japan. It would
turn some of the debt into bonds and sell them to the public,
delaying repayment by many years.
   The bonds would be backed by money paid into special accounts,
managed by the IMF. Repayment of the rest of the debt would be
stretched out.
   But many said Sumita's speech left many questions about the plan
unanswered, such as the advantages to the debtors or whether the
plan shift the risk for the original loans from creditor banks to
the banks' governments and their taxpayers.
   Another issue arising at the meeting was the future of the IMF's
monetary unit _ the ``special drawing right'' or SDR.
   The fund first issued SDRs in 1972 with the hope they eventually
would replace gold, the dollar and other currencies as the world's
major reserve asset. It was thought the international monetary
system could then be better managed, and no longer would depend so
much on gold mining in South Africa and the Soviet Union and on
U.S. domestic policy about the dollar.
   About $27 billion worth of SDRs have been issued, the last batch
in 1981, and the Reagan administration has resisted any further
issue. SDRs, now worth about $1.29 each, are traded only among
governments and some specially authorized banks.
   Sumita suggested expanding use of the SDR, and perhaps extending
it to private business. There should be more reserve currencies
``to complement the dollar's key role,'' he said. He also said
Japan was removing barriers to the use of the yen as an
international currency.
   Nicholas F. Brady, the new U.S. secretary of the Treasury, did
not comment publicly. Any discussion of reducing the international
role of the dollar could be politically explosive in a U.S.
election year.
   Others at the meeting have been skeptical about any bigger role
for the SDR, including West German Finance Minister Gerhard
Stoltenberg and Nigel Lawson, the British chancellor of the
exchequer.
   Lawson said nothing had come of the persistent effort to replace
the dollar with the SDR, and he believed it was unlikely anything
would.
   Stoltenberg said: ``We shouldn't attach too high expectations to
this.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
