<DOCNO> AP880929-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 0446EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-747Anniversary     09-29 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-747 Anniversary,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Twentieth Birthday Of 747s To Be Marked By Seattle Flyby</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first and latest versions of the Boeing 747
will fly side-by-side over Seattle on Friday to mark the 20th
birthday of the world's largest commercial jet.
   The Boeing 747s, each with the trademark hump on top of its
cockpit and front cabin, will fly over Elliott Bay and Mount
Rainier, weather permitting, to give Seattle residents another look
at the region's most famous product.
   ``Of all our planes, the 747's the most recognized worldwide,''
said David Jimenez, a Boeing spokesman.
   Since the first flight in 1969, the 12 different versions of
Boeing 747s produced in Everett have flown almost 850 million
passengers and about 12 billion miles worldwide.
   Boeing has received orders for 875 of the 747s since Pan
American World Airways ordered the first 25 in 1966.
   Industry analysts say the 747, with a price tag of about $125
million a plane, up from about $20 million for the originals,
brings the most cash to Boeing.
   On the surface, the earliest 747 and the brand new 747-400 model
making Friday's flyby look much the same. But company officials say
the two planes have more differences than similarities.
   The original 747 had a maximum takeoff weight of 710,000 pounds
and could carry 385 passengers about 4,000 nautical miles. The
747-400 has a maximum takeoff weight of 870,000 pounds and can
carry 412 passengers 7,300 nautical miles.
   Boeing expects the first 747-400 to be certified by the Federal
Aviation Administration by year-end and then sold to Northwest
Airlines.
   Boeing officials say they are confident the 747 will retain a
strong position worldwide, despite competition from McDonnell
Douglas' MD-11 in 1990 and from Airbus Industrie's A340.
   ``There's still a huge potential because of passenger growth and
for replacing older planes,'' said Phil Condit, executive vice
president of Boeing Commercial Airplanes.
   ``The 5 percent predicted growth in air traffic is a lot of
people, and as airports get more congested, airlines will want the
large 747s,'' Condit said.
   The 747-400 won't be the end of the line of 747s. Boeing
designers are considering shortening the jumbo jet to make it more
efficient, or stretching it to accomodate another 150 passengers.
   Malcolm Stamper, the Boeing vice chairman who oversaw the
building of the first 747, said Boeing's success comes from meeting
market demand.
   For example, the Boeing 747 design evolved when the company was
considering enlarging its popular 707. The 747 was conceived in
1965 because air-traffic growth required a larger, all-new plane,
said Joe Sutter, chief designer of the 747, who is now retired but
works as a consultant for Boeing.
   At the same time, Boeing was designing a supersonic transport,
and most industry officials thought the 747 would be used mainly as
a cargo plane and most passengers would choose the faster SST.
   The hump at the front of the 747 originally was intended to
facilitate loading large cargo containers.
   But when government funding for the SST was canceled, the 747
became the dominant long-haul carrier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
