<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 1011EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Yugoslavia-Economy     09-29 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Yugoslavia-Economy,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike-Triggering Austerity Program To Be Amended</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unpopular emergency economic
program, which has triggered a wave of strikes in Yugoslavia
because it allowed price hikes while limiting wages, will be
amended next week, newspapers reported Thursday.
   Changes in the program, that will include wage increases for
workers of those companies which are making profits, are scheduled
to be adopted in Yugoslavia's parliament on Oct. 3, the Borba
newspaper said.
   There have been numerous protest marches in Yugoslavia by
workers publicly airing their grievances after the government
introduced the austerity program last May, allowing substantial
price hikes and hefty wage cuts.
   The program lifted price controls for about 60 percent of goods
and services which had been under a price freeze since November
last year.
   The unpopular measures contributed to a further decline of
living standards, which have fallen by more than one-third since
1980. Labor unrest also increased.
   Yugoslav officials have repeatedly claimed that there is no
alternative to the market-oriented program, worked out together
with the International Monetary Fund, if the country wants to lower
its 200 percent inflation and repay its $21 billion foreign debt.
   Borba quoted Yugoslav officials as saying that negotiations are
in progress with the IMF in order to get the Fund's approval for
changing wage increase restrictions now in the economic program.
   The adoption of the program was a precondition set by the IMF
and other creditors for rescheduling of Yugoslavia's foreign debt
and obtaining new credits.
   During the first nine months of this year, salaries in
Yugoslavia have dropped by 10 percent in real terms compared with
the same period last year, and have reached the level of early
1970s, newspapers reported.
   Meanwhile, Belgrade shoppers were hit Thursday by a fresh wave
of price hikes, ranging from 300 to over 1,000 percent, the
Politika Ekspres daily reported.
   Of about 600 products, including food, drinks and cosmetics
whose prices went up in Belgrade shops Thursday, the highest
increase was recorded by a brand cheese _ 1,221 percent, said the
newspaper.
</TEXT>
