<HEAD>EEC Hails Reagan Veto Of Textile Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community on
Thursday hailed President Reagan's veto of a bill that would have
limited textile, apparel and shoe imports into the United States.
   Willy De Clercq, the EEC's External Relations Commissioner, said
the ``commission can only be satisfied with the decision by
President Reagan'' and urged the U.S. Congress not to override the
veto.
   ``This bill is very unsettling for international commerce and,
if it were adopted by Congress, would provoke grave consequences
for the trade in textiles,'' he said in a statement.
   He said enacting the bill also would endanger the success of
international trade talks within the General Agreement on Tariffs
and Trade.
