<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 1014EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Taiwan-Stock     09-29 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Taiwan-Stock,0610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angry Investors Demonstrate; Call For Stock Market Closure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 800 investors angered by plunging
share prices demonstrated outside the Finance Ministry Thursday to
demand the government postpone or withdraw its plan to reimpose a
stock profit tax.
   The investors, shouting ``Step Down (Finance Minister) Shirley
Kuo!'' were prevented by police from entering the ministry building.
   Some protesters called for closure of the stock market while the
government works out a more acceptable tax plan with investors.
   Earlier Thursday, stock brokerage firms were flooded with
selling orders that found few buyers when the market re-opened
after a four-day holiday for the mid-autumn festival.
   The stock index fell 175.96 points to close at 8,613.62 points
on what many traders called ``Black Thursday.''
   Of the 151 shares listed on the market, 114 posted the maximum 3
percent daily loss allowed by the government. Three shares recorded
gains and there was no transaction on the others.
   Turnover totaled 280 million Taiwan dollars ($9.6 million) down
from Saturday's 47.5 billion Taiwan dollars ($1.6 billion).
   On Saturday, the Finance Ministry said the government next year
would reimpose a tax on stock profits. The plan calls for investors
who sell stocks worth more than 3 million Taiwan dollars ($103,400)
in one year to include their stock income when filing their annual
personal income tax.
   Many protesters said they wanted the government to scrap the
tax, but others demanded lower tax rates or postponing
implementation of the tax plan by one year.
   ``We were caught up,'' said an investor, who identified herself
only as Ms. Wu. ``The government should not have waited till now to
announce the severe tax. It should have done this half a year ago
before prices soared up like this.''
   She said she purchased 10 million Taiwan dollars (about
$350,000) in stocks Saturday when the market index hit a record
high of 8,789.78 points, a 275 percent increase from last December.
   Lee Ching-tu, one of 10 protesters later allowed in the ministry
to state their cases, said the market should be closed temporarily
to prevent investors from ``dumping their shares amid
uncertainties.''
   The protesters were received by Finance Ministry official Wang
Cheng-yi, who agreed to pass their opinions to the authorities.
   Market analysts expect stock prices to continue to drop for
another two weeks before stabilizing. The government, they said,
imposed the tax to control rampant stock speculation that could
have resulted in severe losses for investors if the market had
crashed.
   Taiwan's stock market has been manipulated by major players
including underground investment firms that attract deposits by
offering as much as 4 percent monthly interest. Analysts say a
market crash could have forced those companies to close and result
in losses to numerous investors.
   John Chien, president of Federated International Securities
Consulting Company, said the tax measure ``was too drastic and came
too late.''
   Kuo said Tuesday the stock tax would not trigger a market crash
because Taiwan has a robust economy that can sustain a market
growth.
   Taiwan's economy grew 11 percent last year and is expected to
grow 7.3 percent this year.
   The stock income tax was lifted in 1976 when Taiwan's economy
slowed because of the world oil crisis.
   The Finance Ministry said investors who hold their purchased
shares for a year or more would have half of their shares waived
from taxes to encourage long-term investments.
   Workers who earn more than 3.5 million Taiwan dollars
   ($121,000) a year pay the top personal income tax of 50 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
