<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 1052EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Trade-IndustryReax     09-29 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade-Industry Reax,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Reagan-Trade</HEAD>
<HEAD>Industry Leaders Think Congress Can Override Textile Bill Veto</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Apparel industry leaders were undaunted after
President Reagan's veto of the textile imports bill, predicting
election-year politics would help supporters of the measure swing
enough votes for a congressional override.
   ``Politically, these are very hot times,'' predicted Howard
Cooley, president of Jockey International and president of the
American Apparel Manufacturers Association, which is holding its
annual meeting during a trade show in Atlanta this week.
   ``There will be an override effort,'' he said. ``We suspect that
there will be some votes changing,'' he said.
   The bill would limit import growth for apparel and textile
products to 1 percent a year beginning in January, freeze imports
of non-rubber footwear and impose quotas on 180 categories of
textile products and 30 types of footwear.
   The bill passed the Senate 59-36, four votes short of the needed
two-thirds to override; the House approved the bill 248-150, 17
votes shy.
   The battle to override will be close, ``but it's winnable,''
said Rep. Ed Jenkins, D-Ga., a supporter of the bill, which
President Reagan vetoed Wednesday.
   The main purpose of the legislation, Jenkins said, is to apply
pressure on Reagan to enforce existing textile import restrictions.
   ``Even if we do not override, we try to keep the pressure on the
president to make sure he enforces the existing agreements,''
Jenkins said.
   American Textile Manufacturers Institute President Daniel K.
Frierson, chairman of Dixie Yarns Inc., said, ``The veto shows a
callous disregard for millions of workers who jobs are being wiped
out by imports.
   ``We believe that the celebration by foreign interests and
giant, money-grubbing importers will be brief because Congress will
override the veto,'' Frierson said in a statement released in
Washington.
   Cooley said the import bill would have brought order to national
trade policy, which he said penalizes apparel and textile
manufacturers.
   ``We are the most labor-intensive industry and therefore are
much more subject to (competition from) the lesser developed
countries,'' Cooley told reporters during a news conference.
   Also predicting an override was Joseph M. Edalin, vice chairman
of underwear manufacturer Fruit of the Loom Inc.
   The bill was supported by both management and labor with
conservative Southern lawmakers, who represent textile-producing
areas, working with such labor unions as the International Ladies
Garment Workers Union and the Amalgamated Clothing and Textile
Workers Union.
   ``I'm very disappointed, but not totally surprised at Reagan's
decision,'' said James K. Tribble, a regional ACTWU director from
Chicago who was in Atlanta for the show.
   He predicted an override effort stood ``a fair-to-middlin'
chance of success.''
   Tribble also blamed imports for contributing to recent shakeups
in the industry which have seen some of the largest manufacturers
broken up or taken over in leveraged buyouts.
   Not all apparel executives support the bill.
   One opposed was Erle Norton, vice president of Atlanta-based
Oxford Industries Inc., one of the nation's 10 largest apparel
manufacturers.
   He said the measure would hurt companies such as his which use
some imported fabrics, or are involved in operations whereby cut
material is sent overseas for sewing, and then brought back into
the United States at reduced tariffs.
   ``Sometimes the cure can be worse than the disease,'' said David
Slossberg, vice president and general manager of Caleb V. Smith &
Son Inc., a Galion, Ohio, uniform manufacturer.
   ``If we get into a protectionist profile, somewhere else down
the line, somebody's going to get hurt,'' Slossberg said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880929-0261 </DOCNO>
