<1ST_LINE>s f BC-Crash-Studies-Glance Adv02   09-29 0887</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Crash-Studies-Glance, Adv 02,0935</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Oct. 2 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Important Studies of the Stock Market Crash, At-a-Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Crash-Studies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are brief sketches of key studies into the October 1987
stock market collapse:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Presidential Task Force</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   This panel, appointed by President Reagan and headed by
now-Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady, recommended that a supreme
regulatory authority such as the Federal Reserve oversee the
markets now governed by separate agencies.
   It also recommended adoption of ``circuit breakers,'' such as
price limits and trading halts, across all inter-related markets.
In addition, it suggested higher margin or down-payment
requirements for speculative trading in futures, and expedited
settlement procedures for stock trading.
   Furthermore, the panel said computerized trading tactics, which
a handful of large investors used to dump massive amounts of
stocks, contributed to the speed and intensity of the collapse.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>White House Working Group on Financial Markets</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   This panel, headed by the Undersecretary for Finance George D.
Gould, evaluated the conclusions of the Brady group, which weren't
well received in the administration partly because they advocated
more regulation. The Gould panel, composed of senior aides in the
Federal Reserve, Treasury Department, Securities and Exchange
Commission and Commodities Futures Trading Commission, rejected the
idea of a single regulatory authority.
   It further rejected suggestions that the SEC should regulate
stock-index futures trading, which is regulated by the CFTC,
although the panel endorsed raising margin requirements in futures.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>General Accounting Office</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   The investigative arm of Congress concluded that computerized
trading and the regulation of transactions should be overhauled to
avoid another crash.
   Since the nation's financial markets are increasingly
intertwined, federal agencies and market officials must monitor the
entire system, not just individual stock exchanges, and trading
officials must find ways to prevent plummeting prices in one
exchange from spilling into others, the GAO said. The GAO agreed
with the Brady panel that government should more effectively
supervise the markets, but it didn't endorse the idea of
designating the Federal Reserve for that job. It took no position
on ``circuit breakers.''
   The GAO is conducting a separate study, still in the early
stages, that will examine the evolution of clearance and settlement
procedures for securities and questions surrounding investor
protection.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Commodity Futures Trading Commission</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   The federal agency that oversees Chicago commodities markets,
where stock-index futures and options are traded, said it could
find no evidence that computerized trading strategies caused or
aggravated the market break.
   The commission blamed what it called ``unprecedented change'' in
investor psychology, and suggested the crash was the culmination of
a drop in stock prices that had begun months earlier.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Securities and Exchange Commission</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   The federal agency that oversees stock and bond markets said
computerized trading techniques did not cause the market plunge by
themselves, but ``had an indirect negative effect.'' The SEC said
``changes in investor perception, institutional stock selling and
program trading strategies combined to accelerate the market's
downward slide.''
   The agency opposed limits on price movements and did not call
for a new regulatory authority to oversee all financial markets, as
the Brady panel did. But the SEC suggested increased curbs on
stock-index futures.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>North American Securities Administrators Association</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   This group of state securities industry regulators concluded the
crash revealed widespread shoddy sales practices by brokers. It
urged tighter margin restrictions and disclosure requirements. The
group's study, the first to come out after the October break, was
based on complaints from investors.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Office of Technology Assessment</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   This research arm of Congress has been asked to study the role
that information technology is playing and will play in the
structure and operations of the financial markets. The study is
scheduled for completion in December 1989.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>New York Stock Exchange</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   The nation's biggest stock market largely blamed the crash on
the Chicago futures markets, calling them a haven for speculators.
The report recommended tighter restrictions on futures markets,
including higher margin requirements.
   The NYSE further recommended that the SEC regulate all financial
instruments, including stock-index futures.
   Despite external criticism that the NYSE specialists who make
markets in individual stocks failed to keep the market orderly
during the crash, the exchange said the specialists generally
performed well under crisis conditions.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Chicago Mercantile Exchange</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   The nation's largest futures market blamed the crash on waves of
selling that struck Wall Street and reverberated everywhere. It
said stock-index futures trading played no role in the crash.
Furthermore it found no need for changing the futures-trading
system. A study by the Chicago Board Options Exchange reached
similar conclusions.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>National Association of Securities Dealers</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   The group that monitors the nationwide computerized network of
over-the-counter trading did not study the causes of the crash but
said it ``clearly revealed vulnerabilities and deficiencies in all
markets.''
   The NASD undertook an extensive review of trading procedures and
tightened the rules for market makers in over-the-counter issues.
It endorsed stricter rules for selling borrowed stocks, known as
short sales, though the NASD said there was no evidence
short-selling was a problem during the crash.
   The NASD rejected the Brady panel's proposal for marketwide
``circuit breakers.'' But it endorsed the idea of a congressionally
supported study of the growth in new trading strategies and their
impact.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Oct. 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
