<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 1121EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-Crash-ProgramTrading Adv02   09-29 0698</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Crash-Program Trading, Adv 02,0723</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Oct. 2 and Thereafter.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Program Trading, Wall Street Bogeyman, Has Declined But Not
Disappeared</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Crash-Studies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The story of last October's stock market crash
featured one notorious villain: program trading.
   Singled out by some studies as an important ingredient in the
collapse and its volatile aftermath, the high-tech strategy became
a hate object for small-time investors and a target of lawmakers
and market officials.
   The flood of criticism and scrutiny pushed the technique into
the background, but program trading lives on here and is beginning
to spread overseas.
   ``Certainly if you're looking post-crash, program trading hasn't
played much of a role in market activity,'' said Jack Barbanel, a
futures expert at the New York investment firm Gruntal & Co. ``But
that's not to say that if Wall Street resumes momentum to the
upside, the major players would not come back.'' In its most common
form, program trading is a computerized version of arbitrage, the
centuries-old practice of buying something in one market while
simultaneously selling its equivalent in another market for a
higher price, pocketing the difference.
   Program traders use computers to buy stock-index futures in
Chicago and sell groups of the underlying stocks in New York, or
vice versa, to profit from price gaps in the two markets.
   Critics say program trading strategies can dump tens of millions
of shares of stock on exchange floors without warning, jerking
prices around and sending ordinary investors fleeing for safety.
   Supporters of program trading say its effect on the markets is
negligible. If anything, they say, program trading helps stabilize
the stock and futures markets by keeping the price spread between
them from widening.
   As a defense, they point to the NYSE's own statistics, which
show program trading accounted for only 8.1 percent of average
daily volume in August and 10.1 percent the month earlier.
   In months prior to the crash, when prices were rising to record
highs, program trading volume on the NYSE was the same percentage
or less, some studies have showed.
   ``As far as the hysteria, it's totally unjustified,'' said
Sanford Grossman, an economics professor at Princeton University
who has studied program trading. ``The impact of program trading is
infinitesimal.''
   The technique has its share of enemies nevertheless. In
Washington, program trading has received extraordinary review, and
some legislators have been devising ways of strictly regulating the
strategy because they believe it is destroying the market's health.
   The New York Stock Exchange, also worried about the impact of
such trading, has taken several steps to limit the technique and
now requires member firms to report all program trades, both for
themselves and their clients.
   In Chicago, meanwhile, down payments have been raised for
stock-index futures, a crucial component of program trading,
thereby making it more expensive and less profitable.
   Perhaps more important, investment firms that once committed
large amounts of money to program trading have been forced to
divert capital to other areas, partly because the crash erased much
of their profits.
   In addition, most big firms have stated as a public relations
gesture that they have curtailed program trading for their own
accounts, though they'll still do it for customers.
   The net result, investment strategists say, has been a
significant decline in the amount of program trading, although its
influence occasionally is felt.
   Many contend the post-crash restrictions on program trading and
misguided public hostility against it inevitably will drive
important sources of Wall Street business overseas. Some say this
already has started.
   The London market, for example, is now serving as a conduit for
some U.S.-based program trading.
   In Japan, which only recently began trading in stock-index
futures, some U.S. investment strategists say privately that they
are looking at ways to use program trading there.
   Asked at a recent NYSE briefing about post-crash reform whether
the nation's biggest securities market is worried about this
potential exodus, executive vice president Donald Solodar was vague.
   ``We recognize the possibility exists, but don't see clear
evidence it's happening,'' he said. Nevertheless, he added, ``it's
a threat we have to watch out for.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Oct. 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
