<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 1122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-Crash-CircuitBreakers Adv02   09-29 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Crash-Circuit Breakers, Adv 02,0466</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Oct. 2 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Highlights of Joint Reform Proposal by New York and Chicago
Markets</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Crash-Studies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are key elements of a post-crash reform proposal by the New
York Stock Exchange and Chicago Mercantile Exchange aimed at what
both markets called ``enhancing investor confidence in the
marketplace.''
   The joint plan was announced July 7 and submitted to the
Securities and Exchange Commission and Commodities Futures Trading
Commission for review. The NYSE has said it hopes for approval by
the anniversary of the Oct. 19 crash.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>`Shock Absorbers' and `Circuit Breakers'</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   Under a one-year pilot program, temporary trading halts would be
triggered by pre-designated price movements. Trading on the NYSE
would stop for an hour if the Dow Jones industrial average fell 250
points, and for two hours if the average fell an additional 150
points the same day. At the CME, trading would stop for an hour if
the Standard & Poor's 500 stock-index futures contract fell 30
points and for two hours if the S&P contract fell another 20 points
the same day. Both markets would coordinate the exact timing of the
halts.
   In addition, if the S&P contract fell 12 points, equivalent to a
approximately a 100-point fall in the Dow average, the futures
contract could not fall further for 30 minutes.
   At the NYSE, meanwhile, computerized program trading orders
would be diverted into a separate area to determine order
imbalances before they could be eligible for execution.
   The one-year experiment would supercede an NYSE restraint on
program trading triggered by a 50-point move in the Dow average.
The so-called ``collar'' has been in effect since February.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>`Front Running' By Professionals</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   Both markets agreed to develop a common policy on so-called
front-running, an abuse akin to insider trading, in which
professionals take profitable positions in one market based on
prior knowledge of an order executed in another market.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>NYSE `Express Lane' Order Routing for Individuals</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   The NYSE will institute what it called an ``Individual Investor
Express Delivery Service'' that will provide transmission priority
to individual investor orders when the Dow average is up or down 25
points from the previous session's close. To qualify, the orders
must be 2,000 shares or less.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Program Trading Data</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   In addition to the joint proposal, the NYSE began in July to
disseminate a monthly breakdown of program trading statistics
submitted by member firms. John Phelan, NYSE chairman and chief
executive officer, said disclosing this data would ``bring
discipline to the market and further reinforce our commitment to
less volatile markets.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Oct. 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880929-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 1123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-Crash-Global Adv02   09-29 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Crash-Global, Adv 02,0791</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Oct. 2 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Foreign Markets Show Mixed Progress in Post-Crash Recovery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market crash moved across time zones
like a stadium wave last October, but the recovery has proceeded
unevenly around the world.
   ``People are still quite nervous about stock markets,'' said
George Murnaghan, vice president at Rowe Price-Fleming
International in Baltimore.
   Nervous enough to slow trading in most countries, but not enough
to impede strong advances in some markets, particularly in Asia.
   George Mulvey, vice president for international research at
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., said volume has picked up recently on
many major exchanges and he views that as a sign that ``investors
are coming back to the market.''
   The world's 20 major stock markets were up about 9.5 percent in
late September compared with the end of October 1987, according to
an index developed by a research unit of Morgan Stanley & Co.
   The markets in Japan, France, Spain, Singapore-Malaysia and
Australia have posted double-digit gains in local currencies since
October, according to Morgan Stanley Capital International, while
the U.S. market was up 5.7 percent.
   The West German and British markets grew more slowly than the
U.S. market did, according to the index, while markets in Italy,
Norway and Switzerland posted small single-digit declines.
   The Japanese stock market, the world's largest, is up about 14
percent since the end of October, and several analysts said it was
the only major market to exceed its pre-crash highs.
   The Nikkei stock average, a measure roughly comparable to the
Dow Jones industrial average, surpassed its pre-crash high of
26,646.63 in April and has since risen an additional 3 percent.
   Japanese stocks have benefited from strong economic growth
trends, particularly in manufacturing, Shearson's Mulvey said. A
surge in corporate profits and consumer spending has also
contributed to the rise.
   But some analysts believe the market in Japan is ripe for a
fall. ``The market is so extended, at some point it has to be more
reasonably valued,'' said Murnaghan of Rowe Price.
   Mark Sladkus, a vice president at Morgan Stanley, said Japanese
stock prices are trading at about 50 times expected earnings, over
three times more than in the United States at the end of August. He
said the Japanese stock market has traditionally traded at big
multiples of earnings, but some analysts are wary about chances
that further price gains can be sustained.
   The markets in Singapore and Malaysia, up more than 29 percent,
have been spurred by strong regional growth trends, Shearson's
Mulvey said.
   Even the Hong Kong market, which closed for four days after the
crash, is up 14 percent.
   Rowe Price's Murnaghan said the Australian market, up nearly 25
percent, has benefited from the rise in commodity prices. The
market has a heavy concentration of commodity-based businesses.
   But not all of the high-performing foreign markets are in the
Pacific.
   The French market is up 19.8 percent and the market in Spain is
up 24.5 percent from October, according to the Morgan Stanley index.
   Murnaghan said takeover activity and strong economic
fundamentals have helped the French market, while Spain has drawn
strength from improving economic growth and progress toward
reducing inflation.
   Both markets have been helped by speculation about the impact of
the planned 1992 dismantling of many trade barriers within Europe,
he said.
   Nonetheless, the British and West German stock markets turned in
below-average performances since the crash, according to the Morgan
Stanley index.
   Murnaghan said the United Kingdom's market, up only 2.83 percent
since last October, has suffered from perceptions that the economy
was growing too fast, a worsening trade outlook, lower oil prices
and higher interest rates.
   West Germany's market was up 5 percent, but has suffered because
of slow growth, the high value of the West German mark and the
central bank's vigilance against inflation, Murnaghan said.
   The Italian market is off 1.75 percent since late October.
Mulvey said ongoing bank reforms there have hurt stock prices.
   One money manager, Jean-Marie Eveillard, who manages the Sogen
International Fund in New York, said institutional investors are
showing a greater willingness to invest internationally.
   ``As time goes by and the equity market gets better
psychologically, they are saying after all that maybe the crash was
an aberration, not a warning. I'm not in that camp, ... but that is
what some think.''
   Eveillard has about $15 million of the fund's $108 million
invested in foreign stocks, about the same ratio as in January.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Oct. 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
