<DOCNO> AP880929-0268 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 1125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-Crash-Tokyo Adv02   09-29 0958</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Crash-Tokyo, Adv 02,0985</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Oct. 2 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Uncertainty Persists In Tokyo Market Despite Outstanding
Performance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo stock market has outperformed most major
world markets since last October's crash, but opinion is divided
over whether that's a sign of strength or reason to worry.
   ``There are so many uncertainties underlying in today's Tokyo
market,'' said Jeff Bahrenburg, an analyst at Merrill Lynch's Tokyo
unit. ``Though it appears to be a bull market at a glance, we have
to be very cautious because any of those uncertainties could bring
down the market any time.''
   It only took a few months for shares on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
to regain what they lost in the crash. Last April, the Nikkei stock
average, a measure roughly comparable to the Dow Jones industrial
average, broke its pre-crash high of 26,646.63, and now stands some
4 percent above that level, while other major markets are still
struggling to recover their losses.
   ``The Black Monday was only a nightmare in Tokyo, and it was
much more than a nightmare in New York and London,'' said Tetsuhiro
Miyake, head of the research section of Nomura Securities Co.
   Analysts who have confidence in the Tokyo market say the
prosperity should continue. With a total value of more than $3
trillion, the Japanese market is the world's largest, accounting
for over 40 percent of the value of all shares traded in the world
today.
   ``Given the current economic growth rate of about 5 percent and
surging corporate earnings, the current share price level on the
Tokyo Stock Exchange is sustainable at least until the end of the
year or possibly longer,'' said Thomas Zengage, an analyst at
International Business Information, an investment and consulting
firm in Tokyo.
   Analysts like Zengage say Tokyo share prices are not as high as
they appear if you take into account differences in accounting and
cultural backgrounds between Japan and New York or London.
   Cautious analysts insist Tokyo's triple-digit price-to-earning
multiples indicate shares are at least four times overpriced
compared to New York or London, but defenders argue the ratios
doesn't reflect Japanese reality.
   Japanese corporations tend to understate their profits by 25 to
30 percent, said IBI's Zengage and other analysts.
   ``It is partially because of the steep corporate tax in Japan,''
Zengage said. ``But it is also a tradition here to understate their
earnings. It is simply one of those things Japanese have been doing
for years and taken for granted.''
   The corporate tax rate goes as high as 52 percent.
   Also, business relations in Japan are considered more valuable
than short-term profits. Corporations commonly hold each other's
stocks, not as an investment but as a testimony of their commitment
to each other.
   As a result of such crossholdings, the actual number of shares
in the market is low compared with the number issued. Analysts and
securities company officials say as much as 70 to 80 percent of all
shares issued on the Tokyo Stock Exchange are locked in corporate
safes for years.
   ``This will automatically inflate share prices because it makes
the supply and demand relation heavily in favor of demand,''
Zengage said.
   The skyrocketing value of land, another peculiarity of Japan,
also strengthens share prices of companies that have substantial
land holdings. In Tokyo's main commercial district, one acre of
land can cost as much as $1.6 billion, according to Land Agency
statistics.
   ``Look closely at bullish shares,'' said Miyake. ``You will find
most of them are attributable to the value of the land they own.''
   Other analysts counter that land prices have started to decline
this year and warn that this will not only reduce the value of
shares but also shrink the amount investors can borrow to buy
equities.
   ``It's a really delicate balance now,'' said Ronald Talmage,
real estate specialist at N.M Rothschild and Sons Ltd., the
British-based investment bank. ``I really think it's this big
bubble that could burst at any time with any imbalance from one of
many sectors.''
   Many foreign investors and fund managers complain of the lack of
transparency in the Tokyo market. Keisuke Matsuura, a veteran
investment consultant, said many stock prices are artificially set
by four major securities companies, Nomura, Daiwa, Nikko and
Yamaichi Securities, who have practical control over 90 percent of
shares on the exchange.
   ``In the Western standard, what they do here is a pure
manipulation of share prices, but in the Japanese rule book, they
are just traditional practices no one wonders about,'' said
Matsuura.
   Such traditions may be reaching a turning point as a series of
stock-related scandals has caused the Finance Ministry to tighten
the Securities and Exchange Law on insider trading.
   The increased presence of foreigners in the market also is
affecting investment patterns of the Japanese, who used to regard
foreign firms' market analyses as impenetrable as technical
computer manuals. But now such analyses draw more attention from
the newly emerging, performance-oriented private Japanese investor,
said David Gerstenhaber, a senior analyst at Morgan Stanley & Co.
in Tokyo.
   ``Japanese are beginning to rely less on brokers'
recommendations and make their own decisions. This may have a
significant impact on the Japanese investment patterns in the long
run,'' Gerstenhaber said.
   Despite concerns about overpriced shares and uncertainties
created by transitions under way, many Japanese contend the Tokyo
market can still provide a great investment opportunity.
   ``There is no doubt that shares on the Tokyo Stock Exchange are
overpriced, but so what?'' said Nomura's Miyake. ``They have always
been high for years, and they still have a potential for growth
more than New York or London. This is the fact of life.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Oct. 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
