<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 1126EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-Crash-London Adv02   09-29 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Crash-London, Adv 02,0748</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Oct. 2 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Slow Trading on the Other Side of the Atlantic</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The great crash of 1987 cast a giant shadow over
Britain's Big Bang.
   The collapse hit the British markets amid a wave of deregulation
_ nicknamed the Big Bang _ that promised to generate an
American-style boom in the securities business here.
   But after the crash, trading on the London Stock Exchange
dissolved to a trickle, and the atmosphere in the City, London's
financial district, turned from daring to cautious.
   The crash also triggered unexpected problems for Britain's
economy. And it could hamper Conservative Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher's huge privatization program.
   ``People have been and still are looking over their shoulders at
the dramatic impact it had and are still a little bit nervous that
there could be a sort of mini-repeat of it,'' said Geoffrey
Lederman, head of equities market making at the London investment
firm Smith New Court Ltd.
   Surprisingly, the government's opponents haven't been clamoring
for increased regulation to prevent another crash, and the
securities industry's system of self-regulation remains intact.
   During the past 12 months, the market has wandered aimlessly
with a tendency to react fitfully to the release of economic
reports, takeover speculation and signals from Wall Street.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index stands about
22 percent lower than its pre-crash level of 2,301.9.
   An average of 489 million domestic shares were traded daily in
August, down 41 percent from 825 million daily in August 1987.
   Investment firms have lost millions of dollars because of
reduced commissions, laid off an estimated 2,250 employees and cut
salaries and perks. There are some 28,000 securities industry
employees among the 273,000 workers in the City.
   It has been an especially rude awakening for firms that prepared
for Big Bang by diversifying and increasing staff at huge salaries.
   ``It was a sort of a Catch-22 situation. Before Big Bang one had
to get into the act and become a serious player,'' Lederman said.
``Now there are far too many players. There will have to be some
further reduction ....''
   In the months before the crash, the fierce competition already
was forcing a shakeout.
   Americans, more used to such competition, had been expected to
do particularly well in post-Big Bang London. U.S. banks, such as
Citibank, were eager to take advantage of a freedom not yet won in
their own country to engage in the securities business.
   But the U.S. companies found it ``like learning to sail in a
hurricane,'' one unidentified bank official said in a U.S.
government report on the subject.
   The impact of the crash on the British economy has confounded
experts who predicted a slowdown in consumer spending, which would
hobble economic growth.
   The British government, like others which feared a recession,
cut interest rates, and that increased spending. Economic growth
expanded to 4 percent, annual inflation rose to 5.7 percent by
August, and the country's trade deficit skyrocketed.
   ``The effect of that was to stimulate the U.K. economy when it
was growing already,'' said David Owen, an economist with the
London investment firm Kleinwort Grieveson Ltd.
   The government has reacted to this ``overheating'' by pushing up
base interest rates 4.5 percentage points since June to 12 percent,
and that worries investors and homeowners, alike.
   The Treasury insists the privatization program remains on
schedule and says the next sale, of British Steel Corp., will take
place at yearend. But many analysts believe Britons will now be
less keen to buy.
   The government has sold off billions of dollars' worth of
state-owned companies and the public has bought the shares eagerly
over the years.
   But the last sale, of the government's one-third stake in
British Petroleum Co. PLC, coincided with the crash, and flopped,
leaving most of $12 billion worth of stock in the underwriters'
hands.
   Looking ahead, the experts are divided about the overall
market's direction.
   Kevin Gardiner, a British economist at the London investment
firm Warburg Securities, predicted a significant rally within four
months, based on strong corporate profits.
   But Lederman said the market ``will jog gently downwards for the
next year or so. If the economic news does get worse, then again,
people will just not invest.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Oct. 2</NOTE>
