<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Slightly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most futures prices of grain and soybeans opened
slightly lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade, pressured by
selling linked to the advancing corn and soybean harvest.
   Harvest pressure remains the dominant force in the crop futures
market, overshadowing an increase in foreign demand for U.S. grain
and soybeans, analysts said.
   The Agriculture Department said late Wednesday that the Soviet
Union had purchased another 250,000 metric tons of U.S. corn, while
Mexico and Taiwan were awaiting word today on their bids for U.S.
soybeans.
   Wheat futures prices retreated on news that the USDA had
rejected Egypt's bid for 40,000 metric tons of subsidized U.S.
wheat under the Export Enhancement Program.
   Rejections of EEP wheat tenders have grown more frequent, and
rightly so, said grain specialist Ted Mao of Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc.
   ``Why keep promoting exports of a commodity that, if we have dry
weather again next year, we could have a shortage of?'' he said.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent to 1{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.15 a bushel; corn was
unchanged to } cent lower with December at $2.86{ a bushel; oats
were { cent to 1 cent lower with December at $2.45 a bushel;
soybeans were 4 cents lower to 5 cents higher with November at
$8.10 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were higher in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .20 cent lower to .02 cent higher with October
at 71.22 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .22 cent lower to .28
cent higher with September at 80.20 cents a pound; live hogs were
.17 cent to .55 cent higher with October at 39.22 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .13 cent to .33 cent higher with February
at 49.20 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures closed mixed on Wednesday while pork futures
ended lower.
</TEXT>
