<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0329</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rallied today, bidding to break
its recent stalemate.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 18.49 points to
2,104.02 by noontime on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by more than 2 to 1 in the overall
tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 830 up, 391
down and 531 unchanged.
   Analysts said there was nothing in the news to stir up much
buying interest.
   However, they said, it appeared some traders were nibbling at
stocks this morning simply because the market hasn't sold off
lately despite a long list of worries and uncertainties.
   Among those problems are the approaching first anniversary of
Black Monday on Oct. 19, which is presumed to be casting a pall
over the market.
   In addition, investors are said to be reluctant to commit
themselves before they can get a clearer idea of where government
economic policy is headed after the election of a new president.
   Nevertheless, brokers said money managers at some investing
institutions seemed interested in adding stocks to their portfolios
before they make reports to their clients for the third quarter,
which ends with Friday's session.
   Gainers in the blue-chip sector included Coca-Cola, up ~ at 44[;
International Business Machines, up { at 114]; Philip Morris, up ~
at 96~, and Union Carbide, up \ at 24.
   C3 Inc. jumped 2[ to 13\. Knoll Capital Management said it
proposed to acquire C3 for $13 a share, and might raise the offer
if the company provides it with information that warrants a higher
price.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.92 to 152.95. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .76 at 299.63.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 67.75 million shares at
noontime, up from 55.24 million at the same point Wednesday.
