<HEAD>London Shares End At Peaks</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing
index; No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices surged late in the session to end
stronger Thursday on the London Stock Exchange, boosted by a
healthy start on Wall Street and continued takeover speculation
affecting particular stocks.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended 16.5
points, or 0.9 percent, higher at 1,829.
   Volume was relatively strong as 562.2 million shares changed
hands, up from 418.3 million shares traded Wednesday. The increased
turnover led to market talk that a significant computer-generated
buying program had been carried out in the morning, but there was
no confirmation of this.
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average surged 18.85
points higher to 2,104.37 as London trading tapered off.
   Dealers said London shares were pulled higher by Wall Street's
confident movements. Several market watchers suggested that London
equities could advance still further if the New York market could
sustain the 2,100 level over the next few trading sessions.
   Dealers said the tone of the London market has felt positive
since Tuesday's release of better-than-expected British trade
figures for August. With a handful of leading stocks in the
100-share index still considered prime takeover bid candidates, the
market is unlikely to come under much selling pressure in the short
term, analysts said.
