<HEAD>Symbol Technologies To Buy MSI Data For $120 Million</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with Symbol Technologies being white knight in
deal, 90 percent share of scanner market, response from Telxon.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Symbol Technologies Inc., the dominant maker of
bar-code scanning equipment, has agreed to buy one of its major
customers in a white-knight deal announced by the companies
Thursday.
   The $23-a-share cash deal to buy MSI Data Corp. values MSI at
$120 million and saves the company from a hostile tender offer by
rival Telxon Corp., which had raised its offer on Wednesday to $20
a share.
   Symbol Technologies, of Bohemia, N.Y., has about 90 percent of
the portable laser scanner market, according to a recent report by
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   MSI Data and Telxon are the leaders in the hand-held data
computer industry, with a combined market share of at least 50
percent, Prudential-Bache said. At least half of the computers use
some form of laser scanner plugged into them.
   Telxon, based in Akron, Ohio, said Thursday it had no comment on
the definitive merger agreement between Symbol Technologies and
MSI, based in Costa Mesa, Calif.
   Symbol Technologies already owns 4.5 percent of MSI Data, the
companies said.
