<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Lower On Harvest Pressure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans posted
modest losses Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting
selling linked to the accelerating harvest and disappointment in
the lack of significant export business.
   Corn prices also were pressured by ideas that the government
will relax its corn planting restrictions in the 1989 price-support
program in a move to replenish supplies thinned by this summer's
drought, said Ted Mao, grain specialist in New York with Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc.
   ``Maybe people are reacting to the fact that they know the
set-aside program won't be as stringent next year,'' he said. ``The
government will try to put back some of the acreage that was taken
out this year.''
   The Midwestern corn and soybean harvest continued to dominate
the market, pushing prices lower on concerns about new supplies
coming to market.
   At the close, wheat was 3 cents to 5 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.13 a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 7} cents lower with December at $2.86{ a bushel; oats
were 3{ cents to 4 cents lower with December at $2.41{ a bushel;
soybeans were 4{ cents to 9 cents lower with November at $8.08 a
bushel.
