<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   09-29 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0527</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market put together a broad rally
Thursday, showing signs of life after the stalemate of the past few
weeks.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 33.78 to
2,119.31, its highest close since it stood at 2,119.13 on Aug. 5.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 5 to 2 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
1,065 up, 412 down and 478 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board stepped up to 155.79
million shares from 113.72 million in the previous session.
Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 181.29 million shares.
   Analysts said there was no single development in the news to
``explain'' the rally.
   However, they said, it appeared some traders were bidding for
stocks simply because the market hasn't sold off lately despite a
long list of worries and uncertainties.
   Among those problems are the approaching first anniversary of
Black Monday on Oct. 19, which is presumed to be casting a pall
over the market.
   In addition, investors are said to be reluctant to commit
themselves before they can get a clearer idea of where government
economic policy is headed after the election of a new president.
   Nevertheless, brokers said money managers at some investing
institutions seemed interested in adding stocks to their portfolios
before they make reports to their clients for the third quarter,
which ends with Friday's session.
   ``The market has been lifeless for so long. It started to move
up, and gave traders a sense of direction,'' said Hugh Johnson at
First Albany Corp. in Albany, N.Y.
   ``After that they jumped on board, with a little encouragement
from the bond market.''
   Though analysts acknowledged that the connection might seem
far-fetched, they also suggested that investors' spirits got a lift
from the successful launch of the space shuttle Discovery.
   Gainers in the blue-chip sector included Coca-Cola, up ~ at 44\;
International Business Machines, up 1{ at 115]; General Electric,
up { at 43}, and Philip Morris, up 1| at 97|.
   Fischbach Corp. jumped 7\ to 20[. A group of investors said it
was making a $25-a-share offer for the company.
   C3 Inc. gained 2 to 13[. Knoll Capital Management said it
proposed to acquire C3 for $13 a share, and might raise the offer
if the company provides it with information that warrants a higher
price.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $30.13 billion, or
1.13 percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained 1.75 to 153.78.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose 4.22 to 312.68, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was up 3.51 at 272.59.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market added
2.77 to 386.05. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 300.81, up 1.94.
</TEXT>
