<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Fed-Yamaichi     09-29 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fed-Yamaichi,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fed Names Yamaichi As Primary Dealer In Bonds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve Bank of New York handed a
victory to the Japanese securities industry Thursday by designating
a unit of Japan's Yamaichi Securities Co. as a primary dealer in
U.S. government securities.
   The decision was criticized as ``ill-timed and ill-advised'' by
Rep. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., the author of recent legislation
that calls on the New York Fed to deny primary-dealer status to
institutions whose home countries deny equal access to U.S.
companies.
   The Schumer provision was included in the trade bill recently
signed by President Reagan.
   Yamaichi International (America) Inc. is the seventh unit of a
Japanese securities firm and the 45th institution in all to be
given the highly prized status of primary dealer. The others
include four British firms and one each from Canada, Hong Kong and
Australia.
   Primary dealers have the exclusive right to deal directly with
the New York Fed when it buys and sells government securities as
part of its duties in controlling the nation's money supply.
   Largely in reaction to pressure from the United States, the
Japanese Finance Ministry earlier this month announced steps to
open its own primary market in government bonds to foreign
institutions.
   In a prepared statement, Schumer said that since the pressure on
Japan was working, it was too soon to let up on it. An aide, Tom
Friedman, said that under the legislation, if the Treasury
Department determines after a year that Japan is not giving equal
treatment to U.S. firms, it could require the New York Fed to
revoke Yamaichi's primary-dealer status.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
