<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FordFamily     09-29 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ford Family,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guardian Named For Grandchildren In Disputed $350 Million Ford
Trust</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lead expected with details from Cristina Ford alimony
hearing; time uncertain; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A snag in efforts to settle a
dispute over a $350 million trust left by auto magnate Henry Ford
II has been worked out with the appointment of a guardian to
represent his minor grandchildren.
   Attorneys for Kathleen DuRoss Ford, 48, widow of the Ford Motor
Co. heir, at first objected to another attorney's insistence of a
guardian, calling it a last-minute stall tactic.
   But they later agreed Tuesday to the appointment of retired Palm
Beach Circuit Judge Robert S. Hewitt, 71, as guardian of the four
minor grandchildren and any unborn grandchildren, residuary
beneficiaries of the trust.
   The minors will benefit after the death of Mrs. Ford, who is
entitled to receive a minimum of $1.5 million a year from the
trust, plus any income derived from investments.
   In another Ford family matter, a hearing was scheduled Wednesday
in Palm Beach County Circuit Court on a motion to dismiss Cristina
Ford's $5.4 million alimony claim. Ford divorced Cristina, his
second wife, in 1980, and she claims she has been cut off since his
death, not receiving any money from Ford's estate.
   Ford, who died Sept. 29, 1987, took control of Ford Motor Co. in
1945 from his grandfather, auto pioneer Henry Ford.
   Provisions of the confidential trust became public when Mrs.
Ford filed a lawsuit challenging the administration of the trust.
She and Ford's son, Edsel B. Ford II, had disagreed over whether
the trust should pay $1 million a year to William Donaldson, an old
friend of Henry Ford's and the third trustee, to manage the money.
   They also disagreed over which attorney would be counsel for the
trust and how the money should be invested.
   The trustees' 14 attorneys were in court Monday, ready to settle
the lawsuit and avoid the publicity a trial would generate.But the
agreement began to unravel when James Weber, attorney for Ford's
grandchildren, said a guardian was needed.
   Judge Vaughn Rudnick, who must approve any agreement, refused to
approve it without Weber's consent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880929-0297 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 1924EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Mellon     09-29 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mellon,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fed Approves Mellon's `Bad Bank' Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mellon Bank Corp. said Thursday the Federal
Reserve Board approved its plan to create a so-called bad bank,
Grant Street National, into which it can dump $1 billion in
troubled loans.
   Mellon said it expects the Comptroller of the Currency to
shortly approve Grant Street National's charter, allowing
Pennsylvania's largest bank holding company and the nation's
15th-largest to insulate itself from the loans.
   ``We are pleased by the Federal Reserve's action today,'' Mellon
Vice Chairman W. Keith Smith said in a prepared statement. ``It
represents important progress toward completing the
recapitalization and asset disposition program announced in late
July.''
   Grant Street National will not take deposits. It will exist
solely to liquidate the loans, which Mellon will sell to the new
entity for a deeply discounted $575 million. Common shares in Grant
Street National will be distributed as a special dividend to
Mellon's common shareholders.
   With the bad loans segregated, Mellon's financial standing will
be improved. Bank officials said it was the first time that the
``good bank, bad bank'' tactic had been used by a relatively
healthy bank.
   Grant Street National will issue high-risk, high-yield junk
bonds while using the wholly-owned subsidiary Collection Services
Corp. to collect as much as possible on the loans.
   Mellon said it lost $844 million in 1987 because of soured loans
in the energy-dependent Southwest and in developing countries in
South America.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
