<FILEID>AP-NR-09-29-88 1930EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CoalMiners     09-29 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coal Miners,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coal Miners Union Announces Plans To Expand Outside Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTHA BRYSON HODEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Mine Workers union, which
has represented the nation's coal miners since its formation in
1890, will expand its organizing efforts to workers outside the
coal industry, President Richard Trumka said Thursday.
   Trumka announced the plan as part of a new ``growth policy''
adopted during a meeting of the UMW's 24-member governing board,
held in Washington, D.C., on Tuesday. The plan calls for ``a new
direction in organizing,'' the union said, ``which will emphasize
recruiting in both coal and non-coal areas.''
   The plan will ``transform the UMWA into the largest and most
comprehensive energy union in North America,'' according to a news
release from the UMW. The union has watched its membership dwindle
over the past 50 years from some 500,000 in the 1940s to around
110,000 active members today, about 80,000 of whom are employed.
   Earlier this year, the UMW was rebuffed in an attempt to merge
with the Oil, Chemical and Atomic Workers union. The UMW's
international executive board approved the merger, but it was
rejected by the OCAW's eight-member governing body. Trumka said the
merger would have created the nation's largest energy union.
   ``Coal miners, and all working Americans, are facing a far
different economic climate than our parents and grandparents, and
it has been obvious for quite some time that our union must change
to better deal with the realities of the day,'' Trumka said
Thursday.
   UMW Vice President Cecil Roberts, who is in charge of the
union's organizing, said the UMW's ``new approach will be to
concentrate resources in those areas which contain the largest
number of non-union miners and the highest tonnage of non-UMWA
coal.''
   ``In addition, we will expand our activities in non-coal areas,
including _ but not limited to _ other energy industries and
related manufacturing,'' Roberts said. He said the union's
governing board also had created a new ``associate membership''
that will be open to workers in companies where organizing drives
are in progress, as well as UMW supporters.
   The ``growth policy'' also includes the establishment of
standing committees that will examine the possibility of
reaffiliating with the AFL-CIO or merging with other unions. In its
1986 convention, the UMW gave Trumka and the rest of the governing
board the authority to merge or affiliate with other organizations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
